<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Khmer Rouge leaders arrive in Phnom Penh, won't be tried
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associate Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders long
wanted for genocide arrived by military helicopter Tuesday at a
base outside the capital to meet Prime Minister Hun Sen, who has
ruled out putting them on trial.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, key members of the inner circle of
late Khmer Rouge chieftain Pol Pot, emerged from the thick jungles
of the Thai border area last weekend and cut a defection deal with
the government that amounted to surrender.
	   In exchange for officially ending their part in a decades-old
guerrilla war, Hun Sen has defied calls by the international
community and many Cambodians to put them on trial for their roles
in the deaths of as many as 2 million people under their rule from
1975 to 1979.
	   ``If we bring them to trial, it will not benefit the nation, it
will only mean a return to civil war,'' Hun Sen said Monday. ``We
should dig a hole and bury the past and look toward the future.''
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea have been sheltered during the past
several days in Pailin, an ex-rebel stronghold run by former
comrades who forged their own peace agreement with the government
in 1996.
	   Such deals broke the back of the Khmer Rouge's long civil war
after being overthrown by a Vietnamese invasion in 1979, but now
that the movement is almost extinct, many wonder when someone will
finally be held accountable for their murderous rule.
	   Under heavy guard, the pair and their families lifted off from
behind the Pailin police station for the two-hour flight to
Takhmau, a Phnom Penh suburb where Hun Sen lives on a military base
dubbed the ``Tiger's Lair.''
	   Leading members of the Cambodian People's Party _ led by those
who, like Hun Sen, were once Khmer Rouge cadres before fleeing
bloody purges _ were arriving Tuesday morning. Soldiers refused
many journalists access.
	   Khieu Samphan was the Khmer Rouge's nominal leader during the
group's existence, though it is debatable how much influence he
had.
	   Pol Pot and other top leaders jealously guarded their identities
and were rarely seen in public, preferring to send Khieu Samphan to
speak for them.
	   Nuon Chea was regarded as Pol Pot's second-in-command and chief
political theorist. There is extensive evidence of his role in mass
executions of party members the hierarchy suspected of treason.
	   The inner workings of the group remain a source of debate.
Former members of the inner circle who have defected tend to place
all blame on Pol Pot, who died in April of a heart attack.
	   Only one guerilla leader is left at large: Ta Mok, known as
``The Butcher,'' is somewhere near the Thai border with no more
than 100 die-hard loyalists. They pose no threat to the government.
	   Despite Hun Sen's statements that Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea
would not be tried, some human-rights activists were still holding
out hope that they would eventually face justice.
	   Youk Chhang, director of a center that gathers evidence of the
genocide, said Hun Sen may be playing a political game with his
pronouncements to lure the pair into custody.
	   ``The circumstances may have forced him to say something like
this,'' Youk Chhang said of Hun Sen's assurances of no trial. ``We
will have to wait and see what will be next.''
	   The United States and other countries should temper calls for a
trial and give Hun Sen time to maneuver, he said.
	   Government spokesman Khieu Kanharith said talk of a trial had
made the defectors afraid they would be arrested.
	   In Washington, the U.S. State Department noted Sunday that the
Cambodian government has repeatedly asked for _ and received _ help
in bringing top Khmer Rouge leaders to justice.
	   Hun Sen said he had support for an amnesty deal for the pair
from King Norodom Sihanouk and the leader of the National Assembly,
Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
	   The opposition Sam Rainsy party, however, said the men should be
arrested and tried for crimes against humanity. 	   
</TEXT>
