<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Yachting-Sydney-Hobart, 3rd Ld-Writethru,1058 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Search scaled back with five sailors dead, one missing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Fixes to `s' coding; DELETES reference to there not being list
of sailors in race in 8th graf. Organizers had list of sailors but
no nationality listing. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-111 &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY HARPER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A frantic rescue operation was scaled
back Tuesday after authorities hauled out the bodies of two sailors
killed in stormy waters during the deadliest Sydney-to-Hobart yacht
race on record.
	   Four bodies have been recovered. British sailor Glyn Charles,
33, was washed off the Sword of Orion yacht Sunday night and
declared drowned on Tuesday, becoming the fifth fatality, said
Australian Maritime Safety Authority spokesman Brian Hill. Race
officials said Charles had represented Britain in the Star Class at
the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta, where he finished 11th.
	   The two bodies found Tuesday were from the 56-year-old cutter
Winston Churchill and one of their colleagues was still missing.
	   Two other sailors were found dead Monday when the 40-foot
(12-meter) boat Business Post Naiad capsized 60 miles (95
kilometers) off the New South Wales town of Merimbula: the yacht's
owner-skipper Bruce Guy and crew member Phil Skeggs.
	   ``We have found two deceased people today and we're still
looking for the missing man, but it's becoming more and more
difficult,'' Hill told The Associated Press.
	   While 35 civilian and military aircraft and a similar number of
