<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Plane Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Site of fatal Thai crash vows to fix runway lights
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ An airport in southern Thailand where a
plane crash killed 101 people this month has said its runway lights
will be fixed by the new year, local papers reported on Tuesday.
	   Surat Thani Airport Director Chamnong Sarn-aksorn said workers
were speeding up repairs to the lighting system and all runway
lights should be working by the end of the week, The Nation
reported.
	   The cause of the crash of Thai Airways flight TG261, which
smashed into a swamp amid a night rain storm on December 11, is
under investigation by a government committee.
	   Some of the 45 survivors have blamed the pilot for attempting a
third landing in bad weather after failing the first two times. The
pilot also died.
	   But questions have also arisen about the safety of the airport
in Surat Thani, 530 kilometers (330 miles) southwest of Bangkok.
	   Airport officials have admitted they removed the instrument
landing system, which helps pilots land during bad weather, during
a runway renovation several months earlier.
	   Also, they have said half the runway lights were not working
because of problems with the electrical system that hadn't yet been
fixed.
	   The pilot had complained he could not see the runway during his
failed attempts to land. 	   
</TEXT>
