w2850 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-NewZea 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India has New Zealand facing defeat in the second test
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES at stumps
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ India rallied around a brilliant
century by Sachin Tendulkar to have New Zealand staring at defeat
in the second cricket test at the Basin Reserve Tuesday.
	   New Zealand, chasing 213 to win, was 73 for four at stumps on
the fourth day with Craig McMillan on 17 and Paul Wiseman yet to
score.
	   After Tendulkar's 113 had inspired India to a second innings
356, leg-spinner Anil Kumble triggered a New Zealand slide with the
important wickets of Stephen Fleming and opener Matthew Fleming in
a three-over spell.
	   New Zealand's hopes took another body blow when the inform
Nathan Astle suffered a broken bone in his left hand off paceman
Javagal Srinath.
	   Astle, who hit 56 in the first innings, will bat if required but
a New Zealand Cricket spokeswoman said he would likely be sidelined
for 3-4 weeks.
	   Kumble followed up his invaluable contribution with the bat _ 23
runs in a 42-run stand with Srinath _ by finishing the day with
2-19 in 11 overs.
	   After losing debutant opener Matthew Bell to a third ball duck,
Horne and Fleming took New Zealand to 42 when Kumble struck in his
fourth over.
	   Fleming (17) let go a delivery, but the ball spun sharply off
the bowlers' foot-holes and hit the left hander's off stump.
	   Horne batted 88 minutes for 31 before he was trapped leg before
wicket by a Kumble ``flipper'' that hurried on him.
	   The last time New Zealand successfully chased over 200 runs was
against Pakistan in Christchurch in 1993-94 when it made 324 for
the loss of five wickets.
	   The highest fourth innings total chased at the Basin Reserve was
181 by New Zealand against Australia in March 1990.
	   India's hopes of setting a big fourth innings target disappeared
with the dismissal of Tendulkar, who hit his 17th test century and
his first against New Zealand.
	   Dion Nash, whose unbeaten 89 inspired New Zealand to a handy
144-run lead, triggered a middle order collapse after lunch and
India never recovered.
	   Nash, surprisingly held back from the bowling crease for 64
overs as India moved ominously to 297 for four, struck with his
first ball of the day, claiming the prized scalp of Tendulkar.
	   Tendulkar having reached his century with a six for the third
time in a 63-match career, drove loosely at Nash to give first slip
Fleming a simple catch.
	   India lost 3-7 in 21 balls including Mohammed Azharuddin for 48
runs. The Indian skipper showed his displeasure after West Indies
umpire Eddie Nicholls adjudged him caught behind to give Nash 2-3
in 12 balls.
	   New Zealand coach Steve Rixon admitted India must be favored to
take a 1-0 lead in the series.
	   ``It has been a game which no team has managed to dominate,''
Rixon said. ``For once it is leaning slightly in India's favor.
Kumble is the threat tomorrow and if we can get through him with 1
decent partnership we can win.''
 &UR; (ik-tjh)
</TEXT>
