<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-World Junior,0380 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Czech Republic 6, United States 3
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRANDON, Manitoba (AP) _ Petr Mika scored two power-play goals
and added an assist to lead the Czech Republic to a 6-3 win against
the United States at the world junior hockey championship on Monday
night.
	   Vaclav Pletka, Martin Lamich, Michal Travnicek and Tomas Divisek
also scored for the Czechs (1-1).
	   Scott Gomez scored two goals and Mathew Doman added one for the
Americans (0-2). Brian Gionta had two assists.
 &UR; Sweden 5, Switzerland 1
	   At Winnipeg, Marcus Kristoffersson had a goal and an assist as
Sweden remained unbeaten after two games with a win over
Switzerland.
	   Jakob Johansson, David Ytfeldt, Christian Berglund and Mattias
Karlin also scored for the Swedes (2-0).
	   Flavien Conne scored for Switzerland (1-1).
 &UR; Russia 7, Kazakstan 0
	   At Portage la Prairie, Manitoba, Denis Arkhipov scored twice
during a four-goal second period as Russia routed Kazakstan.
	   Serguei Verenikine, Iouri Dobryshkine, Dmitri Kirilenko, Denis
Chvidky and Petr Stchastlivyi also scored for Russia (1-1).
Kazakstan dropped to 0-1-1.
	   Arkhipov opened the scoring at 9:41 of the second. Five minutes
later, Dobryshkine converted on a power play and 35 seconds after
that, Verenikine made it 3-0. Arkhipov added his second goal 51
seconds later.
 &UR; Canada 6, Finland 4
	   At Winnipeg, Jason Chimera scored his first two international
goals leading Canada to victory over defending champion Finland.
	   Kyle Calder, Rico Fata, Daniel Tkaczuk and Simon Gagne, with an
empty-netter, also scored for Canada (1-0-1), which opened the game
with two goals in the first three minutes.
	   Canada led 3-0 after the first period, but sagged in the second
period.
	   Philadelphia Flyers draft pick Marko Kauppinen put Finland (1-1)
within one goal of Canada on a power play at the end of the second
period after goals from teammates Olli Ahonen and Tampa Bay
Lightning prospect Eero Somervuori.
	   Tomek Valtonen scored for Finland on a power play with 18
seconds left in the game before Gagne put the game away for Canada.
	   The top three teams in each five-team pool advance to the
quarterfinals with the top team in each pool earning a bye. 	   
</TEXT>
