<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Bank Theft-Internet </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Bank clerk embezzles for Internet friend in Canada
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ A Singapore bank clerk embezzled from her Dutch
employer so she could loan money to a Canadian man she knew only
via the Internet and phone conversations, a newspaper reported
Tuesday.
	   Ooi May Ling, a former clerk at Dutch bank ABN Amro, was
sentenced by a Singapore court on Monday to one year in jail, said
The Straits Times, which had a reporter in the courtroom.
	   She stole dlrs 22,502 from the bank in October, then used it to
settle huge phone bills chalked up in calls to John Elia, whom she
met via the Internet in June, and transferred dlrs 6,663 to his
account, the report said.
	   Elia, whose home town was not reported, had told her he was
facing financial hardship because he was unemployed, and had also
said he was a former employee of the Bank of Montreal, the paper
said. She had been sending him money since August, it added.
	   Ooi, who had been employed at ABN Amro for nearly two years,
returned about 40 percent of the stolen money to the bank, but the
funds sent to Elia had not been recovered. 	   
</TEXT>
