<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Drug Charges </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American man charged for importing cocaine
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ An American who arrived at Sydney
airport in a wheelchair tried to smuggle 3.6 kilograms (8 pounds)
of cocaine into Australia so he could pay for cancer treatment, a
court was told Tuesday.
	   Herbert Edward Mazzola, 53, an accountant from Tampa, Florida,
was charged in Central Local Court with trying to import a
trafficable quantity of the drug.
	   Police prosecutor Sgt. Paul Taylor said Mazzola arrived in
Sydney late Monday night and was wheeled into the terminal building
by Qantas staff.
	   At first he told Australian Customs officials he had nothing to
declare, but later admitted he had the cocaine in packages strapped
to his legs and buttocks, the police prosecutor said.
	   Mazzola said he brought the drugs into Australia so he could
help pay for treatment for lung cancer and brain lesions. Taylor
said Mazzola had a wife and 10-year-old daughter in Florida.
	   Magistrate Geoffrey Bradd remanded Mazzola in custody until Jan.
27. Mazzola did not enter a plea or apply for bail. 	   
</TEXT>
