<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bodies of foreign hostages returned to Britain
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAKU, Azerbaijan (AP) _ The bodies of four men beheaded in
Chechnya were handed over to British officials early Tuesday and
put on a plane for London.
	   The remains were put on to a British Airways flight in the
presence of British diplomats and Chechen officials before dawn.
Azeri soldiers carried the coffins of the four and placed them on
the plane.
	   The bodies had arrived earlier from Chechnya in a convoy
accompanied by Chechen Deputy Prime Minister Turpal Atgeriyev and
Deputy Prosecutor General Magomed Magomadov.
	   Officials from the British Embassy in Azerbaijan met the convoy
in Russia, according to Russian press reports.
	   The handover was originally planned for Monday, but appeared to
have been delayed by the sides' disagreement on where it should
take place.
	   A spokesman for the British Embassy in Moscow, Mike Haddock,
said Britain wanted the handover to take place in the Russian
capital, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   But Chechnya's Deputy Prime Minister Kazbek Makhashev said the
separatist republic considered the proposal ``unacceptable'' and
wanted the bodies to be handed over in Azerbaijan, Interfax
reported.
	   Chechnya, which had fought a 1994-96 war for secession from
Russia, adamantly tries to assert its independence from Moscow. No
country has recognized its sovereignty.
	   The bodies of the four men were found Saturday in the village of
Chernorechiye, on the outskirts of the Chechen capital, Grozny.
Doctors confirmed the identities of the bodies Sunday, according to
Chechen Prosecutor General Mansur Tagirov.
	   The four men _ Peter Kennedy, Darren Hickey and Rudolf Petschi
of Britain, and New Zealand's Stanley Shaw _ were kidnapped Oct. 3,
and their severed heads were found by a roadside on Dec. 8.
	   A mourning service for the four was held Monday in the church of
St. Archangel Michael in Grozny, the capital of predominantly
Muslim Chechnya.
	   Authorities said the men, who were in Chechnya to set up a
cellular phone system, had been killed after a rescue attempt went
wrong.
	   The region, in the southern Caucasus, has seen a boom in crime
and kidnappings for ransom since Chechnya's independence war ended.
	   (stg/ren)
</TEXT>
