w2881 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BalloonQuest-Australi     12-29 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest-Australia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pilots get the feel for space during tests for balloon flight
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos ALS101-106 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia (AP) _ Looking for all the world like a
cosmonaut, balloon pilot John Wallington on Tuesday climbed into
the space suit he will wear during the latest bid to fly nonstop
around the world, giving the thumbs up to its Russian designer.
	   Following the emergency procedures he and his two U.S.
counterparts will follow if anything goes wrong during their
planned subspace flight, Wallington laced, strapped and zipped
himself in before the pressurized suit was inflated with compressed
air.
	   Denver real estate magnate Dave Liniger, Albuquerque, New Mexico
journalist Bob Martin and Australian Wallington expect to take off
Jan. 1 in their bid to pilot a giant balloon around the world,
avoiding adverse weather by flying on the edge of space.
	   Their bid comes just days after Chicago millionaire Steve
Fossett and his team splashed down in the Pacific Ocean, ending the
latest attempt in a more conventional balloon.
	   Final construction of the capsule and equipment checks are
underway in the Australian Outback town of Alice Springs, where
winds and unseasonal summer rains over the desert launch zone have
delayed takeoff by several days.
	   Boris Mikhajlov, an engineer from the Russian space company
Zvezda, which makes space suits for the Soyuz and Mir space
programs, overlooked Wallington's test and spoke to him through the
suit's intercom with the aid of a Russian interpreter.
	   ``This reminds us we're going to near space,'' said Wallington,
after deflating the suit and unclipping the dome-like visor.
	   ``I have total faith in the suits but I sincerely hope that we
don't have to climb into them.''
	   The trio will wear the hot, uncomfortable gear during the
balloon's takeoff and landing _ the most dangerous times _ and then
only if something goes wrong during the flight.
	   The worst thing than could happen is ``explosive decompression''
of the capsule _ a sudden breach of the hull big enough to
instantly turn the atmosphere inside from livable to unbreathable.
There is only 0.3 percent of the Earth's atmosphere where the
balloon will be flying.
	   ``If there is a catastrophic failure, the pilots won't even
know, it will be too fast,'' team spokesman Kevin Roark said.
	   ``If there is a slow leak, which is more likely, the pilots will
be able to get into their suits and either plug the leak with
special tape or make the decision to come down.''
	   The capsule will dangle beneath a polyethylene balloon that is
460 feet (140 meters) in diameter at ``full float'' and 700 feet
(210 meters) high, large enough to envelope the Houston Astrodome.
	   It will rise 1,000 feet (300 meters) a minute during takeoff to
reach a cruising altitude of 130,000 feet (40,000 meters), or about
24 miles (39 kilometers), above sea level.
	   There, the team expects to catch winds that will carry it west
at up to 80 mph (128 miles) along a route that almost directly
follows the Tropic of Capricorn and complete the 22,800-mile
(37,000-kilometer) journey in about 18 days.
	   The NASA-developed balloon type has been used before, but only
to carry unmanned scientific payloads to heights of about 80,000
feet (24,000 meters).
	   Life support systems aboard the capsule include dehumidifiers to
remove perspiration and respiration moisture, oxygen and nitrogen
tanks to provide breathable air and a solid waste disposal unit.
	   Science and research projects the pilots will take part in
include collecting data on upward lightning for the Los Alamos
National Laboratory at the University of California and medical and
other studies for the University of Colorado and the University of
New Mexico. 	   
</TEXT>
