<HEADLINE>
Nissan shuts Indonesian car factory
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Japan' Nissan Motor Co. and its
partners decided to close their Indonesian car factory because of
poor economic conditions, the Jakarta stock exchange said.
	   One of Nissan's partners, PT Indomobil Sukses Internasional,
sent a letter to the exchange in which it announced the closure of
PT Ismac Nissan Manufacturing.
	   ``The decision was made on grounds that a recovery in the
country's automotive industry can't be achieved soon,'' the stock
exchange on Monday quoted the letter as saying.
	   The Indonesian car plant assembled 1,450 vehicles this year,
compared to 7,625 in 1997.
	   Indonesia's worst economic crisis in decades was triggered last
year by the fall of Asian currencies. The regional financial
turmoil has hit especially hard in Indonesia, where millions of
people have lost their jobs and prices have soared.
	   The economy shrank as much as 16 percent this year and a full
recovery is expected to take years. 	   
</TEXT>
