<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Illegal Dividends </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Failed bank may have extended illegal dividends
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A failed Japanese lender is suspected of violating
the law by offering stock dividends this year despite being warned
by the central bank it was in deep financial trouble, a news report
said Tuesday.
	   The Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., which was recently
nationalized after being declared insolvent, announced it would
extend 7 billion yen (dlrs 60 million) in dividends at a
shareholders meeting in June, the Yomiuri newspaper reported.
	   The payments came shortly after the Bank of Japan had informed
LTCB that 70 percent of its 2.79 trillion yen (dlrs 24 billion) in
loans to affiliates had gone sour, placing the bank in danger of
collapsing, said the Yomiuri, Japan's largest daily.
	   The Financial Supervisory Agency says that the dividends may
have broken Japan's Commercial Code, which prohibits companies from
extending dividends in excess of their profits, the Yomiuri
reported.
	   The agency, which has been examining LTCB's books, said the
bank's shortage of reserves to cover potential loan losses and the
extent of its undeclared problem loans showed that the bank had no
profits at the time it offered the dividends.
	   Tokyo prosecutors and the Securities and Exchange Surveillance
Commission are reportedly questioning former LTCB executives about
the case. Officials connected with the investigation were
unavailable for comment.
	   The Yomiuri said that LTCB's June dividend payments for fiscal
1997 were equal to those it had extended the previous year.
Japanese companies have been known to be reluctant to slash
dividends out of concern for concealing their financial
difficulties.
	   The financial supervisory committee revealed in October that
LTCB had drastically understated the amount of its problem loans
before the government discovered the real state of its finances.
	   The government took over LTCB in October as part of its ongoing
efforts to mop up bad debts that have been crippling Japan's
banking system. The bank had liabilities exceeding assets by some
340 billion yen (2.93 billion).
	   LTCB became the first Japanese bank to be nationalized since the
end of World War II.
 &UR; (js)
</TEXT>
