</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Censorship </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese sentenced for printing, dealing in illegal political
</HEADLINE>
publications

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Moving to enforce a ban on publications deemed
politically suspect, Chinese authorities have sentenced several
groups of people to prison sentences of up to 13 years, the
official newspaper People's Daily reported Tuesday.
	   The longest sentences were handed to Wang Suozhu, of Hebei
province, near Beijing, and others convicted of publishing more
than 15,000 ``politically illegal'' items between October 1997 and
April, the report said.
	   Wang and the others were sentenced to jail terms of five to 13
years, and fined between 100,000 yuan and 200,000 yuan (dlrs
12,100-dlrs 24,200).
	   Cases in Beijing, Tianjin, to the east of Beijing, and the
central province of Hunan also resulted in prison sentences and
fines for those found responsible for buying or selling illegal
publications, the report said.
	   The report said only that the items in question had ``severe
political problems,'' without providing any details about the books
or magazines that had been banned.
	   Last week, the government announced a renewed campaign to impose
strict controls on the media and ban all items considered to be
obscene or politically unacceptable to the ruling Communist Party.
	   The campaign is part of a crackdown on dissent that in the past
two weeks has resulted in prison sentences of from 10 to 13 years
for dissidents associated with the China Democracy Party, whose
organizers had attempted to set up a legal opposition party.
	   As China approaches the 10th anniversary of the military
suppression of protests in Tiananmen Square and the 50th
anniversary of the founding of Communist China in 1949, the
government has stepped up efforts to enforce stability and prevent
unrest among the growing army of unemployed workers and other
disaffected groups. 	   
</TEXT>
