</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Foreign Exchange </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Violators of foreign exchange laws to face harsh sentences
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Chinese courts can impose sentences of up to life
in prison for those found guilty of violating a newly revised
foreign exchange law, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported
Tuesday.
	   A revision to the law adopted Tuesday by the top committee of
the National People's Congress stipulates a maximum sentence of
life imprisonment for major violations of foreign exchange
regulations, the report said.
	   Those convicted of purchasing foreign exchange using forged
documents, of evading payments or of engaging in illegal trading
activities could face the maximum penalty, it said without
describing previous penalties.
	   The revised law tightens enforcement of rules banning companies
from making illegal deposits or transfers of foreign exchange
abroad and it holds government and company officials liable to
criminal prosecution for allowing others to commit such offenses.
	   Those found guilty under the law may face fines of between 5
percent and 30 percent of the value of the illegal transactions,
Xinhua added.
	   China's currency, the yuan, is convertible only for trade and
related services. The government has been stepping up enforcement
of widely flouted currency controls to help ensure a stable
exchange rate and prevent companies and individuals from illegally
transfering funds overseas.
	   Police recently uncovered 232 cases of illegal currency deals
involving the equivalent of more than dlrs 8.8 billion, many of
which involved the use of forged documents, the newspaper Legal
Daily reported Tuesday.
	   The report said the police had recently established an economic
crimes investigation unit to deal with such cases. 	   
</TEXT>
