<HEADER>
w2902 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shielded from trial, Khmer Rouge leaders meet premier with smiles
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with details of meeting, Khieu Samphan's
hair dyed, other details &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associate Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders long
wanted for genocide were greeted with handshakes and smiles by
Prime Minister Hun Sen at a military base Tuesday after he defied
growing pressure and pledged not to put them on trial.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, key members of the inner circle of
late Khmer Rouge chieftain Pol Pot, were flown by helicopter from a
former rebel stronghold to Hun Sen's heavily guarded residence on a
base outside the capital.
	   Khieu Samphan, 67, needed help walking up stairs. His normally
white hair was dyed black in an apparent attempt at disguise during
his months on the run as Khmer Rouge territory fell under
government control.
	   Laughing and joking, Hun Sen told Khieu Samphan not to worry
about a throng of journalists, most of whom were kept at bay.
	   ``I told journalists all about this yesterday at a Cabinet
meeting, so I don't need to make a lot of comment,'' Hun Sen said.
	   They posed for pictures with Ieng Sary, a Khmer Rouge leader who
was pardoned in 1996 for his role in genocide in exchange for
making peace with the government and leading thousands of
guerrillas out of a stalemated civil war.
	   In exchange for officially ending their part in the war _ all
but over for more than a year anyway _ Hun Sen said he would not
try Khieu Samphan or Nuon Chea for the deaths of as many as 2
million people.
	   ``If we bring them to trial, it will not benefit the nation, it
will only mean a return to civil war,'' Hun Sen said Monday. ``We
should dig a hole and bury the past and look toward the future.''
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea have been sheltered for several days
in Pailin, an ex-rebel stronghold nominally under government
control run by Ieng Sary.
	   It was Nuon Chea's first visit to the capital since the Khmer
Rouge were overthrown in 1979 by a Vietnamese invasion. Khieu
Samphan came to the capital in 1991 after a peace treaty _ later
broken by the Khmer Rouge _ was signed. He was stoned by a Hun
Sen-controlled mob.
	   In the past two years, granting pardons to Khmer Rouge leaders
broke the back of their guerrilla war and gave Cambodia its best
hope in decades of rebuilding. But now, calls are rising for
someone to be held accountable.
	   The Maoist revolutionaries won a civil war in 1975 and forced
Cambodians into slave labor camps. About one person in five
perished from overwork, starvation, disease and executions.
	   Under heavy guard, Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary lifted
off from the Pailin police station for the two-hour flight to
Takhmau, a Phnom Penh suburb where Hun Sen lives on a base dubbed
the ``Tiger's Lair.'' They were accompanied by their families.
	   Leading members of the Cambodian People's Party _ led by those
who, like Hun Sen, were once Khmer Rouge cadres before fleeing
bloody purges _ joined the meeting.
	   Khieu Samphan was the Khmer Rouge's nominal leader, though it is
debatable how much influence he had. Pol Pot and other leaders
guarded their identities and were rarely seen in public, preferring
to send Khieu Samphan to speak for them.
	   Nuon Chea was regarded as second-in-command and chief political
theorist. There is extensive evidence of his role in mass
executions of party members suspected of treason.
	   Former members of the inner circle who have defected tend to
place all blame on Pol Pot, who died in April of a heart attack.
	   Only one guerrilla leader remains at large: Ta Mok, known as
``The Butcher,'' is somewhere on the Thai border with no more than
100 die-hard loyalists. They pose no threat.
	   Though Hun Sen clearly said there would be no trial, government
spokesman Khieu Kanharith tried Tuesday to leave open the chances
of submitting a case to an international tribunal or local courts.
	   ``Once it is determined by the court, local or international,
who is responsible for the genocide, then we can move forward,''
Khieu Kanharith said.
	   The chaotic Cambodian judicial system is not independent.
	   Youk Chhang, director of a center that gathers evidence of the
genocide, hoped Hun Sen was playing a game to lure the pair into
custody.
	   ``The circumstances may have forced him to say something like
this,'' Youk Chhang said, urging the United States and other
countries to temper calls for a trial and give Hun Sen maneuvering
room. 	   
</TEXT>
