w2904 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Politics     12-29 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sharon says he may run for prime minister
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon has said
he has not ruled out running for prime minister if ``special
reasons'' arise that require his candidacy for the elections on May
17.
	   The popular hawk in the ruling Likud Party did not say if he
might run against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in party
primaries at the end of January or could form his own slate.
	   Hardliner Uzi Landau had thus far been the only candidate in the
party to emerge as a competitor with Netanyahu and polls showed he
had little chance to beat the premier.
	   Although Sharon told the Likud central committee Sunday evening
he did ``not want to be prime minister,'' he said he may run on
Channel Two television Monday night.
	   ``There is a difference between I don't want to be prime
minister and (I may run) for special reasons,'' Sharon said.
	   Sharon did not specify his intentions. But there was speculation
he could throw his hat in the ring if Netanyahu's popularity drops
or key leaders abandon the Likud party as they have hinted they
might.
	   Sharon resigned his post as defense minister in 1983 after he
was held indirectly responsible for the massacre of hundreds of
Palestinians during Israel's military offensive to chase PLO
guerrillas out of Lebanon.
	   Since then and until he was named foreign minister three months
ago, Sharon served only in second-rank posts despite his
popularity.
	   The Likud and the opposition Labor Party agreed Monday that
elections would be held on May 17 after the parliament gave intial
approval last week to a bill for early elections. An expected
second round would be held on June 1.
	   Recent polls have shown that Netanyahu would not receive enough
votes to win a first round.
	   The surveys revealed also that Netanyahu would lose in a second
vote against either Labor leader Ehud Barak or Amnon Lipkin-Shahak,
a former chief of staff who is expected to announce his candidacy
at the head of a newly-formed centrist party.
	   lc	   
</TEXT>
