<HEADER>
w2912 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-DeadlyYacht     12-29 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Deadly Yacht Race-Rescuers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Navy pilot taken back in time during yacht rescue
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BENJAMIN PEDLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MERIMBULA, Australia (AP) _ Navy pilot Tanzi Lea peered down
into mountainous seas and was carried back 20 years to the 1979
Fastnet race where 15 sailors perished.
	   Lea was the pilot of a navy Sea King helicopter which hauled two
dead sailors out of Bass Strait Tuesday, bringing the death toll
from the Sydney-to-Hobart race to five confirmed with one other
presumed drowned.
	   Lea was a member of Britain's Royal Navy during the Fastnet
rescue off the southwest coast of Ireland where only 85 yachts
finished out of 303 starters because of high winds and punishing
waves.
	   ``The seas were as big as I saw during rescues in the Fastnet
race 20 years ago,'' Lea told The Associated Press after arriving
back with the two bodies Tuesday. ``Under those circumstances
you've got to be careful and act prudently.''
	   Lea, now with the Australian navy, was involved throughout the
search and rescue process. He said the weather was at its worst
Monday and Sunday but had calmed considerably by the time his
helicopter reached the bodies Tuesday.
	   ``A big depression formed quickly and although a change was
expected I don't think people thought it would be this bad,'' Lea
said.
	   The two dead men were believed to be from the veteran cutter
Winston Churchill. Another crew member is missing while six others
were carried to safety.
	   Two of the men saved were in a life raft which had its bottom
torn away by heavy seas. A wave knocked their three mates out of
reach.
	   Shane Pashley, a navy diver, reached the two crew members who
had managed to hang onto the remnants of their life raft.
	   ``We winched the first guy up who was absolutely exhausted, the
waves were crashing over the top of the raft which made it very
difficult as I was continually dragged under the water,'' Pashley
told the Associated Press.
	   ``Once we'd winched him up we put him on the floor of the
aircraft and turned the heaters up because he was suffering from
exposure,'' Pashley said.
	   The harness was sent down for the second survivor but it snagged
on the life raft. He was eventually hauled aboard the helicopter.
	   ``One bloke said he knew where the other guys were but we
couldn't do anything as we were nearly out of fuel,'' Pashley said.
``They were just really tired and very thirsty, one of the guys was
only wearing a spray jacket and shorts.''
	   Pashley, like most Australians, has vivid memories of the rescue
of English yachtsman Tony Bullimore, who showed unrestrained joy
after being found following four days alone at sea in early 1997.
	   But there was no great sense of celebration for Pashley.
	   ``There were no Tony Bullimore-style kisses,'' he said. ``They
were just done.'' 	   
</TEXT>
