<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Riot </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two police stations burned in Indonesia protest
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ At least 800 people burned two police
stations on Indonesia's Sumatra island during a protest against the
death in detention of a fellow villager, police said Tuesday.
	   Nine policemen and at least two villagers were injured in the
clash Monday in Liwa, 300 kilometers (187 miles) northwest of
Jakarta, the Indonesian capital. Officers fired warning shots to
disperse stone-throwing rioters who attacked a third police post.
	   Meanwhile, calm returned Tuesday to the Sulawesi island town of
Poso after fighting between mobs that was triggered by weekend
brawls involving gangs of youths.
	   At least 150 people were injured in the clashes Monday, said Dr.
Abram, a physician at the local hospital in Poso.
	   Troops patrolled the debris-strewn streets of Poso and security
was also tight in the Sumatra town of Deli Serdang, where police
firing plastic bullets injured six people Monday during a protest
by peasants over land rights.
	   The violence in Liwa broke out after the death of a villager who
had been detained for questioning in a robbery case.
	   A preliminary autopsy indicated that Sanin committed suicide,
police chief Lt. Col. Tri Parnoyo Kartiko said by telephone.
	   However, rumors spread that police had killed the villager and
residents took to the streets in protest. They were also angry over
the detention of another man in the same case.
	   Mired in its worst economic crisis in decades, Indonesia endured
numerous riots this year as ethnic, political and religious
tensions rose.
	   The unrest reached a peak in May shortly before the ouster of
authoritarian President Suharto after 32 years in power. Some 1,200
people died in riots in Jakarta. 	   
</TEXT>
