<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower against yen, Japanese stocks higher in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing stocks, mid afternoon dollar, bond, other
details

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar was lower against the yen Tuesday
in thin year-end trading, as investors took profits and some grew
bearish about the outlook for the U.S. economy. Japanese stock
prices rose.
	   The dollar bought 115.42 yen at mid afternoon, down 0.70 yen
from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of
115.90 yen overnight.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 137.84
points, or 1.01 percent, to close at 13,846.90. On Monday, the
average fell 88.89 points, or 0.64 percent.
	   In currency dealings, the dollar dipped as traders locked in
profits on the U.S. currency, which was boosted earlier in the
session by commercial demand and news of renewed tension between
the United States and Iraq, traders said.
	   Many Japanese institutional investors were also growing jittery
about the possibility that America's long economic boom may be
running out of steam.
	   ``The number of dollar bears who see the U.S. economy slowing
down next year is increasing among Japanese institutional investors
and interbank players,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of
foreign exchange at ABN AMRO Bank.
	   The dollar was supported in early Tokyo trading and also
overnight in New York on news that U.S. warplanes fired missiles
Monday at an Iraqi air defense site in the northern part of the
country.
	   The attack came two days after Baghdad announced it would fire
at Western aircraft patrolling the no-fly zones over northern and
southern Iraq.
	   The U.S. dollar is considered a safe haven in times of
international unrest.
	   On the stock market, share prices gained in a late surge on
futures-led buying. Trading was thin as many participants have
taken off for the New Year holidays.
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.76 points
to 9,226.75 at Monday's close.
	   Many investors also took to the sidelines to await developments
in a proposed coalition deal between Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's
Liberal Democratic Party and the opposition Liberal Party.
	   The two sides were expected to seal a pact this week that would
boost the LDP's leverage in Parliament, but last-minute
disagreements caused negotiations to stall.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section gained 8.94 points, 0.83 percent, to 1,088.83. The
TOPIX closed down 3.07 points, or 0.28 percent, the day before.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond rose to 1.865 percent from Monday's close at 1.685 percent,
driving its price down to 99.47 yen from 100.93 yen. 	   
</TEXT>
