<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Egypt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Citing better security, Japan eases travel restrictions in Egypt
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan has eased restriction on tours in Egypt,
citing the effectiveness of security measures taken by the Egyptian
government since a terrorist attack last year, the Foreign Ministry
said Tuesday.
	   Japanese travel agencies have restricted their tours in Egypt
since nearly a dozen Japanese tourists were killed in one of the
deadliest terrorist attacks ever at the Temple city of Luxor on
Nov. 17, last year.
	   The measures have been in effect for Japanese travelers to three
Egyptian cities _ Luxor, Aswan and Abu Simbel.
	   In all, 58 foreigners, including 35 Swiss tourists, were killed
in the Luxor attack, which was carried out by Islamic militants.
Four Egyptians and the six gunmen also died.
	   Japan's Foreign Ministry still advises that Japanese who are
staying in Egypt or planning to travel there take precautions, said
a ministry spokesman. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   A record 60,200 Japanese visited Egypt last year, up slightly
from 60,130 in 1996, according to Japanese government figures.
	   Egyptian authorities have campaigned against Islamic militants,
including carrying out raids, making arrests and extraditing
suspects abroad.
	   They say the measures have been successful in stopping random
attacks against government officials, police and tourists. More
security forces have also been posted at Egypt's famous temples.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
