<HEADER>
w2948 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-MarcosWea     12-29 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Marcos Wealth </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Imelda Marcos asks court to dismiss ill-gotten wealth cases
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo MLA101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The widow of dictator Ferdinand
Marcos Tuesday asked a special anti-graft court to dismiss cases
filed by the Philippine government to recover dlrs 570 million in
Swiss bank deposits the Marcoses allegedly stole from public
coffers.
	   A lawyer of former first lady Imelda Marcos said the cases were
filed by Philippine government lawyers in December 1991, more than
a year after the required period for doing so has expired.
	   Lawyer Rodolfo Jimenez said the Philippine government also
violated a law forbidding the filing of such forfeiture cases one
year before any general elections. Presidential, congressional and
local polls were held in the country in May 1992.
	   Under Philippine laws, forfeiture cases can only be filed within
four years after a government official being charged has been
removed from office, Jimenez told a news conference.
	   Marcos was toppled from power by an army-backed popular revolt
in February 1986 and died in exile in Hawaii three years later.
	   The Philippine government has accused the Marcoses of illegally
enriching themselves while in power and has put claims on the
Marcoses' wealth, including the dlrs 570 million in Swiss bank
deposits now held in an escrow account in a Philippine bank. Marcos
has denied the allegations.
	   The money is being contested by the government, Marcos' heirs
and more than 9,000 human rights victims under Marcos.
	   Mrs. Marcos, who appeared at the news conference, said the
forfeiture cases, which are still pending in the Sandiganbayan
court, have dragged on for years but the government has failed to
produce evidence showing the money was illegally acquired by the
Marcoses.
	   She said she was ready to enter into a settlement with the
administration of President Joseph Estrada.
	   ``I'm always ready to sit down, settle, to do what is right,''
she said, adding she wanted to use the money to support projects
for the poor.
	   ``Our hearts are in the right place,'' Mrs. Marcos said. 	   
</TEXT>
