w2954 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Myanmar-Drug     12-29 0245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Myanmar-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Thai drug kingpin sheltered by Myanmar ethnic rebels
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A fugitive Thai drug kingpin is being
sheltered by ethnic rebels in neighboring Myanmar, a former Thai
army chief said in Tuesday's local papers.
	   Gen. Chetta Thanajaro, retired army commander in chief, said
Myanmar's military government had determined the kingpin was living
with the rebel Red Wa army, according to the Bangkok Post.
	   The Wa are an ethnic group that has signed a cease fire with the
government in Yangon and are allowed to continue drug trafficking.
They are major producers and smugglers of opium, heroin and
amphetamines.
	   The Thai drug trafficker, Surachai Ngernthongfoo, alias Bang
Ron, is wanted in Thailand for allegedly running one of the largest
amphetamine rings in the country.
	   Army officers, including a general, have been implicated in his
business.
	   Chetta told the Post that the government of Myanmar, also known
as Burma, was negotiating with the Wa to have Bang Ron handed over
to Thailand.
	   The Post also reported that the police department will force
officers suspected of involvement in the narcotics trade to take a
rehabilitation course aimed at improving their ethics.
	   The decision came after a deputy prime minister said last week
that as many as 800 government officials are suspected of being
involved in the drug trade, but police do not have enough evidence
to arrest them. 	   
</TEXT>
