w2957 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Opposition     12-29 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police warn Singapore politician against speaking publicly
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos SIN101-102
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Threatened by uniformed police, one of
Singapore's few opposition party leaders gave a rare public speech
without a permit Tuesday, saying all other avenues for
disseminating information had been blocked by the government.
	   ``The constitution of Singapore guarantees me freedom of speech,
assembly and association. I'm exercising that right as a fellow
citizen of Singapore and a member of a political party,'' said Chee
Soon Juan, 36, secretary-general of the Singapore Democratic Party.
	   Standing on a lawn at Raffles Place in Singapore's business
district, Chee drew a crowd of more than 250 people to hear his
hour-long speech criticizing the government's economic, human
rights and foreign affairs policies.
	   Chee made statements seldom heard or read in Singapore. He read
detailed descriptions of alleged torture of political prisoners,
said that Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew had been wrong to invest
public money in China, and stated that one of Burma's chief drug
lords comes and goes freely in Singapore, which has a death penalty
for drug traffickers.
	   ``The reason why the government doesn't permit politicians to
talk to you like this is because there's a lot of information they
don't want you to know,'' Chee said.
	   Superintendent Low Hui Hui of the central police station warned
Chee three times before he started speaking that addressing the
public without a permit from the Criminal Investigation Division
violates the Public Entertainment Law. ``I just advised him not to
proceed with the talk,'' said Low. ``If he does, we will open an
investigation.''
	   The night before Chee's speech the police force issued a
statement warning that anyone who gives a talk in a public place
without a permit is subject to a 5,000 Singapore dollars (dlrs
3,030) fine.
	   After the speech, as dozens of onlookers crowded around Chee to
ask follow-up questions, police tried to serve the politician with
a summons to appear for questioning.
	   Chee refused to take it and told the crowd that he intended to
speak at the same place and time next week. Chee, who said his
party has about 200 members, has unsuccessfully run twice for
Parliament. The 84-member legislature has been controlled for 38
years by the People's Action Party.
	   Chee said the government had banned his party's political video,
blocked information from being posted on the Internet about
candidates during the last election, refused or delayed until the
last minute issuing permits for public lectures, and fined him for
trying to sell his book on Asian human rights violations.
	   ``If the government is doing such a good job, why does it have
to have so many controls?'' Chee said. ``We had a very peaceful,
intelligent talk today,'' he said, noting that many in the crowd
were bank employees wearing ties or designer skirts. ``Do you see
anybody going on a riot or running rampant? The permit
(requirement) is here for political control.'' 	   
</TEXT>
