<HEADLINE>
Two bombs explode outside American Express, Barclays banks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) _ Two time bombs exploded early Tuesday
outside bank branches of American Express and Barclays in Greece's
main port city of Piraeus, causing damage but no injuries, police
said.
	   The dynamite bombs had been placed outside the bank entrances
and exploded within six minutes of each other, shortly after an
anonymous caller warned police that the devices had been placed
outside the banks.
	   The caller, who said he represented the little known group
Revolutionary Cells, did not give a reason for the attack.
	   Barclays bank sustained significant damage from the blast, while
windows shattered in nearby buildings and seven cars parked nearby
were also damaged, police said.
	   The American Express branch suffered less damage, mainly
shattered windows, authorities said.
	   In June, the Revolutionary Cells had claimed responsibility for
a time bomb explosion outside the Athens offices of a government
agency responsible for hiring civil servants. Two police officers
had been slightly injured in that attack.
	   A number of small but prolific terrorist groups have this year
carried out more than 150 attacks, mostly firebombs against offices
and cars belonging to government officials, diplomats, journalists
and foreign companies. The attacks are usually carried out late at
night and rarely cause injury.
	   (eb) 	   
</TEXT>
