<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower against yen, Japanese stocks end higher in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with late dollar, bond, other details

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar fell against the yen Tuesday in
light year-end trading amid concern about the resilience of
America's prolonged economic expansion. Japanese stock prices rose.
	   The dollar bought 115.36 yen at late afternoon, down 0.76 yen
from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of
115.90 yen overnight.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 137.84
points, or 1.01 percent, to close at 13,846.90. On Monday, the
average fell 88.89 points, or 0.64 percent.
	   The dollar's decline partly reflected increasing pessimism among
Japanese institutional investors about the United States' ability
to sustain its economic boom, traders said.
	   ``The number of dollar bears who see the U.S. economy slowing
down next year is increasing among Japanese institutional investors
and interbank players,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of
foreign exchange at ABN AMRO Bank.
	   Traders also locked in profits on the U.S. currency, which was
boosted earlier in the session by commercial demand and news that
U.S. warplanes fired missiles Monday at an Iraqi air defense site.
	   The attack came two days after Baghdad announced it would fire
at Western aircraft patrolling the no-fly zones over northern and
southern Iraq.
	   The U.S. dollar is considered a safe haven in times of
international unrest. It ranged between 115.15 yen and 116.21 yen
in Tuesday trading.
	   On the stock market, share prices gained in a late surge on
futures-led buying. Trading was thin as many participants have
taken off for the New Year holidays.
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.76 points
to 9,226.75 at Monday's close.
	   In Tokyo, many investors also took to the sidelines to await
developments in a proposed coalition deal between Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party and the opposition Liberal
Party.
	   The two sides were expected to seal a pact this week that would
boost the LDP's leverage in Parliament, but last-minute
disagreements caused negotiations to stall.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section gained 8.94 points, 0.83 percent, to 1,088.83. The
TOPIX closed down 3.07 points, or 0.28 percent, the day before.
	   An estimated 226 million shares changed hands on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 191.79 million shares
Monday. Advances outnumbered retreats 635 to 435, while 212 issues
were unchanged.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond rose to 1.885 percent from Monday's close of 1.685 percent,
driving its price down to 99.31 yen from 100.93 yen. 	   
</TEXT>
