<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq lashes out at Egypt's Mubarak for supporting U.S. line
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq's official media on Tuesday lashed out
at Arab leaders for not supporting Saddam Hussein's regime while
his deputy prime minister ridiculed the Egyptian president's remark
that Iraq had provoked this month's U.S.-British airstrikes.
	   Arab leaders must either support Iraq or risk the ``wrath'' of
the Arab masses, Iraqi newspapers said and hailed the widespread
public protests in Arab capitals against the Dec. 16-19 airstrikes.
	   The newspapers were commenting on the Arab League's failure to
convene a proposed meeting of Arab foreign ministers to discuss and
condemn the bombardment.
	   In another sign of dwindling official support for Iraq, hopes
are also fading for holding an Arab summit, which Baghdad hopes
will agree to defy U.N. trade sanctions that were imposed after
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   Under U.N. resolutions, the sanctions cannot be lifted until
U.N. weapons inspectors certify that Iraq is free of nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons along with long-range missiles.
	   The inspectors, complaining that Iraq was obstructing their
work, withdrew from the country Dec. 16, triggering the
U.S.-British assault.
	   The governments in Iraq's Arab neighbors have voiced little
opposition to the airstrikes even though the mood on the streets
has been vehemently pro-Iraq.
	   In a front-page editorial, Iraq's al-Qadissiya newspaper warned
Arab leaders that ignoring ``the snowballing Arab wrath ... will
shake the ground from under their feet.''
	   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, in one of his most forthright
comments on the crisis, said in an interview published Monday that
President Saddam's rule was responsible for his country's woes.
	   ``The ruling regime (in Iraq) is the reason for all the problems
... and Egypt naturally does not support this regime,'' Mubarak was
quoted as saying by the al-Gomhuriya, an Egyptian government-owned
newspaper.
	   Mubarak, a close U.S. ally, also said that it was he who
persuaded U.S. President Bill Clinton to halt the bombardment,
whose stated aim was to diminish Iraq's ability to build weapons of
mass destruction.
	   Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz responded to Mubarak with
harsh words in an editorial he wrote for Tuesday's al-Jumhouriya,
an Iraqi government-owned newspaper.
	   ``President Mubarak assumes a role for himself which both
Washington and London have not given to him,'' Aziz wrote in the
front-page editorial.
	   ``In reality there is no noble, fair and intelligent person in
Egypt, in the Arab homeland or the whole world sharing Mr. Mubarak
in his deduction,'' Aziz wrote.
	   He said that in reality Mubarak called for a halt to the strikes
because he feared the anger in the Egyptian and Arab streets.
	   In the first armed clash since the end of the airstrikes, U.S.
warplanes patrolling a no-fly zone over northern Iraq fired at an
Iraqi anti-aircraft system on Monday. Iraq said four soldiers were
killed.
	   The United States said the planes fired in self-defense after
coming under Iraqi missile attack. In the aftermath of the
U.S.-British airstrikes, Iraq had vowed to shoot down Western
planes in its air space even if they were enforcing the no-fly
zones.
	   The United States and its allies set up the no-fly zones to
protect Kurdish and Shiite rebels in the north and south from
Saddam's forces.
	   On Tuesday, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
his government was ``deeply disturbed'' by the exchange of fire. He
also criticized the no-fly zones as violations of U.N. charter and
international norms.
 &UR; lb/vj
</TEXT>
