<HEADLINE>
Two bombs explode outside American Express, Barclays banks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) _ Two time bombs exploded early Tuesday
outside bank branches of American Express and Barclays in Greece's
main port city of Piraeus, causing some damage but no injuries,
police said.
	   The dynamite bombs exploded within six minutes of each other,
shortly after an anonymous caller warned police. The caller, who
said he represented the little-known group Revolutionary Cells, did
not give a reason for the attack.
	   The bomb outside Barclays bank caused significant damage to the
building and seven cars parked nearby and shattered the windows of
buildings in the area, police said.
	   The American Express branch, not far from Barclays bank,
suffered less damage, mainly shattered windows, authorities said.
	   In June, the Revolutionary Cells claimed responsibility for a
time bomb explosion outside the Athens offices of a government
agency responsible for hiring civil servants. Two police officers
were slightly injured in that attack.
	   This year, a number of small but prolific terrorist groups
carried out more than 150 attacks, mostly firebombs against offices
and cars belonging to government officials, diplomats, journalists
and foreign companies. The attacks are usually carried out late at
night and rarely cause injury. 	   
