<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Coalition Talks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Snagged Japanese coalition talks postponed until next year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GINNY PARKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's ruling party and a potential coalition
partner decided Tuesday to shelve talks on an alliance agreement
until next year after negotiators failed to forge a compromise over
defense policy, an opposition party official said.
	   The talks for a pact between the government Liberal Democratic
Party and the opposition Liberal Party snagged during the weekend
over the extent to which Japanese troops should be allowed to join
U.N. military missions.
	   The impasse scuttled a meeting planned for Monday between Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi and Liberal Party leader Ichiro Ozawa.
Negotiators from both sides met on Tuesday to try to work out the
dispute, but the talks later broke up without an agreement.
	   The two sides had hoped to finalize details on the coalition
soon. The LDP is eager to win Liberal Party backing to bolster its
standing in Parliament, where it suffered losses in elections over
the summer.
	   A Liberal Party official speaking on condition of anonymity said
that the two sides decided to wait until Jan. 6, after Japanese New
Year celebrations, to resume talks. News reports also said
negotiators would meet again on that date.
	   On Monday, officials from both sides blamed the other for the
impasse. Ozawa accused the LDP of not being serious about cutting a
deal, which Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka said the LP's
insistence of a broader military role for Japan jeopardized the
coalition plan.
	   Ozawa is pushing for a new interpretation of Japan's
U.S.-written constitution that would allow troops to participate
more fully in U.N. military missions. The LDP, however, wants to
restrict troops to logistical operations away from potential
combat, arguing that the constitution bans Japanese use of force
abroad.
	   News reports on Tuesday also said that Ozawa was holding out for
a better position in the coalition government. The reports said he
was dissatisfied with the position of home affairs minister that
Obuchi was expected to offer him and instead was eager to become
deputy prime minister. The Liberal Party official said he could not
confirm those reports.
	   So far, the two sides have agreed on reducing the number of
Cabinet posts from 20 to 18 and abolishing the system in which
senior bureaucrats speak on behalf of ministers during Diet
debates. 	   
</TEXT>
