<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
England wins fourth test
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Paceman Dean Headley bowled England
to a thrilling 12-run victory over Australia in the fourth cricket
test at the MCG on Tuesday.
	   Although Australia has retained the Ashes, England kept its
hopes alive of squaring the series, down 2-1 with one to play.
	   Australia's tail folded dramatically as the team chased 175 for
victory on the fourth afternoon, losing 7-32 after reaching 130 for
three.
	   Headley claimed 6-60 and made the decisive move when he had
Darren Lehmann, Ian Healy and Damien Fleming out in the space of 12
balls with the total stuck on 140.
	   Steve Waugh, who scored a brilliant century in the first
innings, was stranded at the non-striker's end on 30 as Australia
lost its last three wickets for one run.
	   Darren Gough ended the match by bowling Stuart MacGill and
following up with the wicket of Glenn McGrath.
	   After the first day was lost entirely to rain the other three
days were extended.
	   Australia needed 18 for victory and had three wickets in hand
when it opted to play an extra half an hour Tuesday, offered under
the rules when a result is imminent.
	   The English players clearly did not want to stay on the field,
with captain Alec Stewart arguing with the umpires, but the extra
time worked in their favor.
	   The key to England's win was the performance of its
much-maligned tail end batsmen earlier Tuesday. They carried the
score to 244 along with 60 from Graeme Hick.
	   No.11 Alan Mullally, who had five ducks from six previous test
innings this series, even helped out and riled rival paceman Glenn
McGrath by hitting him for consecutive fours in an innings of 16.
	   Australia made a poor start to its chase, losing Michael Slater
and Mark Taylor with 41 on the board. Hick dropped a chance to put
England in control when he spilled a catch from Justin Langer with
41 still on the board.
	   But Langer was removed by a brilliant catch at square leg by
Mark Ramprakash, diving away to his right, and the dismissal
appeared to galvanize the fielding team.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
