r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Iraq     12-29 0267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China `deeply disturbed' by shooting in Iraq
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China said Tuesday it was ``deeply disturbed'' by
a deadly exchange of fire between U.S. warplanes and Iraqi air
defenses and called for preventing a worsening of tensions over
Iraq.
	   Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao also criticized
the two no-fly zones imposed by the United States and its Gulf War
allies over Iraq, saying they violate the United Nations charter
and the norms of international relations.
	   ``We are very concerned about the developments in Iraq and
deeply disturbed by the exchange of fire in northern Iraq and the
casualties incurred,'' Zhu said at a twice-weekly media briefing.
	   Iraq said four soldiers were killed and seven injured when U.S.
planes patrolling a no-fly zone in northern Iraq fired at an Iraqi
anti-aircraft site Monday. The United States said its planes acted
in self-defense after being fired on by Iraq surface-to-air
missiles.
	   The U.S. attack came two days after Baghdad announced it would
fire at Western aircraft patrolling the no-fly zones over northern
and southern Iraq.
	   ``We hold that the establishment of no-fly zones in Iraq runs
counter to the U.N. charter and the norms governing international
relations,'' Zhu, the Chinese spokesman, said.
	   ``We call on the parties concerned to take necessary measures to
avert further deterioration of the situation,'' he added.
	   He said issues left over from the 1990-1991 Gulf War should be
settled fairly and reasonably ``to restore peace and stability in
the region.'' 	   
</TEXT>
