<SLUG> BC-Britain-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede BAKU
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Bodies of foreign hostages returned to Britain
 &UR; Eds: Updates with bodies' arrival in London. Stands as lead to
Russia-Chechnya &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The bodies of four kidnapped men who were beheaded
in Chechnya arrived in London early Tuesday on a flight from
Azerbaijan.
	   The four victims _ Peter Kennedy, Darren Hickey and Rudolf
Petschi of Britain, and New Zealand's Stanley Shaw _ were kidnapped
in Chechnya Oct. 3, and their severed heads were found by a
roadside on Dec. 8.
	   Their bodies, which were found Saturday near the Chechen
capital, Grozny, were put on a British Airways flight before dawn
in Baku in the presence of British diplomats and Chechen officials.
	   The bodies had arrived in Baku from Chechnya in a convoy
accompanied by Chechen Deputy Prime Minister Turpal Atgeriyev and
Deputy Prosecutor General Magomed Magomadov. Officials from the
British Embassy in Azerbaijan met the convoy in Russia, according
to Russian press reports.
	   At Gatwick Airport, the coffins were unloaded and taken to an
area where relatives could collect them away from the public gaze,
an airport spokeswoman said. Foreign Office officials were also
there.
	   ``It is a relief to have the feeling that they are finally
coming home,'' Hickey's father, Eamonn, said Monday night. ``We are
still devastated but at least there will be a funeral after all.''
	   The handover was originally planned for Monday, but appeared to
have been delayed by the sides' disagreement on where it should
take place.
	   A spokesman for the British Embassy in Moscow, Mike Haddock,
said Britain wanted the handover to take place in the Russian
capital, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   But Chechnya's Deputy Prime Minister Kazbek Makhashev said the
separatist republic considered the proposal ``unacceptable'' and
wanted the bodies to be handed over in Azerbaijan, Interfax
reported.
	   Chechnya, which had fought a 1994-96 war for secession from
Russia, adamantly tries to assert its independence from Moscow. No
country has recognized its sovereignty.
	   The bodies of the four men were found Saturday in the village of
Chernorechiye, on the outskirts of the Chechen capital, Grozny.
Doctors confirmed their identities Sunday, according to Chechen
Prosecutor General Mansur Tagirov.
	   A mourning service for the four was held Monday in the church of
St. Archangel Michael in Grozny, the capital of predominantly
Muslim Chechnya.
	   Authorities said the men, who were in Chechnya to set up a
cellular phone system, had been killed after a rescue attempt went
wrong.
	   The region, in the southern Caucasus, has experienced a boom in
crime and kidnappings for ransom since Chechnya's independence war
ended.
	   (lon-acw/stg-ren)
</TEXT>
