<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese dissident issues protest from prison
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ In a letter penned in handcuffs from prison, a
Chinese dissident has defiantly protested as ``political
persecution'' his 13-year sentence for trying to form an opposition
party.
	   Xu Wenli said he would not appeal his sentence out of contempt
for the judicial system that prosecuted him last week.
	   ``My so-called open trial was in truth nothing but a means of
political persecution,'' Xu wrote in the letter, dated Monday and
made available to foreign news organizations.
	   ``First, I will not answer any questions. Second, I will not
defend myself. Third, I will not appeal to a higher court. This is
a silent protest against political persecution.''
	   Xu is among four activists tried and sentenced in the past two
weeks in China's harshest crackdown on political dissent in two
years.
	   Charged with endangering state security, Xu, Qin Yongmin and
Wang Youcai were sentenced to 13, 12 and 11 years respectively for
trying to organize the China Democracy Party. Labor rights
campaigner Zhang Shanguang was sentenced to 10 years Sunday under
the same statute for telling U.S. government-funded Radio Free Asia
about a farmers protest.
	   Xu is the oldest and most experienced democracy campaigner of
the four. His prison protest accuses a small number of leaders
within the ruling Communist Party of protecting their vested
interests by using China's legal system to defend one-party rule.
	   ``Pluralism in the political sphere is historically inevitable.
No individual or political party can prevent this,'' Xu wrote.
	   ``History will judge us fairly,'' wrote Xu, who in recent months
had provided guidance for younger dissidents and a moderate voice
for the beleaguered democracy movement.
	   The statement ended with the words ``penned in handcuffs'' and
with instructions to Xu's court-appointed lawyer to deliver copies
to his wife and to court authorities.
	   During the Democracy Wall protests of the late 1970s, Xu united
dissidents publishing underground journals to form one of the most
influential periodicals of the time.
	   Convicted of subversion in 1982, Xu spent 12 years in prison,
much of it in solitary confinement. After writing an account of his
arrest and trial that was smuggled out of prison, Xu was moved into
a damp cement vault and not allowed out for 3 1/2 years.
	   When he became politically active again after his parole ended
last year, Xu resumed writing about democracy and China's future
and openly organizing other dissidents. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
