<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Poisoning </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former saleswoman indicted in mass curry-poisoning in Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A woman was charged Tuesday with murder and
attempted murder in a mass poisoning with arsenic-laced curry that
killed four people in western Japan.
	   Masumi Hayashi, 37, a former insurance saleswoman arrested Oct.
4, is also suspected in a series of murder attempts to collect
insurance money.
	   The July 25 poisoning with curry served at a community festival
killed four people, including two children, and sickened 63 people.
The poisoning alarmed Japan, a relatively crime-free nation, and
set off copycat poisonings.
	   Japanese media have ranked the poisoning in Wakayama, 450
kilometers (280 miles) southwest of Tokyo, as the top news item of
1998.
	   Hayashi has denied the charges, her lawyers say. Among those she
is alleged to have tried to kill is her husband, Kenji Hayashi, 53,
who has been arrested on separate insurance fraud charges.
	   Prosecutors say an analysis showed that the arsenic found in the
Hayashis' home matched the arsenic in the curry.
 &UR; (yk)
</TEXT>
