<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Japan, Indonesia, China, Singapore and
separates.

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ U.S. financial services company American Express
Co. plans to establish a securities company in Japan next year, a
company spokesman said Tuesday.
	   The company has applied to the Finance Ministry for permission
to set up the venture under new rules that make it easier to launch
a brokerage in Japan, said company spokemsan Mitsuo Inagaki.
	   American Express hopes to sell investment funds to individual
investors, but the company has not yet decided on its range of
products, Inagaki said.
	   The move comes as many foreign financial institutions launch or
expand operations in Japan to take advantage of the country's ``Big
Bang'' financial deregulation reforms.
	   American Express applied to set up its new company under a rule
change implemented this month that eases the cumbersome approval
process for new brokerages, Inagaki said.
	   Last year, American Express established an investment-advisory
business in Tokyo in its first step toward full-fledged asset
management operations in Japan.
	   ___
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Japan' Nissan Motor Co. and its
partners decided to close their Indonesian car factory because of
poor economic conditions, the Jakarta stock exchange said.
	   One of Nissan's partners, PT Indomobil Sukses Internasional,
sent a letter to the exchange in which it announced the closure of
PT Ismac Nissan Manufacturing.
	   ``The decision was made on grounds that a recovery in the
country's automotive industry can't be achieved soon,'' the stock
exchange on Monday quoted the letter as saying.
	   The Indonesian car plant assembled 1,450 vehicles this year,
compared to 7,625 in 1997.
	   Indonesia's worst economic crisis in decades was triggered last
year by the fall of Asian currencies. The regional financial
turmoil has hit especially hard in Indonesia, where millions of
people have lost their jobs and prices have soared.
	   The economy shrank as much as 16 percent this year and a full
recovery is expected to take years.
	   ___
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Chinese courts can impose sentences of up to life
in prison for those found guilty of violating a newly revised
foreign exchange law, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported
Tuesday.
	   A revision to the law adopted Tuesday by the top committee of
the National People's Congress stipulates a maximum sentence of
life imprisonment for major violations of foreign exchange
regulations, the report said.
	   Those convicted of purchasing foreign exchange using forged
documents, of evading payments or of engaging in illegal trading
activities could face the maximum penalty, it said without
describing previous penalties.
	   The revised law tightens enforcement of rules banning companies
from making illegal deposits or transfers of foreign exchange
abroad and it holds government and company officials liable to
criminal prosecution for allowing others to commit such offenses.
	   Those found guilty under the law may face fines of between 5
percent and 30 percent of the value of the illegal transactions,
Xinhua added.
	   China's currency, the yuan, is convertible only for trade and
related services. The government has been stepping up enforcement
of widely flouted currency controls to help ensure a stable
exchange rate and prevent companies and individuals from illegally
transfering funds overseas.
	   Police recently uncovered 232 cases of illegal currency deals
involving the equivalent of more than dlrs 8.8 billion, many of
which involved the use of forged documents, the newspaper Legal
Daily reported Tuesday.
	   ___
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ U.S.-based Delphi Automotive Systems, the
world's largest vehicle components maker, laid off 15 percent of
its plant workers in Singapore, a spokesman said Tuesday.
	   The plant was temporarily closed Monday, and all 1,500 employees
were invited in to hear the details. Termination notices were given
to 229 in small groups, said Delphi spokesman John Anderson.
Interviews were set up with 11 other multinational companies and 23
job offers were made to the retrenched employees by early
afternoon.
	   Anderson said employees were told early in December that Delphi,
which is being spun off from General Motors early next year, would
be restructuring in Singapore and retrenchments could be expected.
	   ``We have been working hard to avoid this type of restructuring
since April 1995, redeploying workers instead, and adopting hiring
freezes,'' Anderson said. Short shifts, a weekend shift and a third
shift were introduced ``in an effort to balance things out,'' he
said.
	   There is no union at the plant, but the company dealt with the
National Trade Unions Council, he said. No offer was made to freeze
or reduce pay in order to save jobs, as the government has
suggested to some unions during Singapore's worst economic crisis
in a decade.
	   The plant, previously run by the Delco company, has been
operating in Singapore for 20 years.
	   ___
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ The cabinet plans to create tax incentives
and other measures to prop up Taiwan's property market, where the
effects of a 7-year slump have worsened amid the recent economic
slowdown, officials said Tuesday.
	   Details of the strategy will be announced Thursday, but the
package also will include loans to boost buying sentiment and other
measures to reduce construction, government spokesman Chen
Chien-jen said.
	   A task force will also be set up to study financial aid to
troubled real estate companies, he said.
	   Property developers _ also hard-hit by a credit crunch _ have
requested a government bailout.
	   The property slump has left an estimated 800,000 housing units
vacant throughout Taiwan, idling assets that cost developers at
least 1 trillion Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs 31 billion).
	   In hopes to shore up profits, property developers have purchased
large land tracts, but many of the large-scale housing projects
were ill-devised or built in remote areas.
	   Officials said they have rejected a request by developers to set
up a government fund to purchase the homes, saying it would
encourage them to build more.
	   Instead, they said, the government will suspend some public
housing projects, reduce real estate transfer taxes, and provide
low-interest housing loans.
	   Bankers have said they fear Taiwan's economic problems could
worsen if property prices collapse because some 40 percent of bank
loans are collateralized with real estate.
 &UR; (buros)
</TEXT>
