r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKorea-CampaignFund     12-29 0252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Campaign Fund </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top opposition leader's brother indicted for raising illegal funds
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Prosecutors indicted the brother of
the head of South Korea's largest opposition party Tuesday on
charges of raising illegal political funds for him during last
year's presidential election campaign.
	   Lee Hoi-sung, 54, an advisor to a government-funded energy
research center, was accused of collecting 15 billion won (dlrs
12.5 million) for his brother, Lee Hoi-chang, 62, then the ruling
party's presidential candidate.
	   Prosecutors said the younger Lee colluded with top national tax
officials to pressure 25 businesses to contribute funds to his
brother's campaign.
	   Under South Korean law, all political contributions should be
made through official party channels or a neutral election
management committee.
	   In the Dec. 18 election, Lee Hoi-chang lost to opposition
candidate Kim Dae-jung by a narrow margin. It marked the first
transfer of power from a ruling party to an opposition party in
South Korean history.
	   The opposition leader and his brother have denied involvement in
the scheme, but prosecutors said they have enough evidence to
incriminate them.
	   Prosecutors said the tax officials gave tax cuts and other
favors to companies that contributed to Lee's campaign.
	   After the new government was installed early this year, Lim
Chae-ju, then head of the National Tax Office, was arrested for
alleged involvement in the illegal fund raising. 	   
</TEXT>
