<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Spy Agency, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korean parliament approves new name for spy agency
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CLARIFIES history of name change in 4th graf

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ The National Assembly on Tuesday
approved a new name for South Korea's spy agency, hoping the change
will help polish an image tarnished by years of human rights
abuses.
	   The new name, National Intelligence Service, will take effect as
soon as the country promulgates a law approving the name change in
mid-January.
	   Since he took office in February, President Kim Dae-jung,
himself a former dissident once kidnapped and tortured by
government agents, has been overhauling the agency, now officially
called the Agency for National Security Planning.
	   In April, the agency said it wanted to change its name to
National Intelligence Service to have ``a new beginning as an
intelligence agency trusted by the people.''
	   On Tuesday, the single-house Assembly approved the name change
with support from both the ruling and opposition parties.
	   Formerly called the Korean Central Intelligence Agency, the
organization adopted its current name in what skeptics viewed as a
cosmetic change to clean up its image following the 1979
assassination of former President Park Chung-hee by the agency's
chief.
	   The country's past military rulers used the agency to suppress
dissidents. Among its targets was President Kim, who was jailed,
tortured and kidnapped by government agents in the 1970s and 1980s.
	   Since Kim took office, two-thirds of the agency's senior
officials have been fired in a purge aimed at removing the agency
from domestic politics. Hundreds of lower-ranking agents also were
dismissed. 	   
</TEXT>
