<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Networks Fined </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anti-trust panel fines 3 Italian networks over sports broadcasts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ An anti-trust panel has levied a total of dlrs 1.5
million in fines against Italy's three largest television networks
on allegations they blocked free bidding on the rights to broadcast
sports events.
	   Monday's fines targeted state-owned RAI and private media groups
Cecchi Gori and Reti Televisive Italiane. RTI, the nation's largest
private television company, is controlled by media magnate and
opposition leader Silvio Berlusconi.
	   The anti-trust authority says RAI and RTI split the broadcast
rights to soccer matches, Formula One races and the Giro d'Italia
cycling race in 1996, shutting out Cecchi Gori.
	   In 1997, RAI., RTI and Cecchi Gori divided between them the
rights to broadcast Italian soccer matches for the next two
seasons, the panel said.
	   RAI and RTI said they would appeal. The two called the fines
unfounded, saying the 1996 accord was never carried out and that
the 1997 accord had the approval of Italy's soccer league.
	   The fines come as Italy's two, emerging pay-TV networks try to
break into the sports broadcast market, vying for the lucrative
broadcast rights to Italian soccer.
	   One, Tele Piu, is 10 percent controlled by Berlusconi's
companies; the other, Stream, is the subject of a still-pending
deal that would sell a majority stake to Rupert Murdoch's media
empire.
	   (ek) 	   
</TEXT>
