<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
England wins fourth test
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; ADDS details, quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Paceman Dean Headley destroyed
Australia's middle order to deliver England a thrilling 12-run
victory in the fourth test at the MCG on Tuesday.
	   Although Australia has retained the Ashes, England kept its
hopes alive of squaring the series being down 2-1 with one to play.
	   Australia's tail folded dramatically as the team chased 175 for
victory on the fourth afternoon, losing 7-32 after reaching 130 for
three.
	   Headley claimed a career-best 6-60 and made the decisive move
when he had Darren Lehmann, Ian Healy and Damien Fleming out in the
space of 12 balls with the total stuck on 140.
	   ``I can't believe it,'' said Headley. ``It looked like slipping
away but we did it.''
	   Steve Waugh, who scored a brilliant century in the first
innings, was stranded at the non-striker's end on 30 as Australia
lost its last three wickets for one run.
	   Darren Gough ended the match by bowling Stuart MacGill and
following up with the wicket of Glenn McGrath in the same over.
	   ``I was so excited and pleased that we'd done it after everyone
had written us off and said how bad we are,'' Gough said. ``We went
out to play positive cricket because when we do that we can beat
anyone in the world.''
	   After the first day was lost entirely to rain the other three
days were extended.
	   Australia needed 18 for victory and had three wickets in hand
when it opted to play an extra half an hour Tuesday, offered under
the rules when a result is imminent.
	   The English players clearly did not want to stay on the field,
with captain Alec Stewart arguing with the umpires, but the extra
time worked in their favor.
	   The key to England's win was the performance of its
much-maligned tail end batsmen earlier Tuesday. They carried the
score to 244 along with 60 from Graeme Hick.
	   No.11 Alan Mullally, who had five ducks from six previous test
innings this series, even helped out and riled rival paceman Glenn
McGrath by hitting him for consecutive fours in an innings of 16.
	   Australia made a poor start to its chase, losing Michael Slater
and Mark Taylor inside 11 overs while Hick dropped a chance to put
England in control when he spilled a catch from Justin Langer with
41 still on the board.
	   But Langer was removed by a brilliant catch at square leg by
Mark Ramprakash, diving away to his right, and the dismissal
appeared to galvanize the fielding team.
	   ``Throughout the series you are looking for little moments of
inspiration, things that lift everyone. I thought that catch lifted
us,'' said England coach David Lloyd.
	   ``It is a daft game but it keeps everybody going. I thought it
was a great game of cricket and at the end there are winners and
losers.''
	   Headley, whose father Ron and grandfather George Headley played
tests for the West Indies, then tore through Australia's middle
order to send England's infamous supporters, the Barmy Army,
delirious.
	   Long after stumps the traveling fans continued singing outside
the England dressingroom.
	   	   ``Who can't celebrate? We're cricketers, not footballers,'' said
Gough of planned parties ahead of the Jan. 2 fifth test.
	   ``We'll enjoy the win because it's been a great effort. We've
proved this game that we can play cricket, we just need to do it
more often.''
	   Australian captain Mark Taylor said too many of his batsmen
squandered good starts.
	   ``I thought we'd won it but we got a bit lazy. No one made a big
enough score,'' Taylor said.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
