<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Fundamentalism,0379 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Artists concerned about rising threat of fundamentalism in Indian
</HEADLINE>
subcontinent &QL; 
 &UR; By ASHOK SHARMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Militant intolerance has threatened
artistic creativity across the Indian subcontinent, actors and
artists warned Tuesday.
	   In India, Hindu militants halted the screening of a film
depicting lesbian love. In Pakistan, independent theater was
unofficially banned for two decades of military rule. In
Bangladesh, a female writer faces death threats from Islamic
extremists for promoting women's rights.
	   Nationalism, communalism, sectarianism, and totalitarianism have
been joined by a new ``ism'' in nearby Afghanistan, Talibanism,
named for the ruling extreme Islamic Taliban.
	   Fundamentalism ``poses a serious challenge to creativity in the
21st century,'' said Pakistani writer Kishwar Naheed.
	   About 200 people participated Tuesday in the session during a
five-day convention organized by Sahmat, an organization of artists
and scholars. Because of her country's rivalry with India, Naheed
said she was not given approval to attend the conference until 15
minutes before her flight left.
	   Shabana Azmi, an actress who also is a member of Parliament,
warned that Hindu nationalism has put freedom of expression and the
rule of law under a cloud.
	   Hindu activists vandalized theaters showing Azmi's latest film,
``Fire,'' the story of two unhappily married woman within a single
joint family who turn to each other for love.
	   Azmi said the top elected official of the Maharashtra state
government congratulated activists from his right-wing party who
attacked theaters screening ``Fire.'' The same government, acting
under court orders, provided her armed guards to protect her from
the extremists, she said.
	   ``Distorting facts is the hallmark of the fundamentalists,''
said Shameem Akhtar, a Bangladesh human rights activist who
complained that Muslim ideologues were becoming entrenched in the
government bureaucracy.
	   Anand Patwardhan, an Indian film maker, said the people should
take up cultural activism to counter the threat of intolerance.
``We have to keep challenging nationalism as something different
from what is perceived by the rightist forces.'' 	   
</TEXT>
