<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Loyalist forces lose fight for Sierra Leone town
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Rebel forces battling to oust
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah have taken control of the central town
of Makeni, defense force officers acknowledged Tuesday.
	   The town had been the scene of heavy fighting in recent days,
with rebel fighters battling against defense forces from a West
African coalition army.
	   The coalition force, known as ECOMOG, withdrew from Makeni in
what was called a ``tactical retreat,'' according to an ECOMOG
statement.
	   Sierra Leone's Foreign Minister Sam Banya on Monday said
virtually the entire population of several thousand people had fled
Makeni.
	   The rebel Revolutionary United Front has launched a series of
offensives in recent weeks to recapture ground lost to ECOMOG
troops earlier in the year.
	   The Nigerian-led ECOMOG force was used in February to oust from
power a military junta with ties to the RUF. The West African
intervention force has stayed on in Sierra Leone to help defend
Kabbah's elected government.
	   Earlier, rebel leaders said they had taken control of Makeni, a
strategic town in central Sierra Leone about 120 kilometers (75
miles) northeast of Freetown.
	   Diplomats from West Africa, the United States and Britain
meeting in the Ivory Coast on Monday called for more aid to help
defend Sierra Leone's embattled government.
	   Nigeria has assumed the vast majority of responsibilities for
ECOMOG, while Ghana and Guinea have also sent troops. The United
States and Britain have provided logistical support for the
regional task force.
	   Rebel units, however, claim to have closed to within 20
kilometers (12 miles) of the capital and have threatened to start
shelling the city.
	   Banya said mercenaries from Liberia, Burkina Faso and the
Ukraine were fighting alongside the rebels. That claim could not be
independently confirmed.
	   ``The rebels must cease fighting immediately, lay down their
arms and accept President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's government as the
sole legitimate government,'' the ECOWAS statement said.
	   (crm/ids) 	   
</TEXT>
