w1090 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-DissidentsSente     12-29 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents Sentenced </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two exiled dissidents sent to Chinese labor camps
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Two U.S.-based Chinese dissidents who sneaked
back into China were caught by police and sentenced without trial
to three years of forced labor, the Foreign Ministry said Tuesday.
	   The ministry's brief statement was the first official word on
the whereabouts of Zhang Lin and Wei Quanbao since they slipped
into China seven weeks ago.
	   Members of their families asked the Chinese Consulate in New
York on Monday to help locate the pair, but consular officials were
evasive, according to an account by Chinese dissidents in New York
faxed to foreign news agencies in Beijing.
	   The Foreign Ministry said police arrested Zhang and Wei in the
southern provincial capital of Guangzhou in a barber shop operating
as a front for prostitution on Nov. 12.
	   The statement said the two men confessed to hiring prostitutes
and evading border police by hiding inside a truck entering the
city of Shenzhen from Hong Kong on Nov. 11. For those alleged
crimes, police sentenced the two to three years of ``labor
reeducation.''
	   The three-year term is the maximum police are allowed to order
without a trial.
	   Zhang, 35, is a veteran democracy and labor rights campaigner.
He served two stints in prisons and labor camps for a total of five
years between 1989 and 1997 for his campaigning.
	   After his sentence ended last year, Zhang went to the United
States. Wei, 38, went to the United States in 1994. Both reportedly
have U.S. residence permits.
	   The Foreign Ministry identified Zhang and Wei as members of the
China Democratic Justice Party, ``a hostile foreign organization.''
They ``engaged in activities to oppose the Chinese government while
in the United States,'' the statement said.
	   The party was set up early this year by Wang Bingzhang, a
prominent exile, to unite dissidents overseas and in China to
challenge the ruling Communist Party. Earlier this year, the group
claimed to have 100 members in as many as 10 branches in China.
	   A Hong Kong-based group, the Information Center of Human Rights
and Democratic Movement in China, reported last week that Zhang and
Wei had renounced their ties to exile groups advocating democracy. 	   
</TEXT>
