<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tanzania-East Africa </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Regional leaders to meet to assess progress of cooperation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) _ The heads of state of the three
countries forming the East African Cooperation are scheduled to
meet Jan. 22 to review progress of the trading bloc and a request
from Rwanda to join the group, an official said Tuesday.
	   The official, a member of the EAC secretariat who asked not to
be further identified, said the meeting would deal with upgrading
the current cooperation agreement into a full-fledged treaty and
the release of the much-delayed East African passports.
	   Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda make up the EAT, which replaces the
old East African Community that collapsed in 1977, partly because
of a divergence in economic policies pursued by the three countries
and lack of adequate mechanisms to deal with problems of economic
integration.
	   In its heyday, the community had a common airlines, railway,
postal system and currency.
	   When Presidents Benjamin Mkapa, Daniel arap Moi and Yoweri
Museveni last met in April 1997, the launched the East African
Cooperation Development Strategy (1997-2000), a policy document
that lays the basis for the rapid economic integration of the
partner states.
	   The January summit is also expected to focus on the progress
made in establishing a Single Market and Investment Area for the
three member states, all of which now subscribe to pro-market,
pro-private sector and liberal economic policies.
	   Arusha in northern Tanzania is the seat of the EAC secretariat.
	   (sc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
