<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Heroin,0226 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan arrests seven alleged members of an international heroin
</HEADLINE>
smuggling ring &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistani authorities arrested seven
members of an alleged international heroin smuggling ring that sent
heroin to European countries through mail envelops, a senior
official of the anti-narcotics force said Tuesday.
	   During last 13 years, the gang smuggled around 3 tons of heroin
worth billions of rupees (dollars) in envelops that contained 5 to
10 grams or more of heroin powder, said Mukhtar Ahmed, director
general of Anti-Narcotics Task Force Sindh.
	   The arrests were made this week after several months of
investigations. The gang leader remained at large, Ahmed said.
	   Poppy is cultivated in Pakistan's northern areas bordering
Afghanistan. Most heroin manufacturing factories also operate in
the border areas of the two countries.
	   The government launched a massive crackdown on poppy fields
recently, but has been unable to destroy them completely because of
resistance from local population.
	   Ahmed said chemicals for heroin manufacturing are being smuggled
from European countries to Pakistan.
	   The government has taken strict steps to stop heroin smuggling.
It seized 175 kilograms of heroin powder and 173 ton of hashish in
1998 just in southern Sindh province, he said. 	   
</TEXT>
