<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Euro-Tietmeyer </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German bank president sees more competition with euro
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ The introduction of a single currency could create
jobs by stimulating sharper competition among European regions,
German central bank president Hans Tietmeyer said Tuesday.
	   If the 11 states adopting the euro Jan. 1 live up to the new
competition, it could very well lead to additional investment, more
dynamism _ and more jobs, he said in an interview in
DeutschlandRadio Berlin.
	   Tietmeyer also noted that with the advent of the euro, national
problems, such as unemployment, will no longer be able to be solved
through exchange rates.
	   He stressed the need for greater political cooperation among the
11 euro nations.
	   ``We need a higher degree of political cooperation on the
European level,'' Tietmeyer said. ``If everyone takes a separate
path, this could lead to conflict with supranational monetary
policy.''
