<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Hijacked Ship </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese official says hijacked ship not from Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Chinese officials were investigating a hijacked
ship found in an east China port but denied reports it was a
missing Japanese cargo vessel.
	   An official at Zhanjiagang port in Jiangsu, near Shanghai, on
Tuesday declined to provide further details about the investigation
or the ship, saying such matters were confidential.
	   The owner of the 2,600-ton Tenyu, Masumoto Kisen, said Monday
that the ship, traveling under a new name and with forged papers,
had been found in the Chinese port.
	   Company official Takeshi Masumoto said the ship found in China
was found to have the same production number as that of the Tenyu,
which disappeared in the Straits of Malacca after leaving an
Indonesian port on Sept. 27 with a cargo of aluminum.
	   The Chinese official also disputed reports that the ship was
carrying a crew of 16 Indonesians.
	   South Korean maritime police said Tuesday the Tenyu had been
piloted by a South Korean skipper, Shin Young-ju, and chief
engineer, Park Ha-joon, and was manned by a crew of 12 Chinese
sailors.
	   The whereabouts of the original crew and captain were unknown,
they said.
	   In April, Chinese authorities discovered another hijacked
vessel, the Malaysian-registered Petro Ranger, on China's Hainan
Island, and detained 12 Indonesians.
	   The circumstances of that hijacking also raised controversy,
with Chinese authorities saying the ship actually was involved in
smuggling while the Malaysian government contended the vessel had
been hijacked by Indonesians.
	   Vessels traveling through the Straits of Malacca have in recent
years fallen prey to pirates.
</TEXT>
