<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Crime </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian police look into Central Bank activities
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian police are probing the activities of the
Central Bank because of suspicions that up to dlrs 1 billion may
have been misappropriated, the government said Tuesday.
	   The probe spans Central Bank activities since 1992 when Russia
launched market reforms, Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin told a
news conference. He would not give any names or provide additional
details.
	   Sergei Tesis, the ministry's chief investigator overseeing the
probe, indicated that misappropriation of public funds might have
contributed to Russia's economic crisis _ the worst since the 1991
Soviet collapse.
	   Discussing other matters, Stepashin said there were 2.5 million
crimes in Russia this year. In 1997, the Interior Ministry
registered some 2.4 million crimes.
	   Russian police have tended to under report crime to give a
better picture of the law-and-order situation _ a practice
President Boris Yeltsin strongly condemned last week at a meeting
with Stepashin. Stepashin promised to report a realistic figure.
	   Independent analysts say the government reports just a fraction
of the number of crimes committed in Russia.
	   Stepashin said his ministry solved 250,000 economic crimes such
as embezzlement. Some 6,000 officials were caught taking bribes, he
said.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
