<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets mixed in thin trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asia's two biggest stock markets were higher
Tuesday, while smaller ones were mixed in thin holiday season
trading.
	   In Tokyo, share prices rose despite continued concerns over the
domestic political and economic situation.
	   The U.S. dollar fell against the Japanese yen as investors took
profits amid concerns over the Gulf crisis and the domestic U.S.
economy.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 137.84
points, or 1.01 percent, to close at 13,846.90.
	   The dollar bought 115.42 yen at midafternoon, down 0.70 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of
115.90 yen overnight.
	   Many Japanese institutional investors were also concerned that
America's long economic boom may be running out of steam.
	   ``The number of dollar bears who see the U.S. economy slowing
down next year is increasing among Japanese institutional investors
and interbank players,'' said Shuji Takano of ABN AMRO Bank in
Tokyo.
	   Despite thin trading, the Tokyo stock market was boosted in a
late surge on futures-led buying.
	   Most investors waited for new developments in a proposed
coalition deal between Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's Liberal
Democratic Party and the opposition Liberal Party.
	   The two sides were expected to seal a pact this week that would
boost the LDP's leverage in parliament, but last-minute
disagreements stalled negotiations.
	   In Hong Kong, stocks ended slightly higher with the blue-chip
Hang Seng Index rising 55.83 points, or 0.5 percent, to close at
10,225.97.
	   Volume was thin, with some fund managers switching to other
markets in preparation for the inauguration of the single European
currency _ the euro _ on Monday, said Felix Ngai of Sun Hung Kai
Commodities Ltd.
	   ELSEWHERE:
	   BANGKOK: Shares fell amid retail selling in financial stocks.
The SET index fell 8.48 points, or 2.3 percent, to 351.81.
	   JAKARTA: Shares fell with no new leads to reverse the selling
pressure. The JSX Composite Index was down 3.443 points, or 0.90
percent, to close at 396.733.
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose as retail investors and local
institutions kept buying. The Composite Index was up 10.09 points,
or 1.8 percent, to close at 566.23.
	   MANILA: Shares rose in late buying, particularly in blue-chip
stocks. The PSE index soared 35.84 points, or 1.9 percent, to
1,968.78.
	   TAIPEI: Shares fell to a near four-month low on worries over the
country's poor economic fundamentals. The Weighted Price Index was
down 3.38 points, or 0.05 percent, to 6,478.27.
	   SINGAPORE: Shares dipped slightly in narrow trading. The STI was
down 2.82 points, or 0.20 percent, to close at 1,378.45.
	   SYDNEY: Shares rose with many participants still away for the
holidays. The All Ordinaries index was up 4.4 points, or 0.2
percent, to close at 2,768.4.
	   WELLINGTON: Shares fell as investors cashed in on market gains.
The NZSE-40 index was down 13.07 points, or 0.6 percent, to close
at 2,110.34.
	   SEOUL: Markets were closed for the holidays.
</TEXT>
