<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Yachting-Sydney-Hobart-Doomed Yacht, 2nd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Skipper vows to never sail again
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES throughout with official line of 4 dead, two missing
presumed drowned. ADDS details on dead sailor Jim Lawler &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MERIMBULA, Australia (AP) _ The skipper of sunk Sydney-Hobart
yacht Winston Churchill vowed Tuesday never to race again after the
deaths of his close friends.
	   ``I personally won't (race); my decision's pretty well made up
in that direction,'' the boat's owner and skipper Richard Winning
said.
	   The 56-year-old Winston Churchill, an entrant in the inaugural
1945 Sydney-Hobart classic, was abandoned on Sunday night and the
nine crew climbed into two life rafts.
	   Winning and three crewmates Paul Lumtin, Bruce Gould and Michael
Rynan on Monday night were winched to safety after 24 hours in a
life raft in huge Bass Strait seas.
	   On Tuesday they were told that two of their fellow yachtsmen Jim
Lawler and Mike Bannister were dead and another, John Dean, is
presumed drowned.
	   Winning said he had no doubt after their life raft was spotted
on Monday night by rescuers that all in the second craft would
survive.
	   ``When I went to bed I thought these blokes would be here
tonight, if not tomorrow morning,'' he said. ``Two of them have
been my mates since I was a young fella.
	   ``That's Michael Bannister and John Dean. I've been sailing with
those guys since I was a young child. It's shocking to lose your
mates like this.''
	   The wooden-hulled Winston Churchill, built in 1942 and competing
in the Sydney-Hobart race for the 16th time, was restored by
Winning about two years ago.
	   Lawler, a 58-year-old grandfather and ocean racing veteran, was
familiar with extreme and sometimes treacherous conditions in the
Sydney-to-Hobart race. having sailed it 17 rtimes by his family's
count.
	   In the 1993 race, when giant seas battered the fleet off the NSW
south coast, Mr Lawler took shelter until the storm eased then
sailed on in his own yacht, Charisma.
	   ``He took his boat to Eden to shelter from the storm and stayed
there for a couple of hours and then won a place in his division,''
said Robert Brenac, a former sailing secretary with the Cruising
Yacht Club of Australia, today.
	   Lawler's family issued a statement paying tribute to those
involved in the search and rescue epic.
	   ``Our prayers and thoughts go out to those who have lost loved
ones, and we thank the many people who have offered support to us
at this difficult time,'' the statement said. ``Jim Lawler was
truly a man of the sea.''
 &UR; (djp-tjh)
</TEXT>
