w1156 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin vows that Russia will continue reforms
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with ex-official giving economic forecast for next
year, default on foreign debt looming, other details, context in
new grafs 9-17. ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin pledged Tuesday that the
government won't backtrack on democratic and market reforms even
though Russia is mired in the worst economic crisis since the end
of the Soviet era.
	   ``There is no other path for Russia than toward democracy,''
Yeltsin said in a letter published in the business daily
Kommersant.
	   Yeltsin has said little and done even less to address the
economic crisis, leaving day-to-day management of the economy to
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
	   Primakov has said that Russia should continue the market
reforms, but put an end to ``wild'' capitalism by strengthening
state regulation of the economy.
	   Critics say that the government, struggling to pay off domestic
and foreign debts, is likely to print a huge amount of new cash,
leading to the kind of high inflation that has plagued Russia in
the past.
	   Many fear that hyperinflation would push Russia toward
Soviet-style price and currency controls and rationing.
	   Yeltsin said he would not allow that.
	   ``The outgoing year 1998 wasn't the easiest for any of us, and
many people might think that the nation has reversed on its path,''
Yeltsin said. ``That isn't true. As the president of Russia, I say
that there is no way back.''
	   Since a new Cabinet was appointed in September, Primakov and
other officials have been vague about their plans to deal with the
crisis, speaking in general terms about the need for more state
controls and increased state support for domestic industries.
	   The Cabinet has given itself until April to work out a
medium-term economic plan, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported on
Tuesday.
	   Most experts have criticized next year's budget, which won a
quick initial approval by the parliament this month, as unrealistic
and dependent on foreign loans that may not materialize.
	   The International Monetary Fund and other lenders have urged
Russia to pass a realistic budget as a key condition for releasing
aid.
	   The former first deputy chief of Russia's Central Bank, Sergei
Alexashenko, dismissed government projections of an average ruble
rate of 21.5 to the U.S. dollar next year as unfeasible. He said
the ruble is likely to fall to below 40 to the dollar by the end of
next year.
	   He predicted a government plan to cut taxes would lead to a
severe shortfall in revenue, scare away the IMF and leave Russia
with no other choice but to print money to pay its debts.
	   Next year's inflation, projected at 30 percent by the
government, is likely to hover between 100 percent and 300 percent,
Alexashenko said in an interview published by the daily Kommersant
on Tuesday.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
