<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Bribes-Waugh </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Waugh seeks legal advice on bribery inquiry
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Australian cricketer Mark Waugh is
seeking independent legal advice before agreeing to appear before a
Pakistan judicial inquiry into match fixing.
	   While Waugh is seeking advice from lawyers outside the
Australian Cricket Board, leg-spinner Shane Warne and former team
manager Alan Crompton are happy to give their evidence to the
inquiry in public.
	   Waugh, Warne and Crompton will testify before the Pakistan
commission in Melbourne on Jan. 8.
	   The players were requested to provide evidence to the inquiry
after admitting taking money from an illegal Indian bookmaker for
providing information on weather and pitch conditions during
Australia's tour of Sri Lanka in 1994.
	   The bookmaker scandal involving the players has been placed on
an International Cricket Council meeting agenda for Jan. 10-11 and
a bloc of subcontinent countries _ India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka _
will lobby the ICC to slap life bans on the Australians.
	   The pair were fined by the ACB in Feb. 1995 but the action was
kept secret until three weeks ago. The ACB believes no further
action should be taken against Waugh and Warne.
	   The commission accepted an offer from Crompton, who was
Australian team manager at the time, to testify.
	   ACB lawyers Brian Ward and Co. have sent a five-page letter to
the Pakistan commission which is investigating allegations of match
fixing and bribery.
	   Waugh gave evidence to the hearing in Lahore in October during
Australia's tour of Pakistan but did not divulge his link with the
Indian bookmaker.
	   He has alleged former Pakistan captain Salim Malik offered a
bribe to throw a game during Australia's tour there in 1994.
	   Warne and former Test spinner Tim May have made similar
allegations against Malik.
	   ACB communications manager Michael Hogan said Tuesday the board
was waiting on Pakistan to reply to the five-page letter from Brian
Ward and Co.
	   In the letter, the legal firm details its instructions from ACB
chief executive Malcolm Speed.
	   ``We are further instructed by Mr Speed that both Mr Crompton
and Mr Warne are content for their evidence to be given in
public,'' the letter says.
	   ``With respect to Mr Mark Waugh, our instructions are that he is
presently obtaining independent legal advice in relation to his
availability to give evidence and whether he will seek to give
evidence in camera.''
	   Two days after Waugh, Warne and Crompton are scheduled to give
evidence to the Pakistan commission, the ICC will tackle the issue
of gambling in the sport at a meeting in Christchurch, New Zealand.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
