<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Christian Attack,0439 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hindu nationalists distance themselves from anti-missionary
</HEADLINE>
attacks &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ The governing Hindu nationalist party is
distancing itself from an anti-missionary campaign by Hindu
extremists that erupted in violence recently in western India.
However, the government said it will ensure tough action to protect
the small Christian community.
	   A Bharatiya Janata Party spokesman, K.L. Sharma, was quoted in
Indian newspapers Tuesday as condemning the recent attacks on
churches in the western state of Gujarat, although he declined to
blame any specific group. The attacks began Dec. 25.
	   In the latest incidents, Hindu radicals burned down a church
Monday and stormed three others with axes, iron rods, and hammers,
sending Christian missionaries fleeing for safety, police and
witnesses said.
	   Members of two right-wing Hindu parties blamed for most of the
violence are angered by the missionaries' efforts to convert poor,
often illiterate tribal people. They say the missionaries use the
promise of jobs to get people to convert.
	   B.P. Singh, the senior official of the Home Ministry,
responsible for law and order, said he instructed the Gujarat
government to deal sternly in any incident against Christians, and
demanded a report on the recent attacks, Press Trust of India
reported.
	   India's pro-Hindu parties have been further embarrassed by a
comment attributed to Ashok Singhal, leader of the World Hindu
Council, contending that the awarding of the Nobel Prize to
Indian-born economist Amartya Sen this year was part of a worldwide
``Christian conspiracy to propagate their religion and wipe out
Hinduism from this country.''
	   The Council, known in India as the Vishwa Hindu Parishad, was
one of two extremist groups blamed for the attacks.
	   In a speech Sunday, Singhal reportedly argued that the Nobel
laureate's assertion that literacy is essential for India's
development justified the network of Christian-sponsored schools
that often have a broad enrollment of pupils from Hindu families.
	   On Tuesday, Singhal issued a statement saying his remarks were
distorted and that he agreed ``all of society should be educated.''
	   But he again criticized what he called an attempt to convert
poor Hindus with financial inducements, and said Christians were
exaggerating the incidents to attract donations from abroad.
	   About 2 percent of India's population of nearly 1 billion people
are Christian. Although few in number, the community exerts greater
influence because its English-language private schools are in high
demand by India's elite. 	   
</TEXT>
