<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa on the verge of victory in WIndies cricket Test
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa was on the brink of
clinching the series against the West Indies, holding at 75 without
loss at lunch on the fourth day of the cricket test at Kingsmead
Tuesday.
	   Earlier, they wrapped up the West Indies innings in just four
overs and three balls.
	   Shaun Pollock moved to his third five-wicket haul of the series
as he dismissed Curtly Ambrose for five. Allan Donald bowled
Courtney Walsh for three.
	   The tourists were all out for 259, putting them just 145 ahead,
with nearly two full days left for play during the third test of
the West Indians tour.
	   South Africa started steadily and gradually increased the pace,
with Gary Kirsten undefeated on 40 and Herschelle Gibbs on 32.
	   Both looked unperturbed by anything the West Indies bowlers had
to offer, although Gibbs played a rash shot three balls before
lunch and was dropped off a skied pull shot by wicketkeeper Ridley
Jacobs off the bowling of Rawl Lewis.
	   If the South Africans are to fear anything, it is the fact that
Lewis is turning the ball prodigiously.
	   But West Indies received another blow when Walsh damaged his
hamstring running to cut off a ball in the field. It appears his
participation in the next Test is in doubt.
	   If South Africa win, they take an unbeatable 3-0 lead in the
five-test series. The next match takes place at Newlands in Cape
Town on January 2.
	   (str-pr)
