<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 6th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Khmer Rouge leaders say ``sorry,'' ask country to forget butchery
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with news conference, Khmer
Rouge leaders say ``sorry.''

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders came to
Phnom Penh on Tuesday and said they were ``sorry'' for their brutal
rule during the 1970s, asking their countrymen to ``let bygones be
bygones.''
	   Prime Minister Hun Sen met Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, part of
the inner circle of the late Pol Pot, with smiles and handshakes
after cementing their defection _ in essence, surrender _ with
public pledges not to try them for genocide.
	   At a hostile news conference later, the elderly revolutionaries
faced questions whether they felt any remorse for causing the
deaths of as many as 2 million of their countrymen. Many of the
Cambodian reporters present had lost close relatives.
	   ``Yes, sorry, very sorry,'' Khieu Samphan said, looking red and
sullen. ``We would like to apologize and ask our compatriots to
forget the past so our nation can concentrate on the future. Let
bygones be bygones.''
	   MORE 	   
