<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/29/1998 06:47:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1170 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-ChineseDisside     12-29 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Chinese Dissident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan president meets exiled Chinese dissident
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo TPE101
 &UR; By ANNIE HUANG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ President Lee Teng-hui met exiled Chinese
dissident Wei Jingsheng Tuesday in an unprecedented show of support
for the democracy movement in China and drew immediate criticism
from Beijing.
	   ``President Lee said he and Taiwanese people stand firmly behind
the mainland people and will use any methods possible to help the
mainland become democratic soon,'' Wei told a news conference
afterward. ``He made the point very clear.''
	   Lee did not give details about the promised support, but Wei
said, ``our meeting itself demonstrated cooperation.''
	   Describing Lee as a ``very moderate'' person, Wei said the two
also talked about Taiwan's transition to democracy.
	   Lee has refrained from meeting other exiled Chinese dissidents
to avoid provoking China.
	   The meeting with Wei, coming near the end of the dissident's
10-day visit, followed newspaper calls for a meeting between two
figures they called Taiwan's ``Mr. Democracy'' and China's ``human
rights fighter.''
	   In the one-hour meeting, Lee said Taiwan's profound experience
after decades of political separation from the mainland can provide
China and other Asian countries a model for democracy.
	   ``I don't agree to bloody reforms,'' a government statement
quoted Lee as saying. ``It must proceed step by step. That is also
the reason why people would pursue reforms.''
	   In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao
warned Taiwan against exploiting Wei's visit.
	   ``We are opposed to anyone, opposed to any side, using Wei
Jingsheng to achieve their own purpose. You all know what kind of
person Wei Jingsheng is,'' Zhu said.
	   Wei was released from a Chinese prison last year where he spent
much of the last 18 years after his arrest for championing
democracy.
	   Taiwan's Nationalists fled to the island in 1949 after losing a
civil war to China's Communists. China claims sovereignty over
Taiwan and considers it a rebel province to be retaken by force if
necessary.
	   Taiwan's ruling Nationalists say the island's peaceful
transition to democracy over the last decade should be a model for
China, and they say China must have democracy before it can attempt
to reunify with Taiwan.
	   Wei criticized Chinese authorities as suppressing people's
efforts to seek democracy.
	   ``If opposition parties are not allowed, democracy is false,''
he said. ``A peaceful and bloodless transition to democracy is very
important for China.''
	   While praising Taiwan for its democracy, Wei has earlier accused
Taiwanese politicians of not doing enough to help foster democracy
in China.
	   Observers said they hope Wei's visit could foster more
interaction between Chinese and Taiwanese, who have alienated
themselves from Chinese affairs in antagonism over Beijing's
diplomatic isolation of the island.
</TEXT>
