<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Property </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Residential mortgages increase in November
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ New residential mortgages jumped 48 percent in
November from October, officials said Tuesday, indicating the
property market may be headed for recovery amid a series of
interest rate cuts.
	   Hong Kong banks approved mortgages worth 14.7 billion Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.88 billion), compared with 9.9 billion Hong
Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.27 billion) in October, said a statement
from the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, the territory's de facto
central bank.
	   The actual amount home-buyers borrowed surged 61 percent in
November to 10.3 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.32 billion)
from October's 6.4 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 821
million).
	   The amount was expected to edge higher in December ``in view of
improved market conditions,'' the monetary authority said.
	   A series of recent interest rate cuts has helped lift the
market, though most economists predict prices will not rebound to
previous levels anytime soon.
	   Property values have plunged by up to 60 percent from their
peaks reached just before Asia's financial crisis started to
spread.
	   Hong Kong's once-robust economy slipped into recession and
unemployment rose to record highs.
</TEXT>
