</HEADLINE>
 &UR; PHNOM PENH: be bygones.''

<TEXT>
	   Neither accepted personal responsibility. As the half-hour news
conference at a hotel broke up, they were mobbed and demands
shouted at them to personally apologize to the families of those
who perished.
	   Khieu Samphan indicated there would be no trial, especially one
overseas by an international tribunal. The United Nations recently
sent a team of experts to weigh the possibility of such a court.
	   ``Please let the Cambodian people resolve this problem,'' Khieu
Samphan said.
	   ``As you know, Hun Sen, prime minister of the royal government,
has warmly welcomed us,'' Khieu Samphan said. ``If we have to say
who was wrong and who was right, etc., etc., we cannot have
national reconciliation. We cannot put an end to the war.''
	   Nuon Chea, asked who was to blame for the massacre of Cambodians
under Khmer Rouge rule, echoed: ``Let's consider that an old issue.
I cannot clarify that.''
	   ``We are very sorry, not just for the human lives, but also
animal lives that were lost in the war,'' Nuon Chea said.
