<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0670 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1200 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG _ Asia's two biggest stock markets were higher
Tuesday, while smaller ones were mixed in thin holiday season
trading. In Tokyo, share prices rose despite continued concerns
over the domestic political and economic situation. The U.S. dollar
fell against the Japanese yen as investors took profits amid
concerns over the Gulf crisis and the domestic U.S. economy. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 137.84 points, or
1.01 percent, to close at 13,846.90. The dollar bought 115.42 yen
at midafternoon, down 0.70 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also
below its late New York level of 115.90 yen overnight. Many
Japanese institutional investors were also concerned that America's
long economic boom may be running out of steam. (ASIAN-MARKETS)
	   BEIJING _ After years of debate and bureaucratic infighting, the
top committee of China's legislature approved Tuesday a national
law to police the country's freewheeling securities markets. The
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress adopted the
law on the last day of a six-day session. The law will take effect
July 1, 1999, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported. It said
the 12-chapter, 214-article law governs all aspects of the
securities industry, from the issue and trading of stocks to
purchases of listed companies, registration and accounts settlement
agencies, government regulatory bodies and penalties for violating
the law. The new law retains a prohibition already in force against
foreign investors buying shares in China's A-share market, Xinhua
said. Foreign investors remain limited to the smaller, less active
B-share market. (CHINA-SECURITIES LAW)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A failed Japanese lender is suspected of violating
the law by offering stock dividends this year despite being warned
by the central bank it was in deep financial trouble, a news report
said Tuesday. The Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., which was
recently nationalized after being declared insolvent, announced it
would extend 7 billion yen (dlrs 60 million) in dividends at a
shareholders meeting in June, the Yomiuri newspaper reported. The
payments came shortly after the Bank of Japan had informed LTCB
that 70 percent of its 2.79 trillion yen (dlrs 24 billion) in loans
to affiliates had gone sour, placing the bank in danger of
collapsing, said the Yomiuri, Japan's largest daily. (JAPAN-ILLEGAL
DIVIDENDS)
	   BERLIN (AP) _ The introduction of a single currency could create
jobs by stimulating sharper competition among European regions,
German central bank president Hans Tietmeyer said Tuesday. If the
11 states adopting the euro Jan. 1 live up to the new competition,
it could very well lead to additional investment, more dynamism _
and more jobs, he said in an interview in DeutschlandRadio Berlin.
Tietmeyer also noted that with the advent of the euro, national
problems, such as unemployment, will no longer be able to be solved
through exchange rates. He stressed the need for greater political
cooperation among the 11 euro nations. (GERMANY-EURO-TIETMEYER)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ U.S. financial services company American Express
Co. plans to establish a securities company in Japan next year, a
company spokesman said Tuesday. The company has applied to the
Finance Ministry for permission to set up the venture under new
rules that make it easier to launch a brokerage in Japan, said
company spokemsan Mitsuo Inagaki. American Express hopes to sell
investment funds to individual investors, but the company has not
yet decided on its range of products, Inagaki said. The move comes
as many foreign financial institutions launch or expand operations
in Japan to take advantage of the country's ``Big Bang'' financial
deregulation reforms. (ASIAN BUSINESS BRIEFS)
</TEXT>
