<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0638 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ Iraq's official media lashed out Tuesday at Arab
leaders for not supporting Saddam Hussein's government, and his
deputy prime minister criticized the Egyptian president for saying
that Iraq provoked the recent U.S.-British airstrikes. Arab leaders
must either support Iraq or risk the ``wrath'' of the Arab masses,
Iraqi newspapers said, referring to the Arab League's failure to
convene a proposed meeting of Arab foreign ministers to discuss and
condemn the Dec. 16-19 airstrikes. The attacks prompted widespread
public protests in Arab capitals. (IRAQ)
	   SYDNEY, Australia _ Authorities recovered the bodies of four
sailors and gave up hope Tuesday of finding two others after a
monstrous storm decimated the Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race, its
90-mph (145-kph) winds and 35-foot (10.5-meter) swells snapping
masts and flipping boats over. A former British Olympic sailor and
an Australian competitor were missing and presumed drowned, the
Australian Maritime Safety Authority said. The bodies of four
sailors were found over two days in one of Australia's largest
maritime rescue operations ever. The race continued, however,
finishing Tuesday morning when American Larry Ellison and his maxi
yacht Sayonara arrived in Hobart, Tasmania. southeastern coast, 250
miles (400 kilometers) south of Sydney. (AUSTRALIA-DEADLY YACHT
RACE)
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders came to Phnom
Penh on Tuesday and said they were ``sorry'' for their brutal rule
during the 1970s, asking their countrymen to ``let bygones be
bygones.'' Prime Minister Hun Sen met Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea,
part of the inner circle of the late Pol Pot, with smiles and
handshakes after cementing their defection _ in essence, surrender
_ with public pledges not to try them for genocide. At a news
conference later, the elderly revolutionaries faced questions on
whether they felt any remorse for causing the deaths of as many as
2 million of their countrymen. Many of the Cambodian reporters
present had lost close relatives. ``Yes, sorry, very sorry,'' Khieu
Samphan said, looking red and sullen. ``We would like to apologize
and ask our compatriots to forget the past so our nation can
concentrate on the future. Let bygones be bygones.''
(CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE)
	   SAN`A, Yemen _ Yemeni officials started negotiations Tuesday
with Islamic extremists for the release of 16 Western tourists as
security forces encircled the area where the militants are said to
be holding the hostages. Gov. Ahmad Ali Mohsen of Abyan province,
where the kidnappings occurred, is talking with leaders of the
Al-Fadl tribe, an official at the governor's office said. Mohsen
was accompanied by Islamic figures who are influential with the
abductors, the official said on condition of anonymity. A security
official said about 200 troops were deployed Tuesday in Abyan. The
hostages include 12 Britons, six of them women, two American women
and two Australian men. (YEMEN-KIDNAPPING)
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Rebel forces battling to oust
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah have taken control of the central town
of Makeni, defense force officers said Tuesday. Makeni, a strategic
town about 120 kilometers (75 miles) northeast of the capital,
Freetown, was the scene of recent heavy fighting. Rebel fighters
battling against defense forces from a West African coalition army
known as ECOMOG succeeded in pushing coalition forces into a
``tactical retreat,'' according to an ECOMOG statement. Sierra
Leone's Foreign Minister Sam Banya on Monday said virtually the
entire population of several thousand people fled Makeni. (SIERRA
LEONE)
