<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Netanyahu </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In campaign stop, Netanyahu strikes familiar theme: Jerusalem
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos JRL-101-104
 &UR; By MARK LAVIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who is
fighting an uphill battle to get re-elected, on Tuesday prayed at
the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site, and struck a theme that
helped him win in 1996 _ a pledge to keep Jerusalem united.
	   Netanyahu's campaign began in earnest after a parliamentary
committee on Tuesday confirmed May 17 as the date for elections,
more than a year ahead of schedule.
	   Netanyahu faces a growing field of challengers, including
members of his own Likud Party who either seek to wrest the party's
nomination from him or plan to run on their own slate.
	   In 1996, he narrowly defeated incumbent Prime Minister Shimon
Peres. The Netanyahu campaign slogan ``Peres will divide
Jerusalem'' was in part credited with giving Netanyahu his victory.
	   At the time, Netanyahu accused Peres of making too many
concessions to the Palestinians who hope to set up a future capital
in east Jerusalem, the sector Israel captured from Jordan in the
1967 Mideast war and later annexed into its capital.
	   On Tuesday, the secular Netanyahu arrived at the Wall, the last
remnant of the Jewish Temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.,
wearing a black skullcap and holding a prayer book. He caressed the
honey-colored stones and read psalms about Jerusalem.
	   In the Jewish calendar, Tuesday marks the first day of the Roman
siege of ancient Jerusalem and religious Jews observe it by fasting
from dawn to dusk.
	   ``This is an important date in Jewish history,'' Netanyahu said,
adding that since the Roman siege, Jews have been struggling to
regain control over Jerusalem and keep it united.
	   ``This is very much the struggle we are engaged in now, and I
come here to renew my strength and to draw encouragement from
generations of Jews who prayed that we would be here and that we
will stay here,'' Netanyahu said.
	   Netanyahu's trip to the Wall also appeared to be an attempt to
restore his standing among ultra-Orthodox and observant Jews who
voted solidly for him in 1996. The religious group Habad, which
actively campaigned for Netanyahu in the previous election, has
withdrawn its support, saying the prime minister had broken a
secret pledge not to transfer West Bank land to the Palestinians.
	   Some worshippers appeared annoyed rather than pleased by
Netanyahu's pilgrimage, saying the extensive security forced them
to wait for more than an hour on a fast day.
	   ``They checked my phylacteries, everything, and by the time they
were done it was almost too late to pray,'' said Yehiel Ben David,
a seminary student from Jerusalem.
	   One ultra-Orthodox Jew did not let the Netanyahu visit disrupt
his plans. He pressed a mobile phone against the Wall. On the other
end of the line were relatives from France who recited prayers.
 &UR; ml-kl	   
</TEXT>
