<SLUG> BC-France-Arc de Triomphe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Workers continue Arc de Triomphe strike, but end could be near
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Workers voted Tuesday to continue a strike at the
Arc de Triomphe, but said they hoped their labor dispute would soon
be resolved in ongoing talks.
	   About 60 employees work at the monument at the top of the
Champs-Elysees. Union officials say the staff is overworked and
that more staff must be hired. It has been closed to the public
since Saturday.
	   ``We hope to solve this tonight,'' said Francoise Pinson,
spokeswoman for the Union of Cultural Affairs Personnel, members of
which were meeting on Tuesday with Culture Ministry officials.
	   Built between 1806 and 1836 to honor Napoleon's victories, the
Arc de Triomphe draws about 1.4 million visitors a year. Winding
stairways lead up to the roof, with a view of the Paris skyline.
	   Strikes in recent weeks have also hit the Orsay, Louvre and
Grand Palais museums, with employees making similar demands for
more staff to handle larger crowds. Workers also recently went on
strike at the Eiffel Tower.
	   (parf-ip)
</TEXT>
