<SLUG> BC-Greece-Cyprus, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greek, Greek-Cypriot leaders hold crucial talks on missiles
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout to LEAD with Clerides leaving for Nicosia,
missile announcement expected there. ADDS byline. Minor editing. &QL; 
 &UR; By ELENA BECATOROS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Greeks and their Cypriot allies held
crucial talks Tuesday aimed at defusing a political crisis from
Cyprus' decision to deploy Russian-made missiles.
	   Speculation has increased that the S-300 anti-aircraft missiles
will be diverted from Cyprus to the southern Greek island of Crete.
	   But both Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Greek Premier
Costas Simitis gave nothing away after their meeting, which was
also attended by the Greek defense and foreign ministers.
	   Clerides headed straight for the airport to return to Nicosia in
time for a meeting of the policy-making Greek Cypriot National
Council scheduled for later in the day.
	   An announcement on the future of the missiles was expected to be
made by Clerides after the National Council meeting.
	   Diverting the missiles to Crete could defuse tensions with
Turkey, which has threatened military action to stop the missiles'
deployment on war-divided Cyprus.
	   The United States and NATO have criticized Clerides' decision
two years ago to purchase the missiles, fearing conflict between
NATO members Turkey and Greece. Athens has a defense pact with the
Greek Cypriots.
	   Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and a Turkish-occupied north since 1974 when Turkey invaded after a
short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
	   The missiles issue has also caused political tensions in Cyprus,
where the outcome of Tuesday's meeting could affect the survival of
Clerides' government.
	   The Socialist EDEK party, which holds the ministries of defense
and education, has warned it will withdraw from the government if
the missiles are not deployed as planned.
	   Other opposition parties maintain Clerides should resign,
following his promise to do so if the missiles fail to arrive.
	   The Cypriot president had said previously that he would agree to
cancel the missiles' deployment only if Turkey accepted his
demilitarization proposal, or if there was progress in the
U.N.-sponsored talks for the reunification of the island.
	   A U.N. Security Council resolution adopted unanimously last week
called for a reduction of weapons and troops in Cyprus and the
resumption of the talks.
	   (eb-bm)
</TEXT>
