u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Saudi-Budget     12-29 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Papers: Saudi budget deficit realistic, reflects global oil crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ Saudi Arabia's projected 1999 budget
deficit of 44 billion riyals (dlrs 11.73 billion) is realistic and
reflects the ongoing oil crisis in world markets, Saudi newspapers
said Tuesday.
	   ``The budget, by all standards, is progressive and can be
considered as a step forward in the challenging path of the
economic conditions which we hope are temporary,'' the daily
al-Jazeera said.
	   Saudi newspaper usually reflect the government's political and
economic policies.
	   On Monday, Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil producer and
exporter, announced that its budget deficit in 1998 expanded 155.5
percent to 46 billion riyals (dlrs 12.26 billion), from an original
forecast of 18 billion riyals (dlrs 4.8 billion).
	   Acknowledging that the falling oil prices _ the lowest in more
than a decade _ will continue to take their toll on the economy,
the government said that 1999's projected budget deficit will be 44
billion riyals (dlrs 11.73 billion), 4.3 percent lower than 1998.
	   More than 80 percent of the government revenues come from oil
exports and the gloomy forecast for 1999 indicates that Saudi
officials do not expect significant rise in oil prices in the
coming year.
	   Both 1998 and 1999 deficit are the widest budget gaps in recent
years.
	   The Saudi fiscal year begins Jan. 1.
	   The 1999 budget forecast expenditures at 165 billion riyals
(dlrs 44 billion), down 12.7 percent from 1998's actual spending of
189 billion riyals (dlrs 50.4 billion).
	   The 1998 expenditures figure showed the government managed to
cut spending by only 3.5 percent from the projected spending of 196
billion riyals (dlrs 52.26 billion).
	   The budget plan projects the total revenues of 1999 at 121
billion riyals (dlrs 32.2 billion), 15 percent lower than actual
income of 143 billion riyals (dlrs 38.1 billion) in 1998.
	   Finance Minister Ibrahim al-Assaf was reported as saying that
``there is hope that circumstances will improve.''
	   ``But financial planning must reflect the current conditions,''
the daily Al-Eqtissadiyah quoted him as saying.
	   However, the budget statement did not say which oil price level
the government is expecting in 1999.
	   Saudi Arabia's current oil output quota is around 8 million
barrels a day, but the Saudi oil is selling for less than dlrs 10 a
barrel, compared with dlrs 14.5 at the beginning of the year.
	   The oil sector plunged 34.8 percent in 1998 because of the
prices fall, but most of other sectors are showing positive signs,
the budget statement said.
	   The government is expected to continue financing the budget
deficit through borrowing from the local market, in which it offers
a weekly 2-billion riyals (dlrs 533 million) treasury bills issue.
 &UR; str-ti/vj
</TEXT>
