w1218 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Jordan-Iraq     12-29 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Iraq,0414 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jordanian pharmacists' group plans to defy sanctions on Iraq
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHN HALABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The main pharmacists' group in Jordan
pledged Tuesday to ship drugs and medical equipment to Iraq in
defiance of U.N. sanctions.
	   The Jordanian Pharmacists Association, whose members own 1,600
pharmacies and 12 drug factories, will dispatch trucks to Iraq next
Monday carrying ``large shipments,'' said the group's chairman, Dr.
Abdul Rahim Issa.
	   Issa, however, acknowledged that Jordanian authorities may
prevent the trucks from crossing the border into Iraq. If that
happens, the trucks ``will turn back,'' he said.
	   Jordanian government officials were not immediately available
for comment.
	   U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait
ban it from importing or exporting most goods. Humanitarian items
such as food and medicine are allowed, but every sale has to be
approved by a U.N. sanctions committee. The committee's job is to
ensure that seemingly harmless exports to Iraq cannot be used in
its weapons industries.
	   Issa said the association has decided to sell its drugs in Iraq,
at low prices, without ``obtaining approval from the U.N. Sanctions
Committee.''
	   He said the association has asked all drug stores, factories,
and medical equipment shops in Jordan to contribute for the
shipments.
	   ``We have taken this action to support and back the Iraqi
people, who have suffered the unjust embargo for eight years,'' he
said.
	   Issa called upon other business associations in Jordan and other
Arab countries to defy the embargo.
	   On Monday, the association began a boycott of American and
British drugs and medical equipment to protest against U.S.-British
airstrikes on Iraq from Dec. 16 to Dec. 19.
	   Meanwhile, Egyptian newspapers reported Tuesday that the
Egyptian Pharmacists Syndicate has decided to boycott some 74
widely used American and British medicines, and instructed its
members to sell locally made alternatives.
	   The syndicate said it is considering widening the boycott to
include more drugs.
	   The airstrikes on Iraq followed a complaint by U.N. weapons
inspectors that Iraq is hindering their mission to dismantle the
country's weapons of mass destruction.
	   Until the U.N. inspectors certify that Iraq is free of nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons and long-range missiles, the United
Nations cannot lift the trade sanctions.
</TEXT>
