<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Belarus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: Russia, Belarus to introduce single currency, budget in
</HEADLINE>
2000 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia and Belarus will merge closer by
introducing a single currency and a joint budget in 2000, a top
Russian official said Tuesday.
	   But each country will also preserve its own, national budget,
said First Deputy Prime Minister Vadim Gustov, without explaining
how the new currency would work or to what extent funds would be
shared between the two nations.
	   Presidents Boris Yeltsin of Russian and Alexander Lukashenko of
Belarus signed an agreement last week calling for a merger of the
two former Soviet republics as early as next year with a single
currency and harmonized taxes.
	   But no definite schedule has been set, and officials have talked
about holding a referendum on the plan.
	   Russia's economy is gripped by its worst crisis since the Soviet
collapse, but Belarus is in an even worse shape, with virtually all
assets and markets under government control.
	   Soviet-style economic management by the authoritarian Lukashenko
has led to major food shortages in the republic. Rationing cards
have been introduced in many regions, and long lines form in stores
for basic goods.
	   The introduction of a single currency may mean that Belarus
would be able to print the money _ and Belarus would be likely to
do it with relish.
	   Lukashenko's government printed money on a grand scale in the
past, creating soaring inflation. Russia has so far tried to limit
money printing to solve its economic problems.
	   Gustov stressed Tuesday that rules still need to be worked out
to regulate the countries' rights to print the joint currency, the
Interfax news agency reported.
	   Lukashenko, a admirer of the Soviet Union, has long pushed for
uniting his nation of 10 million people with Russia's 147 million
people. In 1996, he and Yeltsin signed a union agreement, boosting
political, economic and military ties between the two nations, but
stopping short of creating one state.
	   Belarus relies on Russia's energy resources and has run up a
huge debt, and Lukashenko wants a merger to solve Belarus' economic
problems.
	   But many believe that the main motive behind Lukashenko's drive
for union is his ambition to run for the Russian presidency.
	   The West and Russian liberals assail Lukashenko for his
crackdown on the opposition and the independent media. The
eccentric president also likes to defy western democracies, and
accuse them of unspecified plots against him.
	   Meanwhile, Russia's deputy minister for relations with former
Soviet republics, Igor Savelsky, said Tuesday that Russian nuclear
weapons will not be placed on the territory of Belarus.
	   After the 1991 Soviet collapse, Belarus got rid of the nuclear
weapons it inherited from the Soviet Union.
	   (ad/ren)
</TEXT>
