<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Shooting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish Cypriots accuse Greek side of firing shots at dividing
</HEADLINE>
line &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ Turkish Cypriot authorities accused the
Greek side Tuesday of opening fire at the dividing line that
separates rival Turkish and Greek sectors of the Mediterranean
island of Cyprus.
	   The shots were fired at Turkish Cypriot security forces from a
car traveling along the road between the Turkish sector and the
British base of Dhekelia, Turkey's Anatolia news service said.
	   There were no injuries.
	   Turkish Cypriot authorities did not return fire. They protested
to U.N. and British officials who monitor the buffer zone, warning
they would respond to such attacks in the future.
	   Tuesday's shooting was the fifth in a series of similar
incidents over the past few months at the U.N.-patrolled buffer
zone, according to Turkish Cypriots, who have demanded increased
security measures at the dividing line.
	   Cyprus has been divided since 1974, when Turkey invaded the
island following a short-lived coup by supporters of union with
Greece.
	   Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in the north, some of which are
positioned only yards (meters) away from Greek Cypriot troops.
	   (ht-ek) 	   
