<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-Men-Downhill </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Maier leads Austrian sweep in fourth season downhill
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: will be UPDATED &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BORMIO, Italy (AP) _ Austrian ski superstar Hermann Maier
captured his fourth World Cup season victory in Tuesday's downhill
at Bormio as he led a 1-6 sweep by Austrian skiers in the last race
of the year.
	   Maier, the defending World Cup champion known as ``The
Herminator,'' mastered the icy and twisty Stelvio course in the
winning time of one minute, 54.51 seconds in a repeat of his last
year's triumph in this Italian alpine resort.
	   It was the 14th World Cup career victory _ the third in downhill
_ for the Austrian ace, who exploded to international fame last
season by winning the World Cup overall, Super-G and giant slalom
titles and two Olympic golds at Nagano, Japan.
	   Maier also earned Austria the first downhill victory on the
men's circuit in the fourth speed race of the 1998-99 campaign.
	   Fritz Strobl and Stephan Eberharter placed second and third
respectively, to complete the all-Austrian podium.
	   Strobl trailed Maier by 0.70 seconds. Eberharter had a gap of
1.28 seconds.
	   Three other Austrians _ Hans Knauss, Werner Franz and Hannes
Trinkl _ placed from fourth to sixth in an unprecedented 1-6 finish
in men's downhill.
	   Austrian skiers had swept the top nine places for an all-time
World Cup record at a Super-G race in Innsbruck last week.
	   Swiss Bruno Kernen, the defending world downhill champion, was
the first non-Austrian finisher in seventh place.
	   Maier, who had captured two Super-Gs and one giant slalom
earlier this season, strengthened his overall lead in the Cup
standings by pocketing 100 points, for a total of 640 after 13
events.
	   His closest rival, Norwegian Lasse Kjus, was sidelined with a
bronchitis and did not start in Bormio.
	   Kjus had dominated the two first season downhills in Val D'Isere
and Val Gardena and had placed second to Italy's Kristian Ghedina
in the third.
	   Kjetil Aandre Amodt, another leading Norwegian skier, and
injured Olympic downhill champion Jean-Luc Cretiter of France were
also missing at Bormio, the site of the 1985 world championships
which will host the world cup finals in 2000.
	   The men's World Cup continues at Kranjska Gora, Slovenia, with a
slalom and a giant slalom, on Jan. 5-6.
 &UR; (pv)
</TEXT>
