<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Settlements </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peace activists file appeal to halt settlement expansion
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Peace activists asked the Supreme Court on
Tuesday to force the government to dismantle mobile homes set up by
Jewish settlers as part of a West Bank land grab.
	   The Peace Now group and dovish legislator Dedi Zucker said they
filed the appeal after Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai ignored
repeated calls to remove 60 trailers from 10 sites in the West
Bank.
	   Mordechai's spokesman, Avi Binyahu, refused comment.
	   The mobiles homes have been set up since the October signing of
the Wye River peace agreement under which Israel was to withdraw
from 13 percent of the West Bank.
	   Settler leaders said they hoped to prevent the transfer of some
of the land by placing trailers on hilltops near settlements.
Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon has encouraged them.
	   The Wye agreement stipulates that neither side should take
unilateral action. Palestinians and Israeli peace activists claim
the settler land grabs violate the Wye accord.
	   Settlement expansion has been viewed as one of the major
obstacles in the peace process and has been criticized by the
Clinton administration.
	   Zucker, a legislator from the opposition Meretz Party, said he
was concerned that settlement activists would step up their
campaign in the months leading up to the May 17 elections.
	   In this period, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who needs
settler support to win re-election, would be unlikely to confront
potential voters by cracking down on illegal settlement.
	   The Supreme Court petition would force Mordechai to dismantle
the 60 mobile homes set up so far and prevent similar actions in
the future.
 &UR; dk-kl
</TEXT>
