<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Fascism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Roman-catholic priest celebrates Mass for Croatia's WW II fascist
</HEADLINE>
leader &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ More then 100 people attended a memorial
Mass for Croatia's World War II fascist leader on the 39th
anniversary of his death, the daily Novi list reported.
	   Ante Pavelic headed a Nazi puppet state that murdered hundreds
of thousands of people, mostly Serbs, Jews and Gypsies, but also
Croats opposing his Nazi-style regime.
	   He died and was buried in Madrid, Spain, in December of 1959.
	   Three right-wing parliamentarians attended Monday's Mass, Novi
list reported.
	   President Franjo Tudjman, who steered Croatia to independence
after it broke away from Yugoslavia in 1991, himself is also often
accused by critics of cultivating nationalism that harks back to
the World War II state. He has repeatedly declared that wartime
Croatia was not simply a fascist state, but also an expression of
Croat desire for independence.
	   Croatian nationalists _ the Ustasha _ ran 28 death camps during
their rule between 1941 and 1945. Dinko Sakic, a commander of
Jasenovac, the most infamous of the camps, was indicted for war
crimes earlier this month, half a year after he was extradited from
Argentina.
	   His wife Nada-Esperanza, who was extradited a few months later,
also faces war crimes charges.
	   (dl/gj)
</TEXT>
