<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 7th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Khmer Rouge leaders say ``sorry,'' ask country to forget butchery
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES pvs, minor editing, changes byline, restores photo
number
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders came to
Phnom Penh on Tuesday and said they were ``sorry'' for their brutal
rule during the 1970s, but asked their countrymen to ``let bygones
be bygones.''
	   Prime Minister Hun Sen met Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, part of
the inner circle of the late Pol Pot, with smiles and handshakes
after cementing their defection _ in essence, surrender _ with
public pledges not to try them for genocide.
	   At a hostile news conference later, the elderly revolutionaries
faced questions whether they felt any remorse for causing the
deaths of as many as 2 million of their countrymen.
	   Many of the Cambodian reporters present lost close relatives
under the Khmer Rouge. With a trial ruled out, the Khmer Rouge
leaders may never again face such a critical audience.
	   ``Yes, sorry, very sorry,'' Khieu Samphan said, looking red and
sullen. ``We would like to apologize and ask our compatriots to
forget the past so our nation can concentrate on the future. Let
bygones be bygones.''
	   The Maoist revolutionaries won a civil war in 1975 and forced
the population into slave labor camps. About one Cambodian in five
perished from overwork, starvation, disease and executions.
	   Khieu Samphan was the nominal leader, though he is generally
viewed as a front-man for the notorious Pol Pot and others who held
real power. Nuon Chea was seen as Pol Pot's second-in-command and
chief political theorist. Pol Pot died in April of a heart attack.
	   Neither man accepted personal responsibility Tuesday. As the
half-hour news conference at a hotel broke up, they were mobbed and
demands shouted for personal apologies to the families of those who
perished.
	   Khieu Samphan indicated there would be no trial, especially one
abroad by an international tribunal. The United Nations recently
sent a team of experts to weigh the possibility of such a court.
	   ``Please let the Cambodian people resolve this problem,'' Khieu
Samphan said.
	   ``As you know, Hun Sen, prime minister of the royal government,
has warmly welcomed us,'' Khieu Samphan said. ``If we have to say
who was wrong and who was right, etc., etc., we cannot have
national reconciliation. We cannot put an end to the war.''
	   Nuon Chea, asked who was to blame for the massacre of Cambodians
under Khmer Rouge rule, echoed: ``Let's consider that an old issue.
I cannot clarify that.''
	   ``We are very sorry, not just for the human lives, but also
animal lives that were lost in the war,'' Nuon Chea said.
	   The pair were flown from Pailin, a former rebel stronghold, to
Hun Sen's residence on a military base near the capital.
	   Leading members of the Cambodian People's Party _ led by people
who, like Hun Sen, were once Khmer Rouge cadres before fleeing
bloody purges in the late 1970s _ joined the meeting.
	   After five hours of talks, the rebels checked in at the Phnom
Penh hotel where they were booked for the night.
	   ``This is the end of the Khmer Rouge,'' Khieu Samphan told
waiting reporters.
	   Neither looked well after months on the run while Khmer Rouge
territory fell under government control. Nuon Chea, 71, walked with
a cane. Khieu Samphan, 67, needed help up the stairs.
	   Khieu Samphan's normally white hair was dyed black in an
apparent attempt at disguise.
	   They later called on Prince Norodom Ranariddh, president of the
National Assembly and son of King Norodom Sihanouk. Hun Sen says
that both have approved the defections.
	   Speaking to the British Broadcasting Corp. from Sweden, Thomas
Hammarberg, U.N. Special Representative for Human Rights in
Cambodia, said it would be `extremely sad'' if the pair were not
charged and tried for crimes against humanity.
	   In the past two years, granting pardons to Khmer Rouge leaders
ended the war and gave Cambodia new hope of rebuilding. But now,
calls are rising for someone to be held accountable.
	   Khieu Samphan said he had separated ``a long time ago'' from the
only chieftain still at large, Ta Mok, known as ``The Butcher,''
who is somewhere on the Thai border with perhaps 100 loyalists.
	   Hun Sen defied international pressure Monday and said the men
would not be tried, saying it would revive civil war.
	   It was Nuon Chea's first visit to the capital since the Khmer
Rouge were overthrown in 1979 by a Vietnamese invasion.
	   Khieu Samphan came to Phnom Penh in 1991 after a peace treaty _
later broken by the Khmer Rouge _ was signed. He was stoned by a
Hun Sen-controlled mob. 	   
</TEXT>
