w1251 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Greece-Bombs 2ndLd-Writethru   12-29 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Bombs, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bombs explode outside American Express, Barclays banks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with newspaper saying anonymous
caller claimed attack was anti-NATO, EU, US. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo Available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) _ Two time bombs exploded early Tuesday
outside bank branches of American Express and Barclays in Greece's
main port, causing damage but no injuries, police said.
	   The dynamite bombs exploded within six minutes of each other,
shortly after police received a warning from an anonymous caller
claiming to represent the little-known group Revolutionary Cells.
	   The daily newspaper Eleftherotypia said an anonymous caller to
its offices claimed the attacks were carried out as ``resistance to
the criminal NATO alliance.''
	   The caller also criticized the European Union and the United
States, adding that the attack was also a form of ``resistance to
... capitalist dictatorship,'' Eleftherotypia said.
	   Barclays bank sustained significant damage from the blast.
Windows were also shattered in nearby buildings and seven cars
parked nearby were also damaged, police said.
	   The American Express branch, located about 500 meters (547
yards) away, suffered less damage, mainly broken windows, said
authorities in Piraeus, about 10 kilometers (six miles) south of
central Athens.
	   In June, the Revolutionary Cells claimed responsibility for a
bomb blast outside the Athens offices of a government agency
responsible for hiring civil servants. Two police officers had been
slightly injured in that attack.
	   A number of small but prolific terrorist groups have carried out
more than 150 attacks in Greece this year, mostly firebombs against
offices and cars belonging to government officials, diplomats,
journalists and foreign companies. The attacks are usually carried
out late at night and rarely cause injury.
	   (eb-bm) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Greece-Bombs, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
