</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Court Bomb </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Treason suspect sets off device in court, escapes amid mayhem
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ A man facing treason charges threw a
court into confusion Tuesday when he exploded a small, homemade
device and then escaped in a hail of gunfire, court officials and
eyewitnesses said.
	   Peter Ategeka, who was standing in the dock with 16 other men,
rubbed the explosive device with stones until it exploded, forcing
people in the courtroom to run for cover, the eyewitnesses said.
	   ``The prosecutor had just read the charges before the explosion
went off, and we had to rush out through the windows,'' said
Abdugadir Kiragga, a reporter for the government-owned New Vision
newspaper.
	   He said two radio reporters were trampled as they tried to
escape, and magistrate Margaret Tibulya quickly left for home.
	   Court clerk Ssenaburya told The Associated Press the device was
made from the hollow metallic handle of a shaving razor which
Ategeka appeared to have filled with phosphorous filed from the
heads of matches.
	   The accused were arrested in May in Kampala and were being
charged with trying to overthrow the government of President Yoweri
Museveni. The charge carries a mandatory death sentence on
conviction.
	   Prison warders fired into the air and blocked the exits,
apparently thwarting the escape of the other 16 men in the dock.
	   Last month, a man on trial for murder attempted to strangle a
woman magistrate in the same courtroom in downtown Kampala.
	   (hw/sl)	   
</TEXT>
