<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Boxing-Veeraphol Tatsuyoshi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thailand's Veeraphol knocks out Tatsuyoshi of Japan to win WBC
</HEADLINE>
title

<TEXT>
	   OSAKA, Japan (AP) _ Veeraphol Nakonluang-Promotion of Thailand
knocked out defending champion Joichiro Tatsuyoshi of Japan in the
sixth round to win the World Boxing Council (WBC) bantamweight
title Tuesday night.
	   The knockout came at two minutes and 52 seconds into the sixth
round when Veeraphol landed a right on Tatsuyoshi's jaw following a
series of smashing blows.
	   Tatsuyoshi looked strong early in the fight, landing a series of
sharp blows against challenger Veeraphol in the second to take that
round.
	   But in the third round, the 30-year-old Veeraphol jolted
Tatsuyoshi with a sharp right blow to the face.
	   Veeraphol, WBC No. 5 contender, continued to punish Tatsuyoshi
with a series of jabs and sharp rights, before 10,000 spectators at
Osaka Municipal Central Gymnasium in Osaka, western Japan.
	   In the sixth round, Veeraphol knocked Tatsuyoshi down for the
first time in the fight with a straight left to his face.
	   When Tatsuyoshi got up, Veeraphol ended the battle with a series
of smashing left and right straight blows. Tatsuyoshi fell backward
to the floor and lay for about a minute before trainers and doctors
revived him.
	   ``I am very pleased,'' Veeraphol said of his victory.
	   Up until the fifth round, Tatsuyoshi was leading 48-47 on
American judge Gale Van Hoy's scorecard.
	   Veeraphol was ahead 49-46 on American judge Marty Sammon's card
and 48-47 on Mexican Ray Solis' card.
	   Tatsuyoshi was making his third defense of the title he won from
Thailand's Sirimongkol Nakornthorn-Parkview in November 1997.
	   It was Veeraphol's 21st victory, including 15 knockouts and one
defeat.
	   Tatsuyoshi, whose career has been threatened by a retina injury,
now has 17 victories, including 12 knockouts, against five defeats
and one draw.
	   Both Tatsuyoshi and Veerapol weighed 53.5 kilograms (118
pounds).
 &UR; (sk) 	   
</TEXT>
