<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Loyalist forces lose fight for Sierra Leone town
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments on ECOMOG's primary focus to defend
Freetown; ADDS quote from Ghanaian defense official. Minor edits.
No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Rebel forces battling to oust
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah have taken control of the central town
of Makeni, defense force officers said Tuesday.
	   Makeni, a strategic town about 120 kilometers (75 miles)
northeast of the capital, Freetown, was the scene of recent heavy
fighting.
	   Rebel fighters battling against a West African coalition army
known as ECOMOG succeeded in pushing the defense force into a
``tactical retreat,'' according to an ECOMOG statement.
	   Sierra Leone's Foreign Minister Sam Banya on Monday said
virtually the entire population of several thousand people fled
Makeni.
	   The rebel Revolutionary United Front has launched a series of
offensives in recent weeks to recapture ground lost to Nigerian-led
ECOMOG troops earlier in the year, when the coalition force ousted
from power a military junta with ties to the RUF in February.
	   The West African intervention force fighting under the banner of
the Economic Community of West African States has stayed on in
Sierra Leone to help defend Kabbah's elected government.
	   ECOMOG troops, including fresh reinforcements from Ghana are now
focused on defending the capital, a senior official from Ghana
said.
	   ``We have sent some men and officers to help beef up what is
already on the ground,'' said the senior Ghanaian defense ministry
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Ghana, a member nation in the ECOWAS bloc, is considering
additional support for the Sierra Leone operation.
	   Nigeria, meanwhile, sent an additional 1,000 soldiers to back up
their positions in Freetown.
	   Diplomats from West Africa, the United States and Britain
meeting Monday in the Ivory Coast called for more aid to help
defend Sierra Leone's embattled government.
	   Nigeria has assumed the vast majority of responsibilities for
ECOMOG, along with Ghana and Guinea. The United States and Britain
have provided logistical support for the regional task force.
	   Rebel units, however, claim to have closed to within 20
kilometers (12 miles) of the capital and have threatened to start
shelling the city.
	   Banya said mercenaries from Liberia, Burkina Faso and the
Ukraine were fighting alongside the rebels. That claim could not be
independently confirmed.
	   ``The rebels must cease fighting immediately, lay down their
arms and accept President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's government as the
sole legitimate government,'' the ECOWAS statement said.
	   (var/ids) 	   
</TEXT>
