w1286 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ethiopia-OAU-Terroris     12-29 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-OAU-Terrorism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAU calls for concerted action to combat scourges of terrorism
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ International action is needed to
combat the scourge of terrorism, the head of the Organization of
African Unity has warned, citing the U.S. embassy bombings earlier
this year that killed 224 people.
	   The bombings of the embassies in Kenya and Tanzania ``remind us
of the need for a decisive and concerted international response,''
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim said Monday.
	   In his New Year's message, the leader of the 52-nation group
also said 1998 was ``a very difficult and turbulent'' year for
Africa with conflicts and civil strife raging in 11 member states,
including Sierra Leone and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
	   Despite the surge of violence, a number of African countries
registered gains in gross domestic product and per capita income,
Salim said. In many countries, the private sector had emerged as a
more potent economic force, he noted.
	   ``This trend needs to be further encouraged in order to
compliment the role of the state in promoting socio-economic
development,'' Salim said.
	   Two hundred and twelve Africans and 12 Americans were killed in
the Aug. 7 bombings of the embassies in Nairobi and the Tanzanian
capital, Dar es Salaam. Nearly 5,500 people were also injured.
	   Earlier this month, the U.S. State Department offered a dlrs 5
million reward for information leading to the capture of each of
the five fugitives accused of helping set up the Tanzania bombing.
Thirteen people have been publicly named as defendants in the
attack.
	   The United States has accused exiled Saudi millionaire Osama bin
Laden of masterminding the attack. A dlrs 5 million reward also has
been offered for his capture.
	   Salim said despite setbacks, the organization would continue to
promote human rights, good governance and the culture of democracy
in the continent.
	   ``I do recognize that these efforts at inculcating a culture of
peace, tolerance and democracy in our societies are still fragile,
but what is encouraging is that there is an ardent desire and
determination to sustain and strengthen them,'' he said.
	   (aa/cn/sl)	   
</TEXT>
