<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Match Fixing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Police sergeant and seven others charged with match fixing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong's top anti-corruption agency on
Tuesday charged a police sergeant and seven others with fixing
soccer matches, government radio reported.
	   The police sergeant was also charged by the Independent
Commission Against Corruption for allegedly offering bribes to a
police superintendent and a chief inspector in return for
information on raids on bookmaking centers, Hong Kong Radio
reported.
	   The unidentified police sergeant allegedly offered up to 100,000
Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 12,820) each to the police officers,
it added.
	   All defendants were charged with operating an illegal bookmaking
center in Hong Kong to fix local and international matches from
June last year to June this year, the report added.
	   The defendants, including an assistant bank manager and four
unemployed men, were ordered to enter pleas in court next month.
Their names were not given.
	   The case followed an earlier ICAC investigation which resulted
in the prosecution of six professional players for fixing matches,
including a World Cup qualifying match against Thailand last year.
	   Top player Chan Tsz-kong was jailed for one year in July on the
match-fixing charges after he pleaded guilty to accepting 80,000
Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 10,256) in exchange for giving up two
goals against Thailand. 	   
</TEXT>
