<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa clinches cricket series against WIndies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with scores at end of match; CHANGES overline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa crushed the West Indies
by nine wickets to win the third test 75 minutes after lunch of the
fourth day at Kingsmead Tuesday.
	   The win gave them an unbeatable 3-0 lead in the five match
series.
	   West Indies failed in its batting performance _ the one area
where they could have saved the match.
	   But South African batsmen improved immensely, making it possible
for their bowling attack to twice inflict major collapses on the
brittle Caribbean line-up.
	   For two hours on Monday, with a seemingly unstoppable Brian Lara
and Shivnarine Chanderpaul, it seemed the West Indies had found
their feet and could win in Durban to keep the series alive.
	   But the brilliant catching of Herschelle Gibbs stopped Lara at
79, providing the downward turning point for the visitors. A
calamitous six wickets fell between tea and an early close on
Monday.
	   South Africa pushed ruthlessly for victory on Tuesday.
	   Guiding the home team to safety at the close were Gary Kirsten
on a really well-struck undefeated 71 and Jacques Kallis on 23.
Gibbs had been removed just one run short of his second test 50 by
Carl Hooper, who trapped him in front.
	   South Africa was already on the brink of clinching the series at
lunch time, holding at 75 without loss. The tourists were all out
for 259, putting them just 145 ahead.
	   Shaun Pollock moved to his third five-wicket haul of the series
as he dismissed Curtly Ambrose for five. Allan Donald bowled
Courtney Walsh for three.
	   South Africa started steadily and gradually increased the pace,
with Gary Kirsten undefeated on 40 and Herschelle Gibbs on 32.
	   Both looked unperturbed by anything the West Indies bowlers had
to offer, although Gibbs played a rash shot three balls and was
dropped off a skied pull shot by wicketkeeper Ridley Jacobs off the
bowling of Rawl Lewis.
	   West Indies received another blow before lunch when Walsh
damaged his hamstring running to cut off a ball in the field. It
appears his participation in the next Test is in doubt.
	   The next match takes place at Newlands in Cape Town on Jan. 2.
	   (str-pr)
</TEXT>
