<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Poll </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll indicates support slipping for Hong Kong leader
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Public support for Hong Kong's leader, Tung
Chee-hwa, has slipped to its lowest level since he took over after
the former British colony reverted to Chinese rule last July,
according to an opinion poll released Tuesday.
	   Tung's support rating fell to an average 57.6 points for 1998,
down from an average of 62.3 points last year, according to Hong
Kong University's Social Science Research Center
	   The poll was conducted through telephone interviews of more than
500 people every two weeks. It had a margin of error of 1 point, or
2 percent.
	   Tung, a former shipping magnate, took over as Chief Executive on
July 1 after the departure of Hong Kong's last British governor,
Chris Patten.
	   Tung has increasingly come under fire for not doing enough to
help Hong Kong out of its protracted economic recession.
	   Late Tuesday, the government announced that gross domestic
product fell by 7.1 percent for the three months ending Sept. 30.
Hong Kong showed its worst quarterly economic performance since
1973, the first year when officials began measuring such
statistics. 	   
</TEXT>
