<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia calls on United States, Iraq to show ``restraint''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Reacting to the latest U.S.-Iraq clash, the
Russian Foreign Ministry on Tuesday called on both sides to show
``restraint'' but stopped short of condemning the U.S. action.
	   ``It's necessary to show common sense and composure in order to
overcome the crisis,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir
Rakhmanin said at a briefing.
	   On Monday, U.S. warplanes fired missiles and precision-guided
bombs to strike an anti-aircraft site in northern Iraq that
launched three missiles at U.S. jets on patrol, the Pentagon said.
Iraq reported four soldiers killed.
	   The Pentagon says U.S. and British patrols in the ``no-fly''
zones over Iraq will continue in an atmosphere of increased tension
after the incident.
	   Rakhmanin said that the creation of ``no-fly'' zones hadn't been
authorized by the United Nations, but he steered clear of direct
criticism of the U.S. action.
	   Moscow denounced U.S. and British air raids against Iraq earlier
this month in harsh rhetoric reminiscent of the Cold War and
briefly recalled its ambassadors to Washington and London. Russian
officials have since changed their tone, stressing they want to
have good relations with the United States and Britain.
	   Moscow, which is owed billions of dollars by Iraq, has pushed
for the early lifting of the U.N. sanctions against Iraq while
urging its long-time ally to comply with the U.N. resolutions.
	   (vi/ml)
</TEXT>
