<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Synchro Diving </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Synchronized diving set for inclusion in 2000 Sydney Games
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Synchronized swimming is an Olympic event, so why
not synchronized diving?
	   Swimming's world governing body (FINA) says synchronized diving
is likely to be included on the program of the 2000 Sydney
Olympics.
	   FINA said that, upon its recommendation, Sydney organizers had
petitioned the International Olympic Committee to accept the
addition of the event.
	   The IOC executive board will announce its decision in March,
FINA said in its latest newsletter.
	   Synchronized diving, recognized since 1995, is now included in
most major international competitions, including the world
championships.
	   The event involves divers plunging into the water side by side
from either the 10-meter platform or from parallel 3-meter
springboards. The divers are judged on individual technical skills
and the ability to coordinate their movements and enter the water
together.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
