<TEXT>
	   EDITORS: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1600 GMT unless
otherwise noted:
	   PRISTINA _ With a tenuous truce apparently holding, about 100
international observers were en route Tuesday to Kosovo to shore up
efforts to minimize fighting in the province amid new NATO warnings
of possible intervention. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO.
	   WITH:
	   _ NATO-KOSOVO. NATO on Tuesday said it was ``ready to
intervene'' in Kosovo if violence intensifies in the breakaway
Serbian province and demanded Yugoslav authorities and armed ethnic
Albanians respect a ceasefire.
	   BAGHDAD _ Iraq is challenging the no-fly zones patrolled by the
United States and Britain by flying its warplanes there, Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan said Tuesday. The move came a day
after U.S. aircraft fired on an anti-aircraft battery in the
northern no-fly zone. Iraq says four soldiers were killed. IRAQ.
	   WITH:
	   _ RUSSIA-IRAQ. Reacting to the latest U.S.-Iraq clash, the
Russian Foreign Ministry on Tuesday called on both sides to show
``restraint'' but stopped short of condemning the U.S. action.
	   SAN`A, Yemen _ Security forces clashed with the abductors of 16
foreign tourists in Yemen Tuesday, an official said. He added that
there were casualties but did not specify whether any of the
hostages were killed. YEMEN-KIDNAPPING.
	   PHNOM PENH _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders came to Phnom Penh on
Tuesday and said they were ``sorry'' for their brutal rule during
the 1970s, asking their countrymen to ``let bygones be bygones.''
CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE.
	   SYDNEY _ Authorities recover bodies of four sailors and give up
hope Tuesday of finding two others after a monstrous storm
decimates the Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race. AUSTRALIA-DEADLY YACHT
RACE.
	   PIRAEUS, Greece _ Two time bombs exploded Tuesday outside bank
branches of American Express and Barclays in Greece's main port
city, causing damage but no injuries, police said. An anonymous
caller told a newspaper the attack was protesting ``the criminal
NATO alliance.'' GREECE-BOMBS.
	   ROME _ Nearly 200 illegal refugees fleeing violence or hardship
at home reached Italy's southern shores in rubber dinghies on
Tuesday, police said. Calm seas and renewed fighting in Kosovo have
brought more than 1,000 immigrants across the Adriatic in the past
week. ITALY-REFUGEE INFLUX.
	   MOSCOW _ Despite severe economic problems, Russia is still
strong enough to develop a new nuclear missile if necessary,
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said in an interview published
Tuesday. RUSSIA-MILITARY.
	   WARSAW _ With Russia and Belarus signaling a new union, Poland
finds itself once again on the border of Europe's East-West
division. POLAND-EASTERN BORDER.
	   JERUSALEM _ In a new blow to Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
his closest political ally, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, says he
does not rule out running for prime minister. Elections are
scheduled for May 17. ISRAEL-POLITICS.
	   ALSO:
	   ANGOLA-PLANE CRASH. The United Nations mission in Angola has
``clear indications'' that a U.N.-chartered cargo plane which
crashed near a war zone is mostly intact, a spokesman said Tuesday.
	   SPAIN-BASQUE GOVERNMENT. A moderate pro-Basque independence
candidate was expected to be elected premier of the new regional
government on Tuesday with the help of deputies linked to the armed
separatist group ETA.
	   CYPRUS-SHOOTING _ Turkish Cypriot authorities accused the Greek
side Tuesday of opening fire at the dividing line that separates
rival Turkish and Greek sectors of the Mediterranean island of
Cyprus.
	   GREECE-CYPRUS. Greeks and their Cypriot allies held crucial
talks Tuesday aimed at defusing a political crisis from Cyprus'
decision to deploy Russian-made missiles.
	   BOSNIA-KILLED CABBIES. Over 1,000 people, most of them Sarajevo
cab drivers, blocked the downtown streets of the Bosnian capital
Tuesday in a protest prompted by the murder of their colleague.
	   SIERRA LEONE. Rebel forces battling to oust President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah have taken control of the central town of Makeni,
defense force officers say Tuesday.
	   YOUR QUERIES: Questions and story requests to The Associated
Press are welcome. Contact your local AP bureau or the AP in London
at (44-171) 427-4152.
	   In addition to the AP Europe Advisory, the following news,
sports and financial summaries and digests move on these circuits.
	   News Digests: 2 am. CET, 9 a.m. CET, 1 p.m. CET, 8 p.m. CET
(0000 GMT, 0700 GMT, 1100 GMT, 1800 GMT)
	   News Summary: 2 p.m. CET (1200 GMT);
	   Sports: 2 a.m. CET, 2 p.m. CET (0000 GMT, 1200 GMT);
	   Financial: 2 a.m. CET, 2 p.m. CET (0000 GMT, 1200 GMT).
