w1376 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq 2ndLd-Writethru   12-29 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq defies U.S.; Claims it is flying aircraft in no-fly zones
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Combines URGENT series; minor editing throughout &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAG 101-103
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq is challenging the no-fly zones
patrolled by the United States and Britain by flying its warplanes
there, Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan said Tuesday.
	   During an interview with Associated Press Television News,
Ramadan was asked if Iraq was flying its own aircraft in the no-fly
zones. He replied: ``We are doing it right now.''
	   ``Iraqi planes in effect are flying in a normal manner in Iraqi
airspace,'' he said.
	   Ramadan's announcement came a day after U.S. planes fired on an
anti-aircraft battery in the northern no-fly zone. Iraq says four
soldiers were killed. The United States says its planes fired in
self-defense after coming under Iraqi missile attack.
	   The United States and its allies set up the no-fly zones in
northern and southern Iraq to protect Kurdish and Shiite Muslim
rebels from Saddam's forces.
	   ``The so-called air exclusion zones exist only in the sick
imagination of the British and American administrations,'' Ramadan
said.
	   The Iraqi defiance is likely to escalate its confrontation with
the United States and Britain, which bombed Iraq for four nights
between Dec. 16 and Dec. 19.
	   The airstrikes were reportedly aimed at diminishing Iraq's
ability to build weapons of mass destruction, which U.N. weapons
inspectors were trying to dismantle until they withdrew on Dec. 16
complaining of Iraqi obstruction.
	   Iraq says 62 soldiers and more than 40 civilians were killed in
the bombardment. Iraq also alleges that many civilian targets were
hit, and not just defense sites as claimed by the United States.
	   Ramadan also said that Iraq will continue firing at any aircraft
that violates its airspace.
	   ``Our resistance will continue against any penetration,'' he
said. ``The war is still on.''
	   Iraq had also claimed on Monday that its gunners shot down ``an
enemy plane.'' Washington denied the claim, saying all its planes
returned safely.
	   The Iraqi claim appeared in banner headlines in all Baghdad
newspapers Tuesday. ``An enemy plane is shot down and search is
under way for the wreckage and pilot,'' the Babil, owned by
President Saddam Hussein's oldest son, Odai, trumpeted.
	   But commentaries and editorials made no mention of the soldiers
reportedly killed in the U.S. attack.
	   The new challenge over the no-fly zone comes as Iraq is trying
to boost its support in the Arab world, where there is widespread
sympathy for Iraqi civilians suffering U.N. economic sanctions
imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   Iraqi newspapers on Tuesday hailed widespread public protests in
Arab capitals against the U.S.-British airstrikes and criticized
Arab governments, which have voiced little opposition to the
bombardment.
	   Under U.N. resolutions, the sanctions cannot be lifted until
U.N. weapons inspectors certify that Iraq is free of nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons along with long-range missiles.
	   Arab leaders must either support Iraq or risk the ``wrath'' of
the Arab masses, the newspapers said, commenting on the Arab
League's failure to convene a proposed meeting of Arab foreign
ministers to discuss and condemn the bombardment.
	   In a front-page editorial, Iraq's al-Qadissiya newspaper warned
Arab leaders that ignoring ``the snowballing Arab wrath ... will
shake the ground from under their feet.''
	   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, in one of his most forthright
comments on the crisis, said in an interview published Monday that
Saddam's rule was responsible for his country's woes.
	   ``The ruling regime (in Iraq) is the reason for all the problems
... and Egypt naturally does not support this regime,'' Mubarak was
quoted as saying by the al-Gomhuriya, an Egyptian government-owned
newspaper.
	   Mubarak, a close U.S. ally, also said that it was he who
persuaded U.S. President Bill Clinton to halt the bombardment,
whose stated aim was to diminish Iraq's ability to build weapons of
mass destruction.
	   Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz responded to Mubarak with
harsh words in an editorial he wrote for Tuesday's al-Jumhouriya,
an Iraqi government-owned newspaper.
	   ``President Mubarak assumes a role for himself which both
Washington and London have not given to him,'' Aziz wrote in the
front-page editorial.
	   ``In reality there is no noble, fair and intelligent person in
Egypt, in the Arab homeland or the whole world sharing Mr. Mubarak
in his deduction,'' Aziz wrote.
	   He said that in reality Mubarak called for a halt to the strikes
because he feared the anger in the Egyptian and Arab streets.
 &UR; lb-lm/vj
</TEXT>
