w1378 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Swimming-DrugS     12-29 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Swimming-Drug Sanctions </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuanian gets 4-year drug ban; Chilean and Brazilian get three
</HEADLINE>
months

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A Lithuanian swimmer was banned for four years,
while two South American water polo players received three-month
suspensions for drug violations.
	   Swimming's world governing body (FINA) said Giedu Rafanavicius
was handed a four-year suspension by the Lithuanian federation
after testing positive for a steroid, metandienone metabolite.
	   The suspension goes into effect from June 25, 1998, the date of
the positive test.
	   Swimming is one of the few sports which mandates a four-year
suspension for drug use. Other sports apply bans of two years or
less for steroids.
	   Meanwhile, water polo players Wilson Caldeira of Brazil and
Claudio Reginato of Chile were sanctioned by the South American
association for positive drug tests during last April's South
American Championships in Venezuela.
	   FINA said Caldeira was suspended for three months, starting
April 11, after testing positive for marijuana. The Brazilian team
was disqualified and stripped of the gold medal, with first place
awarded to the Colombian team.
	   Reginato also was suspended for three months, starting April 11,
after testing positive for the stimulants ephedrine,
pseudoephedrine, phenylpropanalomine and cathine. The Chilean team
was disqualified.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Swimming-Drug Sanctions; CT:s; 
