w1379 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-Kidnapping 1stLd-2ndAdd   12-29 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 1st Ld-2nd Add,0474 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN`A: for comment.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Earlier Tuesday, Yemeni officials began negotiations with
Islamic extremists for the release of the Western tourists while
security forces encircled the area where the militants were
believed to be holding the hostages.
	   Gov. Ahmad Ali Mohsen of Abyan province, where the kidnappings
occurred, was talking with leaders of the Al-Fadl tribe, an
official at the governor's office said. Mohsen was accompanied by
Islamic figures who are influential with the abductors, the
official said on condition of anonymity.
	   A security official said about 200 troops were deployed Tuesday
in Abyan.
	   Tribes often kidnap tourists in Yemen to gain government
concessions such as new roads, water supply or clinics. The
hostages are usually released unharmed.
	   This was the first time an abduction has been carried out by
Islamic militants. Security officials said the kidnappers belong to
Islamic Jihad, many of whose leaders fought in Afghanistan and are
believed to have connections with Egyptian Muslim radicals.
	   The kidnapping occurred Monday near the southern town of
Mawdiyah, about 200 kilometers (175 miles) south of the capital,
San`a.
	   The group is demanding the release of its leader, Saleh Haidara
al-Atwi, who was arrested two weeks ago as part of a government
crackdown on Islamic vigilantes enforcing strict Islamic rules in
southern Yemen. The kidnappers also want the release of another
leader, said security officials who did not identify him.
	   They said Islamic Jihad members flog women for ignoring the
Islamic dress code and men for selling and drinking alcohol, which
is forbidden in Islam. The group, which has no more than 200
members, also ran a military camp in southern Yemen, officials
said.
	   The kidnappers, who included 10 gunmen and eight others,
ambushed a convoy of five vehicles in which the tourists were
traveling and opened fire on a number of policemen escorting them,
officials said.
	   The gunmen threatened to kill the hostages if the police didn't
back off, said one official.
	   He said all the gunmen sported beards typical of Islamists and
had military training.
	   During the melee, the British tour leader and a Yemeni guide
escaped.
	   The Australian Embassy in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, which handles
Yemen, said a diplomat was on his way to San`a on Tuesday to try to
secure the release of the hostages.
	   In April, a British couple and their teen-age son were kidnapped
but released unharmed a month later.
	   Four Germans are also being held at present by a tribe in
northeast Yemen. The kidnappers are demanding more schools,
hospitals and telephone lines in their area.
	   Yemen was once a haven for Islamic militant fugitives from other
countries, but the government has expelled many of them. 	   
</TEXT>
