w1388 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-NisshoIwai     12-29 0212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Nissho Iwai </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nissho Iwai to slash 1,000 jobs by March 2002
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Nissho Iwai Corp., one of Japan's major general
trading companies, said Tuesday it will cut 1,000 jobs, or nearly a
quarter of its work force, by March 2002 in a sweeping
restructuring plan.
	   Nissho Iwai, Japan's sixth largest trading firm, said the plan
followed an agreement with a group of eight creditors, led by Sanwa
Bank Ltd.
	   The group has pledged to lend a total of 600 billion yen (dlrs
5.2 billion) to Nissho Iwai and the agreement will be signed early
January next year, the company said in a statement.
	   Nissho Iwai said the plan calls for reducing its assets by 1.6
trillion yen (dlrs 13.9 billion) to 3.9 trillion yen (dlrs 33.9
billion), including at overseas operations. The company will reduce
assets at the parent company alone by 800 billion yen (dlrs 7
billion) to 2.2 trillion yen (dlrs 19 billion) by March, 2002.
	   The statement said Nissho Iwai also will cut salaries for its
board members by 20 percent to 50 percent.
	   Company officials declined to discuss details of the plan
further, but Kyodo News agency said Nissho Iwai expects a net loss
of 40 billion yen (dlrs 348 million) for the current business year
ending March 31.
 &UR; (sk) 	   
</TEXT>
