r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Corruption     12-29 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China's Communist Party kicks out leader for corruption
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China's Communist Party has kicked out a
high-ranking provincial leader for corruption and ordered other
officials to draw ``bitter lessons'' from his fall from power,
official media said Tuesday.
	   Meng Qingping, a former vice governor of central Hubei province,
has been arrested, the Xinhua News Agency said. Meng, who took up
his post in 1993, is the latest high-ranking official exposed in a
five-year-old government campaign against rampant corruption.
	   Meng's alleged misdeeds date back as far as 1989, when, as vice
governor of southern Hainan province, he helped a businessman
falsify paperwork to buy land, Xinhua said.
	   In thanks, the businessman gave Meng the equivalent of U.S. dlrs
25,000 via his wife, as well as other money at Chinese New Year for
four years, Xinhua said. Meng took other gifts after he moved to
Hubei in April 1993, it said.
	   ``Meng Qingping also was morally degenerate, led a rotten life,
had promiscuous sexual relations and dallied with women,'' Xinhua
alleged.
	   Meng came from a poor family and ``it was the party that trained
him from a cowherd into a university student,'' the report said.
	   As he rose through the ranks, however, ``he relaxed the demands
on his thinking,'' associated with wealthy business people, finally
becoming a ``corrupt element,'' the report said.
	   Meng has been stripped of his Communist Party membership, it
said.
	   ``Leaders and officials at all levels must draw bitter lessons
from Meng Qingping's case,'' it said. 	   
</TEXT>
