r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge-E     12-29 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge-Evidence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No trial for Khmer Rouge leaders, but evidence is there
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ No Khmer Rouge leaders may ever face
trial, but evidence that they sanctioned torture and executions
during the group's genocidal rule is all there for any prosecutor
needing it.
	   Steven Heder, one of the world's leading experts on the Khmer
Rouge reign of terror between 1975 and 1979, showed such
documentation to reporters after Prime Minister Hun Sen dismissed
holding trials for Khmer Rouge leaders on political grounds.
	   Two former leaders, Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan, met Hun Sen in
the capital Tuesday to defect and end their role in a lost civil
war. Hun Sen has said they should not be tried in the interests of
national reconciliation.
	   The pair told reporters they were ``very sorry'' but failed to
accept responsibility for the deaths of as many as 2 million
Cambodians between 1975 and 1979.
	   Heder showed journalists reports received by Nuon Chea and Ieng
Sary, another top leader pardoned two years ago in a bid to bleed
away Khmer Rouge strength when the group was still a powerful
force.
	   The reports from their subordinates contain descriptions of
execution and torture that provide a window into the paranoia that
gripped the Khmer Rouge leaders as they purged the ranks of
suspected traitors.
	   ``It is documentation that Ieng Sary and Nuon Chea were part of
an information loop on executions,'' Heder said. ``It shows they
were aware of what was going on.''
	   One document describes the execution of an official in the
northern province of Preah Vihear on suspicion that he had ``turned
against the movement.'' The writer states the victim was believed
to be part of a group previously rounded up and exterminated.
	   Another report detailed how 20 suspects were ``beaten and
interrogated'' for suspected disloyalty.
	   Nuon Chea was regarded as the movement's political theorist and
second-in-command to supreme leader Pol Pot. Ieng Sary was a deputy
prime minister and brother-in-law of Pol Pot.
	   Evidence against Khieu Samphan, long portrayed as a moderate
intellectual, is more circumstantial, Heder has said, but shows he
built his career in the bloody purges.
	   More documentation exists in the files of a center that has
spent the past several years digging up evidence to be used in the
event any Khmer Rouge leader is ever brought to justice. 	   
</TEXT>
