w1445 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-Politics     12-29 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey's premier-designate confident he can form new government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ The independent lawmaker trying to put
together a new government for Turkey was rebuffed by a leading
center-right party Tuesday but expressed confidence he could still
piece together a governing coalition.
	   Yalim Erez is seeking backing for a multiparty coalition to lead
the country until April parliamentary elections.
	   He opened negotiations with party leaders on Monday, seeking
pledges of support that would assure his coalition the necessary
majority of votes in parliament.
	   ``I believe that after a second round of talks, I will be able
to present a Cabinet list to the president for approval next
week,'' Erez said.
	   ``I am very hopeful. I am more hopeful today than yesterday,''
he added.
	   His optimism comes despite his failure to win support from True
Path Party leader Tansu Ciller. The two have been at odds since
Erez was expelled from True Path last year for opposing Mrs.
Ciller's alliance with an Islamic party.
	   ``She said it was not possible for her party to join my
government and said I should return the mandate immediately,'' Erez
said after a short meeting with Mrs. Ciller.
	   Even without her support, Erez, who has the backing of three
other parties, appeared likely to be able to form a Cabinet.
	   The Islamic Virtue Party, the largest bloc in parliament, has
withheld immediate support for Erez but not turned him down
outright.
	   Turkey's leaders have been trying to come up with a new
government since last month, when a coalition government led by
center-right leader Mesut Yilmaz collapsed over allegations that he
rigged the sale of a bank. Yilmaz has stayed on as acting premier.
	   Veteran leftist politician Bulent Ecevit tried for three weeks
to form a governing coalition that excluded the Islamic party. He
finally gave up, unable to form a purely secular alliance of
Turkey's bickering center-left and center-right parties.
	   Erez took over efforts to form a government last week, hoping
that an independent would be better able than a partisan lawmaker
to form a broad-based coalition.
	   Unlike Ecevit, Erez was willing to negotiate with the Islamic
party.
	   (sf-ek) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Turkey-Politics; CT:i; 
