<SLUG> BC-Germany-Three Tenors-Taxes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Appeals filed in tax conviction of 'Three Tenors' promoter
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANNHEIM, Germany (AP) _ Both sides filed appeals Tuesday in the
tax evasion conviction of Matthias Hoffmann, a former concert
promoter who helped organize the ``Three Tenors'' concerts.
	   Hoffmann, 47, was convicted Dec. 22 of evading 15 million marks
(dlrs 9 million) in taxes and sentenced to five years and eight
months in prison.
	   Prosecutors had sought a sentence of seven years, while the
defense had asked for less than five.
	   Appeals were filed with the Federal Court of Justice in
Karlsruhe, but neither side would comment on them.
	   The tenors _ Luciano Pavarotti, Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo _
and soprano Montserrat Caballe were named as suspects last month
for allegedly helping Hoffmann evade taxes. They are still under
investigation.
 &UR; (pfg-gb)
</TEXT>
