w1455 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-CoalitionTalks 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Coalition Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prime minister meets with opposition leader to discuss coalition
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with Obuchi meeting Ozawa; CHANGES overline,
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ After days of haggling between party negotiators,
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi held a key meeting with an
opposition leader late Tuesday and agreed to keep working toward a
coalition government.
	   Earlier in the day, party officials said Obuchi's meeting with
Liberal Party head Ichiro Ozawa would be postponed until next year
after negotiators failed to forge an agreement over defense policy
_ the main sticking point in the talks.
	   Ozawa, who defected from the ruling Liberal Democratic Party in
1993 to form a more reform-oriented party, has long pushed for a
new interpretation of the Constitution of Japan that would allow
troops to take part more in U.N. military missions.
	   Some Liberal Democrats, however, who want to restrict troops to
non-combat operations, are worried about entering a coalition with
Ozawa.
	   Japan's decades-long inability to tackle such defense issues has
come to the forefront recently since North Korea fired a missile
over Japan in August, serving as a chilling reminder of the
nation's vulnerability to attack.
	   In the late-night meeting at the prime minister's residence,
Obuchi and Ozawa confirmed their commitment to work toward a
coalition government, both sides said.
	   But they did not fully iron out differences in policy and did
not discuss Cabinet posts, said a Liberal Party official, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
	   ``If our policies and views are not realized, then I'd like to
scrap our initial agreement,'' Ozawa told reporters.
	   Obuchi and Ozawa first signed a tentative agreement in November
to work toward a coalition government _ a critical move in the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party's efforts to gain a stable grip on
political power.
	   The ruling party lacks a majority in the upper house of
Parliament and needs support from other parties to get bills passed
at a time when public dissent is growing over the nation's ailing
economy.
	   ``We reconfirmed our commitment,'' Obuchi said. ``I hope to do
my utmost as head of the Liberal Democratic Party to carry out my
promises.''
	   Having Ozawa on board could boost market sentiments because he
is viewed as more aggressive on tax cuts and other measures to turn
around the economy.
	   Ozawa's presence could also help Japan's image at a time when
Tokyo is under serious international pressure to do more to
jump-start its economy.
	   But having a coalition partner is extremely sensitive for senior
ruling party politicians because it means fewer possible Cabinet
posts for party members.
	   The two sides have already agreed to Ozawa's proposal to reduce
Cabinet posts from 20 to 18 as part of an effort toward smaller
government.
	   Obuchi has promised a Cabinet post for Ozawa, but it is unclear
how long it will take for both sides to agree on a specific post
for Ozawa.
	   In recent weeks, politicians have criticized the Obuchi-Ozawa
agreement as merely personal and expressed doubts about a
coalition.
 &UR; (gp-yk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Japan-Coalition Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
