</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Bombs, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bombs explode outside Barclays, former American Express office
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to CLARIFY site was former American Express branch. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) _ Two time bombs exploded early Tuesday
outside a Barclays Bank branch and former American Express offices
in Greece's main port, causing damage but no injuries, police said.
	   The dynamite bombs exploded within six minutes of each other,
shortly after police received a warning from an anonymous caller
claiming to represent the little-known group Revolutionary Cells.
	   The daily newspaper Eleftherotypia said an anonymous caller to
its offices claimed the attacks were carried out as ``resistance to
the criminal NATO alliance.''
	   The caller also criticized the European Union and the United
States, adding that the attack was also a form of ``resistance to
... capitalist dictatorship,'' Eleftherotypia said.
	   Barclays bank sustained significant damage from the blast.
Windows were also shattered in nearby buildings and seven cars
parked nearby were also damaged, said authorities in Piraeus, about
10 kilometers (six miles) south of central Athens.
	   A former American Express branch, located about 500 meters (547
yards) away, was also seriously damaged.
	   American Express had moved out of the building more than two
years ago, but its sign remained outside, a company official said.
