r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Referee     12-29 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Referee Blunder </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ref admits he was wrong to expel Villa goalkeeper
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ Top referee Dermot Gallagher has
admitted he was wrong to expel Aston Villa goalkeeper Michael Oakes
on Saturday for handling the ball outside his area.
	   Oakes did handle the ball outside the penalty box when the
momentum of racing out to catch it took him over the line. But he
let go as soon as he realized he had gone too far and was amazed
when Gallagher stuck to the letter of the law and showed him the
red card in Villa's 2-1 loss at Blackburn.
	   It was a defeat that temporarily cost Villa first place in the
Premier League and manager John Gregory was furious with
Gallagher's handling of the incident.
	   Goalkeepers are expelled automatically for deliberately handling
the ball outside the area to prevent an obvious goalscoring
opportunity. This was not the case this time and Villa, hoping that
Oakes will avoid a suspension, contended that the officials were
wrong.
	   Gallagher issued the red card after consulting his linesman and,
according the Football Association, now admits they made a mistake.
	   ``Dermot Gallagher, in consultation with Philip Don, the Premier
League's referees' officer, has reviewed the video of the sending
off of Aston Villa goalkeeper Michael Oakes in the game against
Blackburn,'' said Premier League spokesman Mike Lee.
	   ``In discussion with referee's assistant (linesman) Dave
Horlick, they have concluded that there was a genuine error of
judgment by the assistant.
	   ``Mr. Gallagher will now be writing to the Football Association
to inform them of his conclusion, with a view to the sending off
not being dealt with as a disciplinary matter.''
	   Don said it was likely the FA would accept Gallagher's change of
mind.
	   ``At the end of the day we want to see the right decisions are
made and Dermot has agreed to write to the FA and inform them an
error was made,'' the former World Cup referee said.
	   ``I would now expect the FA to reverse the decision once they
receive Dermot's letter and his report.''
	   (rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
