<SLUG> BC-Sports-Nordic combined Sprint-World Cup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Manninen wins fifth Nordic combined with furious finish
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OBERWIESENTHAL, Germany (AP) _ Finland's Hannu Manninen won a
dash to the finish line Tuesday to capture his fifth World Cup race
of the season at a Nordic Combined sprint event.
	   Manninen sprinted past Norway's Kenneth Braaten in a furious
finish in the 7.5 kilometer cross-country race to win by 1.3
seconds.
	   Braaten led after the jumping, gaining 124.5 points to
Manninen's 121.5. But the Finn completed the cross-country portion
in 19 minutes, 49.7 seconds to wipe out the deficit.
	   Finland's Samppa Lajunen finished third, 34.3 seconds back.
	   Norway's double Olympic champion Bjarte-Engen Vik struggled to
sixth place, taking himself out of contention with poor jumping
that netted him just 108 points.
	   Vik failed to crack the top three for the first time this
season.
	   Manninen, 20, won the 10th World Cup event of his career and
built his lead in the overall standings out with 935 points to
Vik's 825. Austria's Felix Gottwald is a distant third with 515.
	   Manninen has reached the podium in all seven World Cup events
this season.
