<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Iraq-Kurd TV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraqi Kurds to launch Kurdish TV; broadcasts would reach Turkey
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ An Iraqi Kurdish group said Tuesday it
will launch a new Kurdish satellite television outfit whose
transmissions will also reach Turkey, where broadcasting in the
Kurdish language is banned.
	   The Kurdistan Democratic Party plans to present both cultural
and political programs in what would be the world's second Kurdish
television station.
	   The KDP controls about two-thirds of northern Iraq. The de facto
Kurdish autonomous zone has been in place there since the 1990-91
Gulf War.
	   ``We need a news alternative, other sources of information for
the Kurds,'' said Faik Nerweyi, a representative of the Kurdish
party in Ankara, Turkey's capital.
	   The channel so far has broadcast only short programs as tests
but should be ready for full broadcast soon, Nerweyi said.
	   The other satellite television broadcasting in Kurdish is the
London-based MED TV.
	   MED TV was cautioned twice this year by Britain's television
watchdog for showing bias toward the Kurdistan Workers Party, or
PKK, which has been fighting for autonomy in southeast Turkey for
more than a decade.
	   Broadcasting in Kurdish is still illegal in Turkey. Authorities
in the southeast have cracked down on satellite dish owners, whose
dishes are turned so as to receive MED TV.
	   Ankara has also been pressuring European countries to ban the
Kurdish television.
	   On Tuesday, one official dismissed the upcoming premier of the
Iraqi Kurd station.
	   ``We cannot interfere with other countries' choice of broadcast
language. It is not our concern,'' said Haldun Otman, a spokesman
of the Turkish Foreign Ministry.
	   The KDP fights alongside the Turkish army in Iraq against the
PKK rebels. However, Turkey opposes any move that might create a
Kurdish state in Iraq, fearing it would inspire the rebellion of
the PKK.
	   (ht-ek) 	   
</TEXT>
