<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Armenia-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Armenian parliament approves 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) _ The Armenian parliament approved a draft
1999 budget Tuesday that forecasts a deficit of 5.1 percent of the
gross domestic product _ or nearly one-quarter of budget spending.
	   Parliament voted 122-22 to approve the budget, which projects
spending of 248.3 billion drams (477 million dollars) and revenues
of 191.7 billion drams (dlrs 368 million).
	   Armenia plans to issue treasury bills for 3.6 billion drams
(dlrs 7 million) to cover part of the 56.6 billion drams (dlrs 110
million) deficit.
	   The rest of the deficit will be covered by international loans,
which are expected to total dlrs 112.8 million next year, with most
of the money coming from the World Bank.
	   Prime Minister Armen Darbinian said 1999 wouldn't be an easy
year.
	   He warned that ``the world financial crisis has not been
overcome yet, so it wouldn't be realistic to expect sharp economic
growth in Armenia.''
	   Unlike many other former Soviet republics, Armenia hasn't
suffered much from the economic crisis in Russia, because economic
ties between the two countries have been declining in recent years.
	   (str/ad/ml)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Armenia-Budget; CT:i; 
