<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minister: New Kuwait oil fields can be developed in five years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Kuwait's northern oil fields could be developed
and operated by interested foreign companies for about dlrs 7
billion in five years, the oil minister said in remarks published
Tuesday.
	   The minister, Sheik Saud al-Sabah, told local newspaper editors
on Monday that the operation agreements Kuwait was seeking with
American and British companies would double production from these
fields to more than 900,000 barrels a day.
	   No contracts or memorandums of understanding have yet been
signed with any companies, the minister said.
	   But the firms approached by Kuwait have reacted positively and
they believe Kuwait's proposal is ``unique,'' he added. His remarks
were reported Tuesday by the state-run Kuwait News Agency.
	   The minister stressed Kuwait's project was not a
production-sharing agreement, which is banned by the constitution.
He said foreign companies will not be allowed to own ``a single
drop,'' of Kuwaiti oil.
	   The companies will be paid fees for their services, and will buy
the oil they produce. Also, they will build a new port and a city
for their employees, Sheik Saud said.
	   Kuwait's oil sector is owned and run by the government. A number
of parliament members are worried that opening the door for foreign
companies would eventually lead to loss of control over the
country's oil, the mainstay of its economy.
	   Sheik Saud said the agreements were necessary to ``prepare for
the future,'' and benefit from technologies that are not for sale.
	   In addition to that, the development of the northern oil fields
was a ``strategic'' goal, he said. The fields are close to the
border with Iraq, which invaded Kuwait and occupied it for seven
months before a U.S.-led coalition evicted Iraqi forces in February
1991.
 &UR; de/vj
</TEXT>
