<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Violence,0440 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rioters set ablaze vehicles in Pakistani city to protest the
</HEADLINE>
demolition of shanties &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo KAR101 &QL; 
 &UR; By GHULAM HASNAIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ Armed rioters blocked roads and set
ablaze at least four vehicles Tuesday in the violence-plagued port
of Karachi in demonstrations over the government's campaign to
destroy shanties in a neighborhood dominated by militants.
	   Masked armed men also exchanged heavy gunfire with security
forces in the central Liquatabad area, but there were no immediate
reports of causalities, witnesses said.
	   The police and paramilitary rangers surrounded the troubled
neighborhood as rampaging rioters hurled gasoline bombs at
vehicles.
	   The violence was prompted by the government's efforts to destroy
what is says are shanties built without permission on
government-owned land in the nearby neighborhood of Gharibabad,
considered a stronghold of the militant ethnic Muttehida Qami
Movement (MQM).
	   The authorities have bulldozed dozens of shanties in the
low-income area, saying the structures provide shelter to
``terrorists and criminals.''
	   Also on Tuesday, Karachi police found the bullet-riddled body of
an unidentified young man, bearing marks of torture.
	   Karachi has been under direct federal rule since Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif's government dismissed the Sindh provincial government
in October, saying it failed to maintain peace in this beleaguered
city of 14 million people. About 1,000 people have died this year
in the factional fighting.
	   Sharif has blamed the MQM, a former ally, for most of the
bloodletting in Karachi and set up military courts last month to
try those accused in killings.
	   The MQM, which represents Urdu-speaking people who migrated from
British India at independence in 1947, denies the accusations and
alleges the government is engaging in ``state sponsored terrorism''
against its ethnic group.
	   The government says it has only targeted ``criminals.''
	   MQM spokesman Farooq Sattar told reporters that Tuesday's
demonstrations were a ``natural reaction'' to the razing of houses
in the Gharibabad neighborhood.
	   ``More than 300 houses have been demolished in Gharibabad
without any prior notice. These people were living there for the
last 40 years. The action is targeted only against the MQM
supporters,'' Sattar said.
	   Sattar said the action was ``undemocratic and violated basic
human rights'' and appealed to the president and army chief of the
staff to take up the issue with the government.
	   There was no immediate comment from the government.
</TEXT>
