<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Euro 2000-Action Replays </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dutch official: video refs could prevent crowd trouble
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The Dutch government wants to
study the use of instant replays to rule on controversial calls and
prevent crowd trouble during the Euro 2000 championships, an
official studying anti-hooliganism measures claimed in an article
released Tuesday.
	   ``If technology can limit the number of questionable decisions
by referees, that will lead to less emotion among supporters and
hooliganism will decline,'' said Henk Mannen, the head of a Euro
2000 team at the Dutch Ministry of Health, Welfare and Sport.
	   ``It would therefore be useful to get all those involved around
a table to discuss technological support for referees,'' he added
in the article, a copy of which was released Tuesday.
	   Many of the worst hooligan incidents at this year's World Cup
occurred before kickoff however and experts have long doubted the
influence of the match itself on soccer violence. There was
virtually no crowd trouble inside grounds during World Cup matches
in France despite a slew of controversial calls.
	   The Netherlands and Belgium are jointly hosting the 16-team
European championships from June 10 to July 2, 2000, the first time
such a major soccer tournament has been held in two countries.
Civil servants in both nations are already considering ways of
preventing crowd trouble from marring the tournament.
	   Belgium's worst hooligan incident happened at Brussels' Heysel
in 1985, when 39 fans were crushed to death, trying to escape
fighting before the European Champions' Cup final between Juventus
Turin and FC Liverpool.
	   In March 1997 an Ajax Amsterdam fan was beaten to death by
supporters of Feyenoord Rotterdam during a battle organized by the
rival fans well away from any heavily-policed soccer stadium.
	   Euro 2000 organizers are expecting 1.2 million fans to buy
tickets for the championships' 31 matches.
	   Nobody at European soccer's governing body, UEFA, was
immediately available for comment, but during the World Cup finals,
UEFA President Lennart Johansson said all available resources
should be used to get calls right.
	   ``We have to see about using modern technology in the matches,''
he said. ``We can't go too far. We don't want the referee running
to the TV screen all the time. The match would take nine hours.''
	   Sepp Blatter, the president of world soccer's ruling body FIFA,
adamantly opposes the use of instant replays.
	   (mc-rac) 	   
</TEXT>
