<SLUG> BC-Israel-Military,0351 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli general says it's `unnatural' for women to be pilots
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ An Israeli air force general told a
parliamentary committee that it was ``unnatural'' for women to be
pilots, sparking outrage among female legislators.
	   Legislator Marina Solodkin, who chairs the Committee on the
Status of Women, said Tuesday that the comments showed that the air
force has not changed its attitude toward women despite some
reforms.
	   Last year, Israel's Supreme Court ordered the air force to
change its policy of training only men as pilots and to admit women
to the course. Later this week, one of the new recruits is to
complete a combat navigation course, the first woman to reach such
an advanced stage of training.
	   The latest controversy began Monday when Brig. Gen. Gil Regev
told Solodkin's committee that women don't have the stamina to be
pilots and that the job interferes with child-rearing.
	   ``I'm concerned about the survival rate of the female
soldiers,'' Solodkin quoted Regev as saying. ``I also think it's
not natural for there to be female pilots.''
	   The army spokesman's office said Tuesday that the air force is
implementing the Supreme Court decision allowing women to train as
pilots.
	   ``On Thursday, for the first time, a female candidate will
successfully complete the course,'' the spokesman said.
	   Solodkin said the air force apparently was reluctant to change.
	   ``They show unwillingness to accept the women as equals to
men,'' Solodkin said. ``This is unprofessional because they don't
even see the advances of women in other countries in this field.''
	   In Israel, women are drafted for nearly two years while men do
three years of compulsory service. However, women mostly serve in
clerical jobs and rarely hold command positions.
	   In a landmark ruling in 1995, the Supreme Court overturned an
army policy that barred women in combat. Two years ago, the court
ordered the air force to accept women in its courses and the first
women were accepted last year.
</TEXT>
