<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0337 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prime minister meets with opposition leader to discuss coalition
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo TOK107 &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and a key opposition
leader agreed Tuesday to keep working toward a coalition
government, although they were unable to overcome differences that
still threaten to end talks.
	   Obuchi and Liberal Party leader Ichiro Ozawa tentatively agreed
in November to work toward a coalition government _ a critical move
in efforts by Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party to secure its hold
on power.
	   ``If our policies and views are not realized, then I'd like to
scrap our initial agreement,'' Ozawa told reporters after a
late-night meeting at the prime minister's residence.
	   Despite the words of warning, both sides confirmed their
commitment to keep trying. Party negotiators have been haggling for
days; their main sticking point has been defense policy.
	   Ozawa, who defected from the ruling Liberal Democratic Party in
1993 to form a more reform-oriented party, long has pushed for a
new interpretation of the constitution that would increase
participation in U.N. military missions.
	   A Liberal Party official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said after Tuesday night's meeting that policy differences remain
and that Obuchi and Ozawa did not discuss Cabinet posts. Obuchi has
promised Ozawa a Cabinet post, but it is unclear how long settling
on which one will take.
	   The ruling party lacks a majority in the upper house of
Parliament and needs support from other parties to get bills passed
at a time when public dissent is growing over the nation's ailing
economy.
	   Having Ozawa on board could give markets a lift because he is
seen as more aggressive on tax cuts and other measures aimed at
turning around the economy. Ozawa's presence also could help
Japan's image at a time when Tokyo is under international pressure
to do more to jump-start its economy. 	   
