<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslav foreign minister demands KLA be declared terrorist group
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslavia's foreign minister
demanded Tuesday that the ethnic Albanian rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army be declared a terrorist organization and its financial
resources in the West be frozen.
	   In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, a copy of
which was faxed to The Associated Press in Belgrade, Zivadin
Jovanovic said that those demands were among key conditions for
achieving peace in the southern Serbian province.
	   Jovanovic accused the KLA of abusing an October agreement
mediated by American diplomats. He claimed the KLA has carried out
1,854 ``terrorist'' attacks in 1998, including 470 attacks since
October agreement. The KLA killed 284 people this year, said
Jovanovic.
	   ``At the time, the escalation of insolent terrorist attacks, the
abuse of reduced presence of the security forces and their
restraint, the abuse of the deployment of Kosovo Verification
Mission, represent the biggest obstacle to the political, peaceful
solution,'' said Jovanovic.
	   In the lengthy letter, Jovanovic listed the weapons obtained by
the rebel Albanian fighters, including US-made large caliber sniper
rifles.
	   Accusing the KLA of links with ``organized international
terrorism,'' Jovanovic called for ``explicit condemnation'' of the
group, efficient cutting off of its resources of financing abroad,
cessation of all contacts with KLA, closing down of the KLA offices
in the West and condemnation of Albania as the groups main base.
	   (jg/reid)
</TEXT>
