r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Olympics-IOC-F     12-29 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-IOC-FIFA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Samaranch, Blatter set summit meeting for Jan. 6
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ The presidents of the IOC and
soccer's world governing body will meet next week to try to resolve
their differences on the anti-doping fight and other key issues.
	   Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the International Olympic
Committee, will meet with FIFA president Sepp Blatter at FIFA
headquarters in Zurich on Jan. 6.
	   FIFA said in a statement Tuesday that the agenda includes FIFA's
position on measures to combat doping, the structure of the soccer
tournaments at the 2000 and 2004 Olympics and the creation of a
soccer arbitration panel.
	   The IOC and FIFA, probably the two most powerful bodies in
international sport, have been at odds over the drug problem for
some time.
	   FIFA was one of three Olympic sports federations, along with
those representing tennis and cycling, which expressed reservations
to an IOC resolution on drugs last month.
	   FIFA objected to an agreement calling on all Olympic sports to
impose a minimum two-year suspension for athletes found guilty of
using steroids.
	   FIFA officials questioned whether the penalty was enforceable
and argued that not all drugs on the IOC's banned list have
performance-enhancing qualities for soccer players.
	   Under the resolution, sports which don't comply risk being
dropped from the Olympics.
	   Samaranch said last month that he was confident that FIFA would
sign up to the agreement before the Feb. 2-4 world anti-doping
summit in Lausanne, Switzerland.
	   On another issue that has divided the two organizations, FIFA
has repeatedly rebuffed Samarananch's calls for eligibility rules
for Olympic soccer to be eased or dropped altogether.
	   FIFA, intent on safeguarding the supremacy of its World Cup,
limits the Olympic tournament to players 23 or under. In Atlanta in
1996, FIFA made a slight concession by allowing teams to field
three players over 23.
	   FIFA announced earlier this month that the same rules would
apply for the 2000 Sydney Games, rejecting Samaranch's request for
teams to be allowed to field five players over 23.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
