<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-NATO Spy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former East German communists want to employ convicted spy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ A former communist mole at NATO headquarters,
convicted of spying in 1994, has been reassigned to a
minimum-security prison and may start working in politics,
officials said Tuesday.
	   Rainer Rupp, a West German codenamed Topaz by then-East German
intelligence, confessed immediately after his arrest in 1993 to
having passed on highly sensitive NATO secrets from 1977-1989.
	   He has been serving a 12-year prison term since 1994.
	   Olaf Papesch, spokesman for the Saarland state Justice Ministry,
said Rupp was moved on Monday to a minimum-security facility, which
will allow him to hold an outside job during the day.
	   He said Rupp applied for the transfer after having served a
third of his sentence and it was not opposed by state or federal
prosecutors.
	   In a newspaper interview, Rupp said he wanted to go to work as
an adviser on foreign and security affairs in parliament for the
Party of Democratic Socialism _ successor party to the East German
communists.
	   PDS spokesman Hanno Harnisch said the party liked the idea.
``We're also for it,'' he said. ``Rupp must also be reintegrated
into society.''
	   But the idea of a convicted spy working for the former
communists drew immediate criticism from Germany's conservative
Christian Democrats, with general secretary Angela Merkel saying
the PDS was trying to twist history.
	   Any attempt to compare NATO to institutions of the communist
regime is ``unanswerable historical misrepresentation,'' Merkel
said.
	   Rupp, who worked for former East German spymaster Markus Wolf,
was convicted of handing over sensitive strategy plans, codes and
military preparedness to his communist contacts when he worked at
NATO headquarters in Belgium from 1977 to 1989.
	   One of Germany's most prominent authors, Martin Walser, had
appealed for Rupp to be pardoned in a speech in October, saying
Rupp had spied because he thought he could preserve world peace.
 &UR; (gb-pfg)
</TEXT>
