w1551 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-PensionReform     12-29 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Pension Reform </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President signs new pension system into law
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BEATA PASEK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ President Aleksander Kwasniewski on
Tuesday signed into law the final part of a new pension system to
replace a communist-era program that is going broke.
	   The new system brings Poland in line with Western standards, a
condition for the government's goal of joining the European Union
early next century.
	   Pension reform is ``most urgent and necessary right now,'' Prime
Minister Jerzy Buzek said, adding that the current system would
break down in a few years.
	   Under the new system, workers' pensions are tied to years of
service and paid for by money from workers, employers and private
investment funds. The current state-subsidized system provides
meager payments not directly related to workers' contributions.
	   The new plan doesn't affect people over 50, who will continue to
get the same pension as under the old plan. Workers between ages 30
and 50 can choose between the current state program or the new one.
Workers under 30 come under the new plan.
	   Social security contributions remain at the current level _ 45
percent of the payroll, split equally between employers and
employees. The new plan also sets strict retirement age limits _ 65
for men and 60 for women _ and curtails early retirement. It takes
effect Jan. 1.
	   Mine workers held an underground protest at more than 50 coal
mines in December to oppose the new retirement ages. They demand
preserving their current right to retire after 25 years of service
with a full pension, no matter their age.
	   They contend working in dangerous conditions, such as mining,
lowers the life expectancy below the new retirement age limits.
	   Under an agreement reached last week that brought a suspension
of the mine protests, the government proposed miners would receive
so-called ``bridge'' pensions of 70 percent of their monthly wages
if they retire with 25 years of service before the legal age. They
would receive the regular full pension when they reach the legal
retirement age.
	   Miners' leaders said they must examine the deal before they
decide whether to continue the protest next month. One union called
for Kwasniewski to veto the pension reform bill.
	   (bp-tsc)
</TEXT>
