w1574 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Spain-MinisterPardone     12-29 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Minister Pardoned </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sentences suspended for officials already partially pardoned for
</HEADLINE>
anti-Basque 'dirty war' &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHANNA TUCKMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Spain's constitutional court on Tuesday
suspended the prison sentences of a former minister and his deputy,
six days after they were partially pardoned for involvement in a
``dirty war'' against Basque separatists.
	   Former Interior Minister Jose Barrionuevo and his chief of
security Rafael Vera left the Guadalajara prison, 50 kilometers (30
miles) northeast of Madrid, within two hours of the court's
decision.
	   Both Barrionuevo and Vera were sentenced in July to 10-year
terms for orchestrating the 1983 kidnapping of a French businessman
mistaken for a hitman from the armed Basque separatist group ETA.
	   The court's decision to suspend the sentences pending appeal of
the convictions was a knock-on effect of a partial pardon granted
by the conservative government of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar
on Wednesday.
	   The pardon reduced the 10-year terms to three years and a half,
and the constitutional court tends to suspend sentences of less
than five years when appeals are pending.
	   Tuesday's decision also affects three other former officials
convicted of the 1983 kidnapping that was the first action
attributed to a death squad calling itself the Anti-terrorist
Liberation Groups, or GAL.
	   Over the next four years, the GAL killed 27 people in a campaign
against ETA. Many of them were mistaken targets.
	   Revelations in the early 1990s linking the government to the
GAL, contributed to the 1996 electoral defeat of Socialist Prime
Minister Felipe Gonzalez after nearly 14 years in office.
	   Gonzalez has denied his government was involved in the GAL and
insisted that Barrionuevo and Vera are innocent victims of an
anti-Socialist conspiracy.
	   Last week's pardon granted by Gonzalez' conservative successor
had earlier prompted the prison authorities to allow the former
minister and his deputy to go home for Christmas.
	   Outside the prison gates, Barrionuevo had told a crowd of
cheering supporters that although delighted with the pardon they
would be seeking recognition of their innocence.
	   ETA has killed nearly 800 people in a 30-year-old drive for an
independent Basque homeland made up of parts of northern Spain
smaller areas of southern France.
	   A cease-fire observed by ETA since September has ushered in
hopes for a negotiated resolution of the conflict.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
