<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Crime, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian police look into Central Bank activities
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reax from former Central Bank chief, context in
new grafs 4-7, CORRECTS official's name in 3rd graf. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian police are probing the activities of the
Central Bank because of suspicions that up to dlrs 1 billion may
have been misappropriated, the government said Tuesday.
	   The probe spans Central Bank activities since 1992 when Russia
launched market reforms, Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin told a
news conference. He would not give any names or provide additional
details.
	   Saveli Tesis, the ministry's chief investigator overseeing the
probe, indicated that misappropriation of public funds might have
contributed to Russia's economic crisis _ the worst since the 1991
Soviet collapse.
	   The Former Central Bank chief Sergei Dubinin denied any
wrongdoing in an interview with the Echo Moscow radio on Tuesday.
``I'm not guilty of any wrongdoing,''he said.
	   Dubinin was ousted along with Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko
for making the Aug. 17 decision to devalue the ruble and default on
some debts that triggered Russia's worst economic crisis since the
Soviet times.
	   During the the past few months, officials have accused Dubinin
and other bank officials of spending the bank's resources on
ambitious construction projects and high salaries to themselves
instead of using them to ensure stability of the currency and
financial markets.
	   No charges have been brought.
	   Discussing other matters, Stepashin said there were 2.5 million
crimes in Russia this year. In 1997, the Interior Ministry
registered some 2.4 million crimes.
	   Russian police have tended to underreport crime to give a better
picture of the law-and-order situation _ a practice President Boris
Yeltsin strongly condemned last week at a meeting with Stepashin.
Stepashin promised to report a realistic figure.
	   Independent analysts say the government reports just a fraction
of the number of crimes committed in Russia.
	   Stepashin said his ministry solved 250,000 economic crimes such
as embezzlement. Some 6,000 officials were caught taking bribes, he
said.
	   (vi/ml)
</TEXT>
