w1592 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Skiing-Cretier     12-29 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-Cretier </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian organizers say they're not worried by lawsuit threat from
</HEADLINE>
Cretier &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VAL GARDENA, Italy (AP) _ Italian organizers insisted Tuesday
they were not responsible for the season-ending knee injury
suffered by Olympic downhill champion Jean-Luc Cretier during a
World Cup race in Val Gardena.
	   They said they were not overly worried about a threatened
lawsuit by the French skier.
	   Cretier, who won the Olympic title in Nagano this year, tore his
left knee ligaments and fractured his left hand following a
high-speed fall in the Dec. 19 speed race in this north Italian
valley.
	   The 32-year-old French skier from La Plagne, who's considering
retirement following the knee injury, was quoted by French media as
saying he was going to sue Italian organizers because the upper
section of the Saslong track was not protected by safety nets.
	   Cretier skidded off the track and fell over a ridge of grass and
snow after falling at a jump.
	   ``We have a clear conscience. We believe we've acted in the best
possible way,'' said Eric Demetz, president of the organizing
committee of Val Gardena, in the Italian Dolomite mountains.
	   Demetz added that nets in the section where Cretier fell could
have created a dangerous obstacle and caused additional risks to
skiers in a discipline which is considered dangerous because of
high speeds.
	   Demetz also said that the race was covered _ as required by the
International Ski Federation _ by a 5 billion lire (dlrs 3.1
million) insurance against possible damage.
	   Cretier was one of the five skiers who suffered season-ending
knee injuries in spills during the back-to-back World Cup downhills
on the icy Saslong track.
	   American Ehlias Louis and Canadian Ed Podivinsky were among the
others.
	   (pv-ek)
</TEXT>
