<HEADLINE>
Greenland parliament elections set for Feb. 16
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) _ Elections to Greenland's local
parliament will be held Feb. 16, Premier Jonathan Motzfeldt said
Tuesday.
	   Motzfeldt, of the social democratic Siumut party, has led the
Danish territory's home-rule government since last year. He
replaced Lars-Emil Johansen, who resigned.
	   The Cabinet coalition, which also includes the liberal Atassut
party, holds 24 of the 31 seats in parliament. The last parliament
vote was held on March 4, 1995. Elections are held every fourth
year.
	   Greenland, the world's largest island, won substantial home-rule
from Denmark in 1956 and has had its own parliament since 1979.
	   Denmark continues to be in charge of foreign and defense policy,
as well as matters related to law and the currency of the arctic
island's 56,000 people.
	   (jo-ewm)
