<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Army </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tudjman: Army must be ready to solve potential border problems
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SNJEZANA VUKIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Following new tensions with NATO along
the Bosnian border, President Franjo Tudjman told military
officials Tuesday that the army must be ready for potential
incidents on Croatia's frontiers.
	   ``We came out of the war, but the borders with most of our
neighboring countries are not established yet,'' Tudjman said,
according to the state-run news agency HINA.
	   ``Border cases and incidents could lead to all kinds of
situations and you should have that in mind,'' he said, adding that
Croatia would do all to solve the border disputes by negotiations,
but the border police and the army should be ready to ``secure the
state's policy'' if needed.
	   In 1991, when Croatia, Bosnia and Slovenia seceeded from the old
Yugoslav federation, the former republic borders became the
boundaries of the new independent states. Since the republics'
borders were not always precisely drawn, a number of border
disputes surfaced that the countries are trying to solve by
negotiations.
	   Croatia still is discussing several border points with Slovenia,
Bosnia-Herzegovina and today's Yugoslavia.
	   Last week, Croatia was reportedly contemplating of sending its
troops to Martin Brod, a Bosnian city on the border with Croatia,
after the NATO-led peace troops deployed in Bosnia removed Croatian
border police from the half of the city they controlled since 1995.
	   Martin Brod, situated in southwestern Bosnia, was considered a
Bosnian city before the war. But during the 1995 offensive in which
Croatian army joined Bosnian Muslim troops in routing the Serbs
from that region, Croatia established its police on the river Una
that runs through the city. Croatia said some maps show that part
of the city should be Croatian.
	   But Bosnia insists the city must stay within its borders,
providing maps and other papers that support its claim.
	   The Canadian troops sent armored cars to Martin Brod and briefly
detained four Croatian policemen, as they acted on the instructions
from the top Bosnian international official, Carlos Westendorp.
	   Westendorp decided to restore Bosnian control of the whole city
until the two countries reach an agreement.
	   Besides Martin Brod, Croatia and Bosnia have yet to agree on
about four other border disputes.
	   (sv/reid)
</TEXT>
