<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Bishop, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swedish Roman Catholic bishop consecrated; first since Reformation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS convent to monastery in graf 2. All else same &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo pending &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ A 49-year-old monk on Tuesday was
consecrated bishop by the Roman Catholic Church. He's the first
Swede to hold the post in about 400 years.
	   Anders Arborelius was appointed last month by the Vatican. He
speaks seven languages and spent the past three decades in a
Carmelite monastery in southern Sweden.
	   He was born in Switzerland of Swedish parents, and grew up in
the Swedish city of Lund.
	   The 16th century Reformation religious movement changed Sweden
from an almost entirely Catholic country into a Protestant one
where Catholics were banned. Native Swedes were not allowed to be
Catholic until 1860.
	   The Catholic church claims about 165,000 members in Sweden --
about two percent of the population. Most of its priests are
foreign-born, according to the Stockholm diocese, which includes
the whole country.
	   Arborelius replaced Hubertus Brandenburg, a German, who retired
six weeks ago when he turned 75, the usual retirement age for
bishops.
	   (hm-ewm)
</TEXT>
