<SLUG> BC-France-Arc de Triomphe, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arc de Triomphe hit by strike, but end could be near
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: RECASTS with background, adds byline
 &UR; By MARILYN AUGUST &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The Arc de Triomphe, one of the world's most famous
monuments to military glory, has become a battlefield in its own
right, with striking workers pitted against management and
frustrated tourists.
	   Workers voted Tuesday to continue their strike for a fourth day
to demand more staff. About 60 people work atop the monumental
stone arch at the head of the Champs-Elysees.
	   Some 50 meters (about 150 feet) high and 45 meters (about 135
feet) wide, the Arc at the head of the Avenue des Champs-Elysees
attracts about 1.4 million visitors a year.
	   Workers complain they can't handle the increasingly large crowds
drawn to the Arc's splendid rooftop view: a panorama of the Right
Bank's skyline and the 12 tree-lined avenues stretching out like
spokes of a wheel.
	   The Arc _ where an eternal flame has flickered above France's
Tomb of the Unknown Soldier since 1920 _ was commissioned by
Napoleon Bonaparte to commemorate his many victories.
	   Construction began in 1806 when the Champs-Elysees, or Elysian
Fields, was still just that. Besides the names of Napoleon's
generals and victories are oversized, neo-classical sculptures
depicting bare-breasted women waving the French colors.
	   Since its completion in 1836, the Arc was the backdrop for
displays of national pomp and military might, not always in
victory.
	   In 1885, millions flocked to the Arc for Victor Hugo's funeral
procession down the Champs-Elysees.
	   In 1940, Nazi troops victoriously goose-stepped from the Arc
down the Champs, the city's most prestigious street. Four years
later, it was Gen. Charles de Gaulle, the leader of the
London-based Free French Forces, who rallied Allied troops to the
Arc for a victory parade applauded by millions of Parisians.
	   After suffering from pollution and vibration from underground
subway lines, the Arc underwent renovations a decade ago that may
be partially responsible for its growing popularity.
	   Though some hearty souls still climb the Arc's winding
staircase, most opt for the high-speed elevator that gets them to
the top in less than a minute.
	   Besides the rooftop view, a spacious indoor hall houses
user-friendly exhibits on French military history.
	   But like other French attractions plagued by recent strikes, the
Arc may be a victim of its own success, with growing crowds
stretching existing staff.
	   Union officials said they hoped the dispute would not drag on.
	   ``We hope to solve this tonight,'' said Francoise Pinson,
spokeswoman for the Union of Cultural Affairs Personnel, whose
members met Tuesday with Culture Ministry officials.
	   Strikes also have hit the Orsay, Louvre and Grand Palais
museums, with employees making similar demands for more staff.
Workers also recently went on strike at the Eiffel Tower.
	   (ma-parf-ip)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-France-Arc de Triomphe, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
