<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's parliament debates 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VIKTOR LUHOVYK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's parliament on Tuesday approved
projected budget revenues and the deficit for 1999, spending hours
in heated debate between government supporters and the leftist
opposition.
	   The 450-seat Verkhovna Rada voted 272-114 to approve the
government-proposed deficit of 1 percent of gross domestic product
and gross revenues of 34 billion hryvna (dlrs 9.9 billion).
	   The budget debate is to continue Wednesday, with deputies
scheduled to decide how the projected revenues should be divided
between the central and local governments, and also discuss
individual spending and revenue targets.
	   Tuesday's debate followed several budget clashes between the
government and leftist lawmakers in previous weeks, with the two
sides insisting on sharply different targets and failing to reach a
compromise each time.
	   Communists and their supporters continued arguing Tuesday for a
higher deficit to provide for more social subsidies and demanded
higher revenues, which they said government officials were
intentionally lowering to use the remainder for personal gain.
	   ``Never before did we have such a disgraceful budget debate (as
this year), effectively instituting a policy of genocide,'' said
Natalia Vitrenko of the leftist Progressive Socialist Party.
	   ``For the first time ever we touched at the money that has gone
past the budget in previous years, but the government does not want
to part with its shadow resources,'' said parliament's budget
committee chief, Julia Tymoshenko.
	   However, Cabinet officials pleaded with lawmakers to approve the
document they proposed, arguing that with Ukraine's economy
expected to further decline by 1 percent in 1999 and with mounting
debt obligations, the former Soviet republic cannot count on
revenues as high as parliament wanted.
	   ``I'm very concerned about what would await us next year if we
don't approve the budget on time,'' Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko told parliament.
	   Ukraine's government has consistently failed to implement
reforms since gaining independence in 1991. The country has been
plagued by economic decline, mounting wage arrears and a huge
foreign debt.
	   The government wants a well-balanced low-deficit budget to
present to the International Monetary Fund so that it can resume
the suspended dlrs 2.2 billion loan.
	   Many analysts have said that without foreign aid Ukraine would
hardly be able to repay its 1999 debt obligations since the
government cannot raise the required money from internal sources.
	   The government raised only 63 percent of planned annual revenues
in the first 11 months of 1998, while its debt in unpaid wages and
pensions has steadily grown to more than 3 billion hryvna (dlrs 875
million), according to official statistics.
	   (vl/ml)
