<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Republic of Congo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vatican: Fighting in Republic of Congo kills dozens, sends
</HEADLINE>
thousands fleeing &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ Government-allied forces in the Republic of
Congo attacked a city in that country's southwest, killing dozens
and sending thousands fleeing, the Vatican's missionary news
service said Tuesday.
	   Fides news service cited missionaries in the targeted city,
Nkayi, in its account of the fighting.
	   It blamed the attack on Angolan soldiers allied to Republic of
Congo President Denis Sassou-Nguesso. The forces bombarded the
35,000-resident city overnight from Saturday and Sunday, Fides
said.
	   On Monday, Republic of Congo authorities decided to evacuate
remaining residents of the city, sending them on a forced march
toward Dolisie, 90 kilometers (55 miles) away, the news service
said.
	   Missionaries expressed particular fears for the safety for the
young men among the residents of the city, in a region known for
its opposition to Sassou-Nguesso.
	   There was no immediate confirmation of the attack from the
Republic of Congo.
	   Sassou-Nguesso seized power in the central African nation last
year. Angola and Chad have soldiers in Republic of Congo supporting
Sassou-Nguesso's government against continued fighting by
opponents.
	   (ek)
</TEXT>
