<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Bin Laden,0278 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Afghan opposition leader urges Bin Laden to leave Afghanistan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Afghanistan's opposition alliance on
Tuesday held Muslim militant Osama Bin Laden responsible for the
U.S. missile attacks on Afghanistan in August and urged him to
leave Afghanistan.
	   The United States, which accuses Bin Laden of being behind
bombings of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania in early August,
rained missiles on Afghanistan on Aug. 21 to destroy what it says
were training camps for Muslim militants run by Bin Laden.
	   ``Because of (Bin Laden's) presence, the country had to face a
missile attack from the United States,'' said opposition commander
Ahmed Shah Massood, who is fighting the Taliban militia, which
controls 90 percent of Afghanistan.
	   ``We don't want this man on Afghan soil,'' Massood said in a
telephone interview from opposition-controlled territory in
Afghanistan. ``Afghanistan is earning a bad name in the world
because of Bin Laden's activities and his training camps,''
	   Bin Laden denies he played a role in the bombings, but has said
that he welcomed the attacks. Earlier this month, Bin Laden urged
Muslims to kill Americans and Britons in retaliation for the
U.S.-British airstrikes on Iraq.
	   The Taliban militia, which his imposed its strict brand of
Muslim rule throughout most of Afghanistan, has refused to expel
Bin Laden from Afghanistan saying he is running religious schools
not military training camps.
	   Massood, a former defense minister, said Bin Laden's forces are
fighting alongside the Taliban against the opposition coalition
based in northern Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
