</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Koestler Bust </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
University removes bust of writer Arthur Koestler
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) _ A bronze bust of the late writer
Arthur Koestler, alleged in a recent biography to have been a
serial rapist, was removed from a foyer in Edinburgh University
after security fears that it would be defaced, the university said
Tuesday.
	   ``The university decided, as a temporary precaution, to remove
the bust from the Department of Psychology's main entrance hall
into another part of the department, in case anyone decided to take
action against the bust,'' a spokeswoman for the university said.
	   Koestler, who died in 1983 aged 77 in a suicide pact with his
wife, was described this year in David Cesarani's biography, ``The
Homeless Mind,'' as being a heavy drinker who was routinely violent
toward women.
	   British newspapers reported Tuesday that female students
reported feeling uneasy about the statue.
	   ``There was a feeling he should not be there and some female
students reported feeling uneasy under his gaze,'' an unidentified
spokesman for the student's union was quoted as saying in the Daily
Telegraph newspaper.
	   However, the university said that although it was aware of
complaints reported in newspapers, it had received no complaints
directly from students.
	   Koestler was a former Communist whose best-known novel
``Darkness at Noon'' was an indictment of Stalinist terror. He was
held as a prisoner under General Franco during the Spanish Civil
War while working as a journalist, and settled in England in 1940.
	   The writer left money in his will to set up a chair of
parapsychology at a British university to investigate the
paranormal after his death. The 500,000 pounds (dlrs 800,000)
bequest was awarded to Edinburgh University, which erected the bust
in its benefactor's honor.
	   (mb-rs-er)
</TEXT>
