<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebels </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels push into northwestern Congo, capture town
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GOMA, Congo (AP) _ Rebels advancing into northwestern Congo said
Tuesday they had captured the town of Gemena and approached the
home village of the late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko at Gbadolite
that is also used by the government allies to launch a
counteroffensive.
	   Rebel commander Sylvain Buki said his forces over the weekend
took Gemena, 1,000 kilometers (620 miles) northeast of the capital,
Kinshasa and were poised to overrun Gbadolite near the border with
Central African Republic.
	   Gbadolite is also the base for Chadian troops fighting in
support of President Laurent Kabila.
	   There was no independent confirmation of the rebel claims. But
the rebel forces, supported by Rwanda and Uganda, have been making
steady gains in northern Congo.
	   Kabila accuses Rwanda and Uganda of sponsoring the Aug. 2
rebellion of ethnic Tutsis, disaffected Congolese soldiers and
opposition politicians. Kabila's refusal to negotiate with the
rebels has torpedoed efforts to broker a cease-fire and open
political negotiations.
	   On Tuesday, Rwandan and Ugandan presidents said their forces
will remain in Congo until security along their western borders is
assured.
	   Both countries, which installed Kabila in power after rebels
ostensibly under his command ousted Mobutu in May 1997, accuse the
Congolese president of enlisting thousands of Rwandan and Ugandan
rebels who had operating from bases in eastern Congo to destabilize
their governments.
	   The rebel advance into forested Equateur Province is an attempt
to approach Kinshasa from the northwest, five months after Kabila's
foreign allies, who also include Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia,
repulsed an assault on the capital.
	   Rebel commanders said their next target is the Congo River port
of Mbandaka, the provincial capital, 600 kilometers (372 miles)
upriving from Kinshasa.
	   (hh/sl)	   
</TEXT>
