<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
France confirms it bowed out of Iraq overflights
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ France confirmed on Tuesday that its planes have
stopped participating in allied overflights over southern Iraq
since Dec. 16, a decision prompted by the U.S.-led bombings against
Iraq.
	   ``The obvious reasons for the French withdrawal were the chain
of events that led to the airstrikes,'' Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret told a daily news briefing.
	   Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassine Ramadan had already said in a
TV interview on Sunday that France had probably stopped its
participation in the U.S.-led air patrols known as ``Southern
Watch,'' but said he was unable to confirm the news.
	   France halted the overflights on the first of a four-day series
of airstrikes by U.S. and British forces aimed at punishing Baghdad
for blocking U.N. weapons inspections.
	   If France withdrew from the Northern Watch mission in 1996, its
warplanes were still patrolling the skies of southern Iraq, where a
no-flight zone had been imposed in August 1992 to protect Shiite
Muslims from Iraqi repression after the 1990-91 Gulf War.
	   However when Americans and British decided to extend the zone to
the 33nd parallel in 1996, Paris decided to keep its forces within
the limits of the 32nd parallel.
	   France has taken a softer line toward Iraq in recent years,
arguing for a lifting of sanctions it says have hurt Iraqi citizens
more than Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and the ruling elite.
France is also eager to renew once-lucrative trade ties with
Baghdad.
	   According to the French Foreign Ministry, French participation
to Southern Watch amounted to 175 people, five 2000C Mirages, two
Mirages F1 CR and one tanker aircraft. French forces are based in
Saudi Arabia.
	   (nv-cb)
</TEXT>
