<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Islamic Jihad </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Yemen-Kidnapping
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Yemen's Islamic Jihad has been friend and foe of government &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ The Islamic Jihad _ whose abduction of 16
foreigners ended in tragedy Tuesday with the death of three
hostages _ has a history of political ups and downs in this nation
on the Arabian peninsula.
	   The Yemeni group has loose ties to radical Muslim groups
elsewhere in the Arab world since the Yemeni Jihad's leaders _ like
other Islamic radicals _ fought against the Russian occupation of
Afghanistan in the 1980s.
	   Yemeni fundamentalist groups including Islamic Jihad became
influential after conservative North Yemen united with the
socialist South in 1990 _ following a decades-long war between the
two sides of the split nation.
	   President Ali Abdullah Saleh allied himself with the
fundamentalists to gain leverage over his Socialist rivals. The
Islamic Jihad upped its influence after a 1994 civil war when it
defeated attempts to tear apart the union.
	   After the war, Islamic Jihad imposed strict religious law in
some parts of the country, flogging women for ignoring the Muslim
dress code and men for selling and drinking alcohol, which is
forbidden under Islam.
	   But many ordinary Yemenis resented the interference in daily
life, and Saleh began to fear the group's political ambitions. The
result was Islamic Jihad never got the full influence it sought.
	   The deterioration in relations also had an effect on other Arab
radicals who had taken refuge in Yemen. The government began
expelling Egyptian, Algerian and Pakistani radicals.
	   Government troops also clashed with Yemeni members of Islamic
Jihad to try to weaken the group. The group itself had carried out
several bombings over the years, including one which killed a
Belgian woman tourist.
	   After 1997 parliamentary elections, Saleh tried to get control
of the group by persuading some of its leaders to join his party,
the General People's Congress, and giving them government posts.
	   But those who refused were arrested _ and remain in jail _ and a
new government crackdown began in the past few weeks.
	   Among those rounded up recently was Islamic Jihad's leader,
Saleh Haidara al-Atwi, whose release was demanded by the kidnappers
of the 16 foreign tourists.
 &UR; str-ti-ggl
</TEXT>
