<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Bribe Investigation, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mitchell promises 'thorough and prompt' probe into Olympic bribe
</HEADLINE>
allegations &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Mitchell remarks &QL; 
 &UR; By WILL LESTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell
promised Tuesday a ``thorough and prompt'' investigation into
claims that bribes helped Salt Lake City win the 2002 Winter
Olympic games.
	   Talking with reporters after his initial meeting with members of
a special commission investigating the allegations, Mitchell noted
that the panel has to file its report with the U.S. Olympic
Committee by Feb. 28.
	   ``I entered this process with a completely open mind both as to
the practices and standards which have been utilized in the past
and those which ought to be utilized,'' he said. ``We owe (the
athletes) the obligation to make certain that the Games in which
they participate are in fact and are perceived as totally fair and
above reproach.''
	   Mitchell said that in Tuesday's initial meeting the commission,
which was appointed by the U.S. Olympic Committee, ``established
for ourselves a process which we will use to conduct an
investigation which is at once fair and prompt.''
	   Past and present officials of the Salt Lake City Olympic
Committee have acknowledged they gave members of the international
committee gifts and paid college tuition to some of the committee's
relatives prior to the city being selected for the winter games.
	   Mitchell, who, 3rd graf pvs
</TEXT>
