w1726 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 3rdLd-Writethru   12-29 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More international verifiers arriving, NATO warns warring sides
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; RECASTS, adds Yugoslavia's demand for KLA to be declared
terrorist organization. no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ After the worst outbreak of fighting
in months, more international monitors were sent Tuesday to Kosovo
to shore up the fragile truce between government forces and ethnic
Albanian rebels.
	   Meanwhile, NATO repeated warnings it stands ready to intervene
if the two sides fail to respect the Oct. 12 agreement between
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke, which ended seven months of fighting and averted NATO
airstrikes.
	   That agreement was severely strained by four days of fighting
between government forces and the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation
Army, which erupted Christmas Eve and left at least 15 people dead.
	   Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia's main republic Serbia, was
generally quiet Tuesday.
	   But the ethnic Albanian-run Kosovo Information Center, reported
some overnight shooting on the outskirts of Kosovska Mitrovica, 30
kilometers (18 miles) northwest of here, which ``made the situation
there very tense and difficult.''
	   In an effort to shore up the October agreement, about 100
international ``verifiers'' were heading Tuesday for Kosovo. The
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which is
running the verification mission, said an undetermined number of
American, Canadian and European observers arrived in Kosovo late
Tuesday and the rest were expected in another day or two.
	   Their arrival will bring to about 700 the number of verifiers
already on the ground in Kosovo. The OSCE expects to have a full
compliment of 2,000 verifiers by mid-January, according to
spokesman Sandy Blyth.
	   The verifiers, however, do not carry weapons, and critics among
ethnic Albanians and Serbs have questioned whether the mission will
be able to prevent a new round of fighting, possibly in the spring.
	   After last week's fighting, the chairman of the OSCE, Polish
Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek, warned that continuing violence
could prompt the 54-nation organization to reconsider its
peacekeeping role.
	   But an OSCE spokesman, Jorgen Grunnet, told a radio station in
Saarbruecken, Germany on Tuesday that the Kosovo Verification
Mission had no plans to stop its peacekeeping efforts.
	   As a sign of international resolve, NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana warned the two sides Tuesday ``not to endanger the
fragile security situation.''
	   ``NATO is ready to intervene if the situation requires,'' Solana
said In Brussels, Belgium.
	   Nevertheless, the rhetoric on both sides underscored the
bitterness between Serbs and the ethnic Albanians, who are
demanding independence for the province.
	   The spokesman for the ethnic Albanian rebels, Adem Demaci, said
the guerrillas will respect the cease-fire ``but we will defend
ourselves with all means if necessary.''
	   Yugoslavia's foreign minister demanded that the KLA be declared
a terrorist organization. In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic accused the rebels
of taking advantage of the Oct. 12 agreement to rearm and regroup.
	   The ultra-nationalist Serbian Radical Party, a close ally of
Milosevic, called Tuesday for ``complete extinction of Albanian
terrorist gangs,'' as the only way to solve the crisis in Kosovo.
	   rr/jg/ms
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
