w1731 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-Englan     12-29 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-England Celebrates </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tears of joy for Dean Headley's parents; even Fred Trueman's
</HEADLINE>
smiling &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ England's spectacular cricket victory over
Australia was hailed as a ``miracle'' by the media on Tuesday,
while the parents of fast bowler Dean Headley wept tears of joy
after his match-winning performance in Melbourne.
	   In a huge turnaround and a dramatic finish, England beat the
Australians by 12 runs after appearing on course for a third loss
in a row. Needing only 175 to win, Australia collapsed from 130 for
three to 162 all out and Headley, a comparative newcomer in Test
cricket, took six for 60.
	   ``It's a miracle. We win a Test'' the London Evening Standard
said in a front-page headline.
	   Although Australia has already clinched the big prize, the
Ashes, and still leads 2-1 with one Test to go, the euphoria over
such a rare victory over the old enemy was nationwide.
	   At the Stourbridge, central England home of the Headley family,
Dean's father Ron, who played Test cricket for the West Indies,
said he was immensely proud of his son.
	   ``I am one of the luckiest guys in the world really, to have my
son perform like that after what I have done,'' said Ron Headley,
who has lived in England for 30 years. ``Having played the game
myself I know the emotions he will be going through.
	   ``We just hugged each other and there were some tears of joy.''
	   His wife, Gail, was convinced the team was going to lose once
again.
	   ``I went to bed when he got out for a single,'' she said. ``I
thought `That is it, they have not got a chance'. I got up at 6:45
a.m. and Ron, who has had the radio on all night, said `The lad is
doing it but it is very tight'.
	   ``I couldn't stand it. I have been pacing the floor crying and I
had to keep leaving the room. But he did it''.
	   Lord MacLaurin, chairman of the England and Wales Cricket Board,
has flown out to watch the last two Tests.
	   ``They always win for me. I've just turned up for the last two
tests and they have done it for me,'' he said. ``That was really
something. It showed guts and a certain mental toughness. Great
stuff. Now we'll square it at Sydney.''
	   Ian Botham, whose match-turning century against Australia at
Leeds in 1981 was hailed as one of the greatest innings in the
history of the game, said he was surprised that the English players
tried to call the game off as a draw in the late stages.
	   ``England were wrong to try to come off,'' the Sky TV cricket
analyst said. ``I bet England are glad they stayed out there. Their
supporters certainly are. It was one of the great finishes.
	   ``Our supporters have had a hard time and taken a lot of stick.
What a 24 hours it will be for them. Any win against Australia is
beautiful. When you beat them at the MCG it's even more
beautiful.''
	   England's dramatic win sparked celebrations everywhere and even
the team's sternest critics, such as former team selector Ted
Dexter and ex-Yorkshire star Brian Close, were impressed.
	   ``It was thrilling. I got up at 6am to watch it and it was
tremendous entertainment,'' said Dexter, a former England captain
and chairman of selectors.
	   ``Remember that Mark Taylor put us in, which is always a danger
batting last, but they got their comeuppance this time. It's
wonderful when the wheel turns.''
	   Close, also a former England captain famous for his
uncompromising attitude on the field, had watched team fail
miserably, match after match.
	   ``Funnily enough I said after the first innings that this was
the best position we'd been in in a bloody long while. I'm
delighted,'' he said.
	   Sports Minister Tony Banks said the triumph at Melbourne and a
series-tying victory at Sydney would boost the battered image of
English cricket with the World Cup approaching in May.
	   ``It's a tremendous victory and a great boost to cricket, and
the morale that would come from victory in Sydney will do wonders
for cricket in the World Cup year,'' Banks said.
	   ``It's amazing how something like this does wonders for the
well-being even amongst those people who are not interested in the
cricket.''
	   Fred Trueman, probably England's most famous fast bowler who has
spent the last 20 years bemoaning the decline of the English team,
was uncharacteristically euphoric.
	   I'm a very happy man, a very, very happy man,'' the
blunt-speaking former Yorkshire pacemen told reporters. ``Happy New
Year.''
	   (rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
