<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Bishop, 1st Ld-Writethru,0194 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swedish Roman Catholic bishop consecrated; first since Reformation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS to monastery, sted convent, in 2nd graf. Minor
edits. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo STO101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ A 49-year-old monk was consecrated as a
bishop Tuesday by the Roman Catholic Church _ the first Swede to
hold the post in about 400 years.
	   Anders Arborelius was appointed last month by the Vatican. He
speaks seven languages and spent the past three decades in a
Carmelite monastery in southern Sweden.
	   He was born in Switzerland of Swedish parents, and grew up in
the Swedish city of Lund.
	   The 16th century Reformation religious movement changed Sweden
from an almost entirely Catholic country into a Protestant one
where Catholics were banned. Native Swedes were not allowed to be
Catholic until 1860.
	   The Catholic church claims about 165,000 members in Sweden _
about 2 percent of the population. Most of its priests are
foreign-born, according to the Stockholm diocese, which oversees
the whole country.
	   Arborelius replaced Hubertus Brandenburg, a German, who retired
six weeks ago when he turned 75.
</TEXT>
