w1745 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Angola-Fighting     12-29 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Angola-Fighting,0488 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angolan army, rebels continue battles in central highlands
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CASIMIRO SIONA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ The government army said it drove back an
offensive Tuesday by rebel troops encircling the central highland
city of Kuito, killing 30 rebels and capturing two armored vehicles
during a four-hour battle.
	   The UNITA rebels advanced at dawn on Cunhinga, 30 kilometers (18
miles) north of Kuito, Brig. Simione Mucume told state radio RNA.
	   He said that after the attack, the rebels shelled outlying
suburbs of the city with long-range artillery, killing 10
civilians, including a child.
	   There was no independent confirmation of the report.
	   Kuito, which lies 500 kilometers (300 miles) southeast of the
capital Luanda, has been cut off by a rebel siege since the
southwest African country's civil war restarted Dec. 4, ending a
four-year peace process.
	   Huambo, the country's second-largest city which lies 130
kilometers (80 miles) to the west of Kuito, reportedly was quiet,
though the army and rebels were said to be fighting in the
surrounding countryside.
	   The International Red Cross said it could not resume aid flights
to Kuito, where some 30,000 displaced people have joined the local
population of about 100,000, because the rebels were shelling the
airport.
	   However, a flight was scheduled for Huambo early Wednesday, IRC
spokeswoman Francoise Zambelini said.
	   A cargo plane chartered by the United Nations crashed near
Huambo on Saturday. The cause of the crash, as the plane passed
through a war zone, was not known.
	   The army also said the rebels launched an attack on Cubal, 100
kilometers (60 miles) west of Huambo, and that eight local police
officers were missing.
	   Cubal lies on the strategic Benguela railroad, which crosses the
country from the west coast, passing through Huambo and Kuito. The
attack apparently was aimed at preventing the government from
moving reinforcements to the central highlands.
	   The Civil Aviation Authority said Tuesday that an Antonov 12
cargo plane disappeared last weekend en route from the capital
Luanda to Lukapa in the northeast.
	   There was no sign of the aircraft, which belonged to the private
airline Arcar Cargo, officials said.
	   The United Nations observer mission, which is monitoring a 1994
peace accord that halted a two-decade civil war between the rebels
and the government, has been unable to stop the renewed fighting
which so far has focused on the central highlands.
	   The U.N. Security Council has blamed UNITA, a Portuguese acronym
for the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, for
the return to war.
	   UNITA refused to yield control of areas under its control and
maintained a hidden army, according to the United Nations.
	   The country has been ravaged by conflict since gaining
independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
