<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bahrain-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bahrain announces fiscal budget with dlrs 849 million deficit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) _ Bahrain's emir, Sheik Isa bin Salman Al
Khalifa, has ratified the island nation's 1999-2000 budget with a
projected deficit of 320 million dinars (dlrs 849 million), the
official Gulf News Agency reported Tuesday.
	   The deficit is considerably higher than the estimated 150
million dinar (dlrs 390 million) shortfalls in the previous two
years.
	   Bahrain, which has much less oil income than its Gulf neighbors,
functions with a two-year budget cycle.
	   The Gulf News Agency said the emir, Sheik Isa bin Salman Al
Khalifa, had ratified the budget.
	   It forecasts revenues at 1.138 billion (about dlrs 3 billion)
and expenditures at 1.458 billion dinars (about dlrs 3.9 billion),
the agency said.
	   Finance Minister Ibrahim Abdul-Karim told the agency that the
budget was constructed amid very ``delicate circumstances'' _ low
world oil prices and difficulty in predicting oil prices in coming
years.
	   Bahrain, like other Gulf states, gets most of its income from
oil. The tiny Gulf island state has an output capacity of just
40,000 barrels a day, compared with 8 million barrels produced
daily by neighboring Saudi Arabia.
	   The Bahrain government's income comes mainly from sales of
products made from imported oil.
	   Earlier this month the finance minister said the government had
decided to tighten its budget for fiscal 1999-2000 by cutting
expenditure on construction and development by dlrs 133 million.
Some 260 million dinars (dlrs 690 million) has been earmarked for
such projects.
	   The minister said the squeeze on capital spending was to provide
``good quality of life'' for Bahrainis in terms of free health,
education and social services.
 &UR; am-eap
</TEXT>
