<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-KwaZulu Arrests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Suspects charged in Dec. 23 slaying of 6 in SAfrica
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (aP) _ Police on Tuesday charged 20 people
in connection with the slaying of six people last week in the town
of Harding, a police official said.
	   Another ten suspects were released, said police spokesman
Director Bala Naidoo..
	   Police have linked the killings to fighting between two clans in
southern KwaZulu-Natal.
	   More than 20 people died in four different attacks in the
province since Dec. 23, but police have discounted any links among
the killings.
	   In the worst attack on Christmas Eve, eight people died in the
town of Margate.
	   President Nelson Mandela said he backs a special initiative from
the National Director of Public Prosecutions to investigate the
killings.
	   Multiple killings in KwaZulu-Natal receive special attention
after more than 10,000 people died in political clashes in the
years before the first all-race elections in 1994.
	   On Christmas Day in 1995, a political massacre claimed 18 lives
in Shobashobane, when 2,000 armed supporters of the Zulu
nationalist Inkatha Freedom Party attacked rival members of
Mandela's African National Congress.
	   (var-pr)
</TEXT>
