r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RepublicofCongo-Borde     12-29 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Republic of Congo-Border Pact </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Neighboring Congo's sign non-aggression pact
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRAZZAVILLE, Republic of Congo (AP) _ Presidents from central
Africa's neighboring and at times rival Congos signed a
non-aggression pact Tuesday and agreed to establish a joint border
security force.
	   Host President Denis Sassou-Nguesso from the Republic of Congo
met with visiting President Laurent Kabila from the Democratic
Republic of Congo, formerly Zaire, prior to signing the pact which
reaffirms the sovereignty of both countries.
	   ``I came to Congo to reassure our two peoples, that apart from
some venomous media reports there is nothing wrong in the relations
between our two countries,'' Kabila told reporters during the
signing ceremony.
	   Although Sassou-Nguesso and Kabila espouse friendly bilateral
ties, both leaders in the past have accused each other of
supporting rebel movements in one another's country.
	   Kabila is battling a insurgent army in the east that is moving
steadily into the north of the country. Sassou-Nguesso has been
facing a small but growing threat from a militia army in the south
linked to the country's former government.
	   The two leaders signed a second agreement to establish a joint
border security force composed of military personnel from both
countries.
	   Brazzaville and the Democratic Republic of Congo's capital,
Kinshasa, are twin cities separated only by the Congo River.
	   The pact signed Tuesday comes despite persisting mistrust and
tension from Kabila, who accused Brazzaville of offering safe haven
to members of the government of the late Zairian dictator Mobutu
Sese Seko.
	   Mobutu fled Kinshasa in May 1997 to escape Kabila's advancing
rebel forces. Several of his senior military officers and cabinet
members escaped to Brazzaville.
	   (lo/ids)
</TEXT>
