w1780 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Macedonia-Albanians     12-29 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Macedonia-Albanians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parliament passes amnesty law to pardon jailed Albanian officials
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo
 &UR; By KONSTANTIN TESTORIDES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ Macedonian parliament passed Tuesday an
amnesty law, pardoning four ethnic Albanian officials whose
sentencing to prison terms last year stirred ethnic tensions in the
former Yugoslav republic.
	   Rufi Osmani and Alydin Demiri, mayors of two predominantly
ethnic Albanian towns in western Macedonia, and two other
officials, were jailed to a total of 13 years in prison for
inciting unrest in Gostivar and Tetovo, in July last year.
	   The four then defied a government ban and put up Albanian flags
in the towns, triggering clashes between Macedonian police and
ethnic Albanians in which three people were killed and some 150
wounded.
	   Macedonia, whose 23 percent of the population are restive ethnic
Albanians, borders neighboring Yugoslavia's Kosovo, whose Albanians
are fighting the government forces for secession.
	   Macedonia is a host for a still-forming NATO extraction mission
for Kosovo.
	   There have been fears that Macedonia could explode in similar
violence as in Kosovo. The amnesty law is widely seen as an attempt
to ease ethnic tensions and as a conciliatory move by the
government toward Macedonia's ethnic Albanian parties.
	   But the law also faced criticism from former ruling party, the
Social Democrats or renamed Communists, who said it would only
radicalize the situation. The Social Democrats lost an election
earlier this year to a central-rightist coalition.
	   The amnesty law was passed with 85 votes for, 18 against, and
one deputy abstaining from the vote. Macedonia's parliament has 120
seats.
	   President Kiro Gligorov, who led Macedonia into independence
from former Yugoslavia without bloodshed in 1991, has refused to
pardon the four ethnic Albanian officials saying the consequences
of their moves were too grave. It was not immediately clear whether
Gligorov needs to sign the amnesty law to make it effective.
	   Ethnic Albanian political parties in Macedonia have declared the
sentencing of their officials as ``draconian punishments,'' and
threatened boycott of the government and the assembly.
	   Macedonia is crucial for stability in the Balkans, especially as
a 1,800-man strong NATO force is forming in the country to provide
protection for international monitors in Kosovo in case they run
into trouble.
	   (kt/jg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Macedonia-Albanians; CT:i; 
