<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chemical Weapons </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's official for chemical, biological weapons problems
</HEADLINE>
dismissed &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The head of a presidential committee in charge of
issues related to chemical and biological weapons has resigned, a
news report said Tuesday.
	   President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree accepting the
resignation of Pavel Syutkin, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   No reason for the resignation was given, and no replacement has
been named.
	   Russia insists it has scrapped the Soviet Union's biological
weapons program, and is trying to destroy its huge stockpile of
chemical weapons.
	   But concern has been mounting about the costs of destroying
Russia's 44,000 tons of deteriorating chemical weapons _ the
largest stockpile in the world _ which it promised to get rid of
when it ratified the international Chemical Weapons Convention last
year.
	   A prominent analyst warned recently that Russia's cash-starved
government may resort to burning the chemical weapons if it cannot
come up with the money for more environmentally safe and
internationally condoned methods of dismantling and disposal.
	   Yeltsin ordered his prime minister last month to step up efforts
to to attract private funding to help Russia destroy its chemical
weapons stockpile.
	   In a sign of another problem, Russia's Emergency Situations
Ministry announced last week that chemical weapons dumps in the
Baltic Sea are contaminating the water with heavy metals and
arsenic.
	   Russia says it stopped producing chemical weapons in 1987.
	   Russia also insists it has strictly complied with the 1972
Biological Weapons Convention, which bans the development,
production and stockpiling of biological and toxin weapons.
	   However, some experts have claimed that Russia may be keeping
alive a portion of its Cold War biological weapons program.
	   Both Russia and the United States continue to do research on
programs to defend themselves against biological attacks.
	   (ad/ml)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
