</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-No Bank Holiday </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of employees to prepare for euro starting New Year's eve
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo FRA110 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ New Year's eve and the weekend
following won't be so-called banker's hours for thousands of bank
employees in Germany, the institutions said Tuesday.
	   The launch of Europe's new currency - the euro - will see
bankers especially busy from Thursday when conversion rates for the
11 currencies joining the venture are set and Jan. 4, the first
trading day of the euro.
	   About 8,000 people at Germany's four largest banks, the stock
exchange, the European Central Bank and the Deutsche Bundesbank
will be involved in the process of redenominating securities,
payment and settlement systems.
	   Deutsche Bank will have 2,000 staff worldwide working over the
conversion weekend, 1,000 alone at the Frankfurt headquarters where
they'll being doing shifts around the clock, a spokesman said.
	   A Dresdner Bank spokeswoman said about 1,700 people would be
working in its Frankfurt headquarters over the conversion weekend,
and another 900 in the rest of Germany.
	   Commerzbank said it will have about 300 people busy with the
conversion, and Munich-based Hypo-Vereinsbank said it will have
about 500 employees adjusting some 300 computer programs.
	   Deutsche Bundesbank said it will have about 1,200 on the job
around the country and a 90-person team will be doing the
conversion for Deutsche Boerse - the stock exchange.
	   At the Frankfurt-based European Central Bank, which takes over
responsibility for the joint monetary policy on Jan. 1, some 150 of
it of 570-strong workforce will be involved in the conversion, with
many others on call, a spokeswoman said.
	   The 11 countries in the monetary merger are Germany, France,
Italy, Ireland, Spain, Portugal, Austria, the Netherlands,
Luxembourg, Belgium and Finland. Many people are expected to be
burning the midnight oil in other countries as well.
	   (apdj-gb)
	   (apdj-gb)
</TEXT>
