w1802 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sudan-Opposition     12-29 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security bars opposition from delivering petition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Security guards on Tuesday prevented the
leaders of several banned Sudanese opposition parties from handing
over a protest letter to President Omar el-Bashir.
	   The delegation members later told a news conference they sent
their memorandum by fax and registered mail to the president.
	   A 17-man delegation included former Vice President Abel Alier
and several former generals.
	   The guards at the palace told the group that el-Bashir was not
in his office. And they confiscated the film of photographers who
covered the event.
	   The opposition leaders called on el-Bashir to ``work out a
comprehensive, just and permanent peace agreement that ends the
war'' in the south.
	   They also asked for ``the establishment of a strong, democratic
foundation for the administration of the country.''
	   Southern rebels have been fighting for 15 years for more
autonomy from the Islamic north. Some 1.9 million Sudanese have
died in the fighting and resulting famines.
	   El-Bashir earlier this month signed into law a bill that allows
Sudanese to form ``political associations'' starting Jan. 1.
	   The new constitution adopted in June does not mention the right
to form political parties, which el-Bashir banned after the
military coup that brought him to power in 1989. But it does allow
political associations.
	   Sudanese opposition leaders living in exile have rejected the
constitution, which is based on Islamic law, and vowed to keep up
their struggle for democracy.
	   A senior member of the ruling National Congress rejected the
demands made Tuesday by the opposition leaders in Khartoum.
	   ``We don't want the former (opposition) leaders to think that
the new era means a return of their parties without accepting the
new constitution,'' said Mohammed Hassan el-Amin, head of the
political department of the National Congress.
	   The opposition leaders blamed el-Bashir's government for the
``total collapse of the economy'' and human rights violations.
	   It also accused the government of ``widespread institutionalized
corruption'' and of being isolated from its neighbors and the
international community.
	   The opposition called for a ``free and fair general elections
... under regional and international supervision.''
 &UR; str-my/eap
</TEXT>
