u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cyprus-Politics     12-29 0236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish Cypriot parties reach deal on forming government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ Turkish Cypriot Premier-designate Dervis
Eroglu and the leader of a center-left party on Tuesday agreed to
form a government that would pursue the goal of international
recognition for the breakaway state.
	   President Rauf Denktash was expected to approve of the coalition
on Wednesday by formally accepting the proposed Cabinet list.
	   Eroglu's center-right National Unity Party, which won 24 seats
in the Dec 6. elections, reached the deal with Mustafa Akinci's
Salvation party, which has seven seats in the 50-member Parliament,
the Turkish Cypriot news agency, TAK, reported.
	   Eroglu won 40 percent of the votes in elections earlier this
month what was seen as approval for his hardline stance over the
future of the island. He has headed a coalition in the breakaway
state since 1996.
	   The Salvation Party on Tuesday agreed to closer economic
cooperation with Turkey despite having voted against a series of
economic deals that foresee an economic integration with Turkey in
the past.
	   Cyprus has been divided since 1974, when Turkey sent in troops
after a coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
	   The Turkish Cypriots declared their own state in 1983, which is
only recognized by Turkey.
	   Numerous U.N. efforts to reunify the island have failed.
	   (sh-sf)
</TEXT>
