w1822 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Greece-Cyprus 3rdLd-Writethru   12-29 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Cyprus, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President cancels deployment of S-300 missiles
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series, MINOR editing. &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEX EFTY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ President Glafcos Clerides said Tuesday
that he was canceling plans to deploy controversial, Russian-made
missiles in this island nation.
	   His decision was announced in a statement issued at the end of a
meeting of the policy-making Greek Cypriot National Council, which
is composed of party leaders.
	   Participants said there were intense disagreements among council
members over the missiles and that, in the end, Clerides said he
was taking the responsibility on himself to cancel the deployment.
	   The announcement in Nicosia followed talks in the Greek capital
Athens earlier in the day between Greek and Cypriot officials aimed
at defusing a political crisis over the missiles.
	   There has been speculation that the S-300 anti-aircraft missiles
will be diverted to the southern Greek island of Crete.
	   But both Clerides and Greek Premier Costas Simitis gave nothing
away after their meeting, which also was attended by the Greek
defense and foreign ministers.
	   After the meeting, Clerides returned to Nicosia for the National
Council meeting.
	   Diverting the missiles to Crete could defuse tensions with
Turkey, which has threatened military action to stop the missiles'
deployment in Cyprus.
	   Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and a Turkish-occupied north since 1974, when Turkey invaded after
a short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
	   The United States and NATO have criticized Clerides' decision
two years ago to purchase the missiles, fearing conflict between
NATO members Turkey and Greece. Athens has a defense pact with the
Greek Cypriots.
	   The missiles issue has also caused political tensions in Cyprus,
where the outcome of Tuesday's meeting could affect the survival of
Clerides' government.
	   The Socialist EDEK party, which holds the ministries of defense
and education, has warned it will withdraw from the government if
the missiles are not deployed as planned.
	   Other opposition parties maintain Clerides should resign,
following his promise to do so if the missiles are not deployed.
	   The Cypriot president had said previously that he would agree to
cancel the missiles' deployment only if Turkey accepted his
demilitarization proposal or if there was progress in the
U.N.-sponsored talks for the reunification of the island.
	   A U.N. Security Council resolution adopted unanimously last week
called for a reduction of weapons and troops in Cyprus and the
resumption of the talks.
 &UR; ath-ae-eap
</TEXT>
