<SLUG> BC-Martinique-Banana Strike,0269 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police unblock port _ again _ as Martinique banana workers continue
</HEADLINE>
protest &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FORT-DE-FRANCE, Martinique (AP) _ Police on Tuesday cleared
angry banana workers from a back entrance of Martinique's main port
as exporters rushed to move shipments blocked for weeks by
protesters' barricades.
	   The workers continued to block the port's main entrance with a
weighted freight container. Police reported no injuries or arrests.
	   About 200 banana workers struck Nov. 21 to demand raises. They
agreed Dec. 19 to remove the barricades, but raised them again
after labor negotiations fell through on Dec. 22.
	   On Monday, police cleared the back entrance long enough for
freight companies to move about 300 containers of goods ranging
from clothing to groceries. As soon as they left, the protesters
resumed the blockade.
	   About 4,200 containers are stranded on the port, said
Jean-Claude Lubin, manager of the Martinique Chamber of Commerce.
He said the protesters struck as retailers were gearing up for the
lucrative holiday business season.
	   ``Several companies will face financial obstacles and file for
bankruptcy because of the strike,'' Lubin told the newspaper
France-Antilles.
	   Companies have lost about dlrs 200 million (1 billion French
francs) because of the barricades, said Daniel Robin, president of
the Regional Union of Small Companies.
	   Banana shipments, meanwhile, are rotting in warehouses.
	   On Dec. 18, hundreds of company managers gathered in front of
the government's prefecture offices to stage a counter-protest
against the workers.
</TEXT>
