<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Loyalist forces lose fight for Sierra Leone town
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with rebel ultimatum and
deadline for attack on Freetown. ADDS quotes from RUF commander Sam
Bockarie. Edits to conform. No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ A top rebel commander on Tuesday
said his forces would begin attacking Sierra Leone's capital within
two days if the government fails to agree to immediate talks to be
mediated by the Organization or African Unity.
	   ``This is our ultimatum,'' rebel leader Sam Bockarie said in a
telephone interview from his hideout in the countryside. ``If a
dialogue is not started we will have to invade Freetown. They have
48 hours.''
	   The renewed threat comes after Sierra Leone's defense force
retreated from the key central town of Makeni and were redeploying
to defend the capital.
	   The rebel Revolutionary United Front along with allies from
Sierra Leone's disbanded military are demanding President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah's resignation and rejected an offer of amnesty in
return for their weapons.
	   Bockarie said the rebels would not lay down their arms, calling
instead for mediation by the Organization of African Unity's
chairman, Blaise Compaore, the President of Burkina Faso.
	   A West African intervention force led by Nigerian troops has
been fighting on Kabbah's behalf, but in recent days it has been
caught off guard by rebel advances.
	   Makeni, a strategic town about 120 kilometers (75 miles)
northeast of the capital, Freetown, fell to the insurgents in
recent days after heavy fighting in the area.
	   The coalition defense force, known as ECOMOG, were driven into a
``tactical retreat'' from Makeni, according to an ECOMOG statement.
	   Sierra Leone's Foreign Minister Sam Banya on Monday said
virtually the entire population of several thousand people fled
Makeni.
	   The United Nations World Food Program on Tuesday warned the
escalating hostilities could jeopardize relief programs in the
country's interior.
	   Food aid shipments to Makeni and other areas have been halted,
affected feeding and distribution programs for close to 24,000
people, WFP said in a statement.
	   ``Those most likely to be affected by the lack of food are
displaced persons who were living in camps and urban areas in the
north and the east,'' said Sierra Leone's WFP representative
Patrick Buckley.
	   Fighting in the eastern Kono region may have forced as many as
40,000 to flee their homes, Buckley said.
	   In February, ECOMOG ousted a military junta with ties to the
Revolutionary United Front.
	   But the West African intervention force has failed to disarm the
rebels who are now staging a serious counter-offensive.
	   ECOMOG troops, including fresh reinforcements from Ghana, are
focused on defending the capital, a senior official from Ghana
said.
	   ``We have sent some men and officers to help beef up what is
already on the ground,'' said the senior Ghanaian defense ministry
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Nigeria, meanwhile, sent an additional 1,000 soldiers to back up
their positions in Freetown.
	   Diplomats from West Africa, the United States and Britain
meeting Monday in the Ivory Coast called for more aid to help
defend Sierra Leone's embattled government.
	   Rebel units, however, claim to have closed to within 20
kilometers (12 miles) of the capital.
	   Banya said mercenaries from Liberia, Burkina Faso and the
Ukraine were fighting alongside the rebels. Bockarie dismissed that
claim as propaganda.
	   (var/ids)
</TEXT>
