<HEADLINE>
Serb official seeks to reassure Kosovo's Serbs about their safety
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Seeking to reassure Kosovo's Serb
population, the province's top-ranking official said Tuesday the
government will not allow ethnic Albanian ``terrorists'' to drive
them from their homes.
	   ``The state will not allow the terrorists to achieve their plan,
which is to `ethnically cleanse' these lands,'' Zoran Andjelkovic
told the municipal council in the northern Kosovo town of Podujevo,
scene of fierce clashes last week between government forces and the
ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army
	   The government's Tanjug news agency quoted Andjelkovic as saying
the army and the police would continue to ``do all in their power
to protect the people in this part of Serbia.''
	   According to Tanjug, the Serb official said it was not the job
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe ``to
tell us what to do and how to deal with the terrorists.''
	   ``It is their job only to verify the facts on the ground and
inform their superiors of their findings, and the facts clearly
show that the criminal gangs are terrorizing the civilian
population,''
	   During the visit to the town, Andjelkovic met with families of
Serb civilians who have gone missing from the villages of Velika
Reka, Obrandza and Perane.
