<SLUG> BC-Israel-Egypt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel and Egypt to negotiate supplying Egyptian gas to Israel
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel and Egypt will negotiate a deal to pipe
Egyptian natural gas to Israel, an Israeli spokesman said Tuesday.
	   Israel's infrastructure ministry told the national electricity
supplier to open negotiations after the Egyptian natural gas
company, EGPC, sent a letter expressing interest in the deal, the
ministry said in a statement.
	   Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, who has protested Egypt's
prohibition against selling gas to Israel, said the letter allows
``serious examination of the possibility of reliable and continuous
gas supply based solely on commerce and economics.''
	   Relations between Israel and Egypt have been strained in recent
months by the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations over
the West Bank and Gaza. Israel and Egypt maintain a `cold peace''
with few commercial or economic ties.
	   Negotiations over price and the quantity of gas to be supplied
were to begin in the next few days, the statement said.
 &UR; sb-rk
</TEXT>
