<SLUG> BC-EU-Cyprus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU applauds Nicosia's decision on Russian missiles
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ The European Union on Tuesday applauded a
decision by Greek Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides that he was
canceling plans to deploy Russian-made missiles in his island
nation.
	   Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel said the decision
to scrap the missiles represented ``a great success for quiet
diplomacy'' by the EU, Britain and the United States.
	   Austria currently holds the rotating EU presidency.
	   Schuessel said the Cypriot government appeared to have been
influenced by its desire to join the EU and had made ``a
significant contribution to stability in the region.''
	   The United States and NATO have criticized Clerides' decision
two years ago to purchase the air defense missiles, fearing
conflict between NATO members Turkey and Greece. Athens has a
defense pact with the Greek Cypriots.
	   Turkey had threatened military action if the missiles were
actually deployed. The missiles issue has also caused political
tensions in Cyprus, where the outcome of Tuesday's meeting could
affect the survival of Clerides' government.
	   rr
