</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four Westerners killed in bloody end to Yemen kidnapping
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: For AMs. Combines urgent series, ADDS details. &QL; 
 &UR; By AHMAD AL-HAJ &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ The kidnapping of 16 Western tourists in
Yemen ended with the deaths of four hostages Tuesday as security
forces confronted the Islamic extremist captors.
	   A statement issued by Yemen's Interior Ministry said that the
kidnappers killed three of the captives and that a fourth, who was
wounded in the incident, died later in hospital.
	   It was not immediately clear if the fourth victim, a British
man, had been harmed by the kidnappers or wounded in the shootout
between the Islamic extremists and some 200 Yemen security forces.
	   The Interior Ministry said that all of the dead were British.
But in London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said the dead
included three British hostages and an Australian.
	   Cook also urged British nationals to leave Yemen.
	   Two others _ British and American women _ were hospitalized with
injuries, the ministry said.
	   The Interior Ministry said that three of the kidnappers also
were killed and that one of them was an Egyptian national.
	   Earlier reports said a policeman was killed and three wounded in
the shootout.
	   The tourists were kidnapped on Monday near the southern town of
Mawdiyah, about 200 kilometers (175 miles) south of the Yemen
capital San`a.
	   Their convoy of five vehicles was ambushed by men who opened
fire on their police escorts. The kidnappers threatened to kill the
tourists if the police did not back off, Yemen security officials
said.
	   Tribesmen in unruly Yemen have frequently kidnapped tourists to
pressure the government into providing them with new roads, water
supply or clinics. But the hostages generally have been treated as
guests and released unharmed.
	   Four Germans are being held at present by a tribe in northeast
Yemen. The kidnappers are demanding more schools, hospitals and
telephone lines in their area.
	   The latest incident marked the first time an abduction was
carried out by Islamic extremists.
	   Security officials said the kidnappers belong to Islamic Jihad,
many of whose leaders fought Russian troops in Afghanistan. The
group is believed to have about 200 members.
	   The Interior Ministry statement said that members of the
``extremist terrorist gang'' killed three of the captives _ two men
and a woman.
	   ``They proceeded in killing the captives after refusing any
attempts at negotiations, which led security forces to storm the
area to prevent further bloodshed and ensure the safe release of
the rest of the hostages,'' the statement continued.
	   One of the wounded hostages, a Briton, died later in hospital,
the statement said.
	   The bodies of the slain tourists and the injured were ferried by
government helicopter to the Republican Hospital in the southern
port city of Aden, security officials said.
	   The other tourists were escorted by troops to a hotel in Aden,
they said.
	   After the shootout, security forces detained scores of suspected
Islamic extremists, the officials said. All spoke on condition
their names not be used.
	   The kidnappers had demanded the release of their leader, Saleh
Haidara al-Atwi, who was detained two weeks ago as part of a
government crackdown on Islamic vigilantes enforcing strict Islamic
rules in southern Yemen, Yemen security officials said.
	   Islamic Jihad members reportedly were flogging women who did not
observe the Islamic dress code and men for selling and drinking
alcohol, which is forbidden in Islam.
	   The kidnappers also wanted the release of another leader, the
officials said. They did not identify him.
	   The group also ran a military camp in southern Yemen, security
officials said.
	   Yemen was once a haven for Islamic militant fugitives from other
countries, but the government has expelled many of them.
	   Before the shootout, Yemeni officials tried to negotiate with
the Islamic extremists for the release of the tourists as Yemeni
security forces encircled the area.
	   Ahmad Ali Mohsen, governor of Abyan province, where the
kidnapping took place, was leading the talks with leaders of the
Al-Fadl tribe, to which the kidnappers belong, an official at the
governor's office said.
	   A London-based Islamic human rights group said Tuesday that it
had contacted the kidnappers late Monday and received assurances
that they would not harm the hostages.
	   ``They promised not to harm the hostages,'' said a spokesman for
the Islamic Observation Center. ``We hold the Yemeni government
responsible for the deaths. The way the authorities handled the
situation was barbaric and irresponsible.''
 &UR; prvs-ti/eap
</TEXT>
