<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Euro All-Stars </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dino Radja and Bodiroga lead East to Euro All-Star win
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Former Celtics player Dino Radja and Dejan
Bodiroga Tuesday hit key baskets down the stretch Tuesday as the
East beat the West in the European All-Star game.
	   It was Bodiroga, although he had several former NBA players as
teammates, who poured in six straight points that wiped out a
two-point West lead with 3:20 left as the East won 104-98.
	   Bodiroga, playing for Greece's Panathinaikos Athen, scored 15
points for the East in a match played under near NBA-like rules
including a 24-second clock.
	   Radja led the team with 17 and dunked twice with time running
out to kill the West's last hopes.
	   Carlton Myers of Italy's TeamSystem Bologna was the game MVP
after hitting for 20 points while former Miami Heat player Pedrag
Danilovic added 19.
	   For a while it appeared Myers and Danilovic, who had 16 of his
points in the second half, would break the West jinx. The East has
now won all three editions of the all-star contest.
	   Danilovic, of Italy's Kinder Bologna, poured in nine points as
the West went on an 18 to 10 run to start the second half that put
them up 69-65.
	   Myers, who also won the three-point contest at halftime, then
took over by firing threes.
	   A crowd of 7,500 watching the match came hoping to see
spectacular moves in a game -- that like most all-star contests --
didn't really heat up until the fourth quarter.
	   Fenerbahnce Istanbul's Conrad McRae set the crowd buzzing when
he missed a power dunk that shook the rim and would have given the
East a 82-81 lead.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
