u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Saudi-Gulf-Iraq     12-29 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Gulf-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gulf states hold meeting over disagreements on Iraq
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ Foreign ministers from Gulf
Cooperation Council states met Tuesday in Riyadh in a special
session intended to resolve differences over convening an Arab
League meeting on Iraq.
	   A meeting of the 22-member league was postponed Monday, two days
before it was to consider calling an Arab summit on the plight of
the Iraqis following the U.S.-British airstrikes in mid-December.
	   Holding a summit remains a divisive issue among Arab leaders
since they disagree over whether to let Iraq back into the Arab
fold eight years after it invaded neighboring Kuwait in 1990 and
set off the Gulf War.
	   Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported in Cairo that the
meeting ended late Tuesday night but that no official communique
would be issued.
	   The session was held under extreme secrecy, without Saudi
officials announcing the arrival of foreign ministers from the
other states in the six-nation GCC.
	   The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates,
Oman, Bahrain and Qatar in a federation for economic development
and defense.
	   A Gulf diplomat, who spoke on customary condition of anonymity,
said postponement of the league meeting was the main reason for
differences among the GCC states.
	   The diplomat said some members were angered that Saudi Arabia's
foreign minister, Prince Saud al-Faisal, visited Cairo on Sunday to
ask Egypt to back the kingdom's request that any meeting be put off
until after Ramadan. He said they felt the trip should not have
been made without consultation with other GCC members.
	   Muslims fast from dawn to dusk during Ramadan, which
commemorates Mohammed's receiving the Koran from God. The holy
month ends in mid-January.
	   On Tuesday, Iraq's Foreign Ministry criticized the delay in the
league meeting, saying the Arab leaders were ignoring the feelings
of their people who demonstrated through much of the Arab world
against the U.S-British attacks.
 &UR; str-my-ggl
</TEXT>
