<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Inflation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey nearly halves inflation in 1998 to 56 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey succeeded in nearly halving its
inflation rate this year, bringing it down to 56 percent, Finance
Minister Zekeriya Temizel announced Tuesday.
	   Slashing at inflation _ the worst woe of Turkey's developing but
uncertain economy _ was one of the main economic targets of the
minority government led by center-right leader Mesut Yilmaz.
	   Yilmaz was ousted last month after 17 months in power over
allegations that he entertained ties with the mob and tampered with
the sale of a state bank. He is the acting premier until the next
government is formed.
	   His government, which gained the praise of the International
Monetary Fund with its rigorous fiscal policies, aimed at reducing
wholesale inflation to 50 percent from the 97 percent of 1997.
	   Meanwhile, a commission gathering governmental officials, trade
unionists and employers, announced Tuesday that the monthly minimum
wage would increase on Jan. 1 to some 78 million Turkish lira (dlrs
251) gross, twice the amount compared to the minimum wage set in
January 1998.
	   (ht-dj-fd)
</TEXT>
