<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ireland-Obit-Hatfield </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Actor Hurd Hatfield of ``Dorian Gray'' fame dies at 80
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CORK, Ireland (AP) _ Hurd Hatfield, the American leading man
famed for his portrayal of the title character in the Oscar-winning
``The Picture of Dorian Gray,'' has died.
	   Hatfield died at a friend's house in Monkstown, Ireland, on
Friday, the Cork Examiner newspaper said. He was 80.
	   A New York native, Hatfield had lived in Ireland since the early
1970s.
	   He never escaped from his portrayal in the movie version of
Oscar Wilde's novel about how the vanity of a society dandy returns
to haunt him in the form of a portrait of him that ages while he
remains eternally youthful, seeing the world he loves decaying
around him.
	   Hatfield was forever associated with that role he played
opposite Angela Landsbury in 1945, despite his having appeared in
20 other movies and scores of television and stage productions.
	   ``That accursed role. Why is he still all anyone ever sees?'' he
reportedly told The Guardian newspaper in an interview in 1992, 40
years after the movie was released.
	   ``They forget everything else, all the other parts _ ``The Count
of Monte Cristo,'' ``Crimes of the Heart'' with Sissy Spacek, ``The
Left Handed Gun'' with Paul Newman _ all they remember is Dorian
Gray,'' he said.
	   It is said that when casting for the film in 1944, director
Albert Lewins took one look at Hatfield and exclaimed: ``Look, it
is him! It is Dorian Gray!''
	   Hatfield told The Guardian he always thought he was miscast in
that role, adding that he had no confidence in his appearance.
	   ``I almost walked away. Isn't that funny, I wonder what would
have happened in my life,'' he said.
	   William Rukard Hurd Hatfield was born Dec. 7 1918 and came to
England to study acting at the Chekhov Theater Studio in
Devonshire.
	   He made his Hollywood debut in ``Dragon Seed'' in 1944. ``The
Picture of Dorian Gray'' was his second movie. He won an Emmy
nomination for best supporting actor for ``The Invincible Mr.
Disraeli'' in 1963.
	   Friends said a private service was planned for Wednesday and
that Hatfield was to be cremated on Thursday, the Cork Examiner
said.
	   His ashes were to be scattered in the grounds of his home in
Rothcormac, in County Cork, the newspaper said. A public memorial
service will be planned for sometime after the new year.
	   No immediate family members were named as survivors.
	   (er)
</TEXT>
