r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Kosovo-DressRehearsal 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kosovo-Dress Rehearsal, 1st Ld-Writethru,0750 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The battles around Podujevo: preparations for the spring
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: REWRITES and RECASTS throughout, no pick up &QL; 
 &UR; By VESELIN TOSHKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PODUJEVO, Yugoslavia (AP) _ In the snowy hills of northern
Kosovo, both Serbs and ethnic Albanians fear that the four days of
fighting which raged here last week were a dress rehearsal for
fiercer battles to come.
	   Clashes that erupted here Christmas Eve added at least 15 people
to the more than 1,000 dead in Kosovo since February, when Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic launched a crackdown on
independence-minded ethnic Albanians.
	   Last week's clashes were halted by international monitors sent
to Kosovo under an agreement reached Oct. 12 between Milosevic and
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke to end seven months of fighting.
	   But the bitterness remains. Ethnic Albanian rebels appear
gearing up for a new round of fighting, possibly in the spring. And
Serb civilians are anxious for the government to finish off the
rebels, regardless of threats of NATO intervention.
	   ``Soon, there will be no Serbs here unless the state takes
measures and finishes off with these bandits and savages,'' said
local Serb official Srboslav Bisercic, referring to the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
	   Although this area has been quiet for the past two days, ethnic
Albanian rebels show no signs of backing down. If the rebels
capture Podujevo, they would control the main highway between
Kosovo's capital Pristina and the heartland of Serbia, Yugoslavia's
main republic.
	   KLA trenches lie only a few hundred meters (yards) away from the
30-kilometer (20-mile) road linking Podujevo with the provincial
capital Pristina.
	   ``The KLA will do everything to keep these positions,'' said
Fehim Rexhepi, an ethnic Albanian journalist who reports on the
rebel movement.
	   Caught in the middle are the hundreds of unarmed monitors sent
by the 54-nation Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe to verify compliance with the Oct. 12 truce.
	   On Tuesday, OSCE said 100 additional verifiers were on their way
to Kosovo, bringing to 700 the number deployed in the province to
help keep the peace. In a few weeks, OSCE expects to have the full
compliment of 2,000 verifiers in the Serbian province.
	   But critics among both the Serb and ethnic Albanian communities
have questioned whether unarmed verifiers can long contain a
conflict, given the bitterness on both sides.
	   On Tuesday, the chief Serb official in Kosovo, Zoran
Andjelkovic, told local Serbs here that the OSCE verifiers have no
business telling the government ``what to do and how to deal with
the terrorists.''
	   ``It is their job only to verify the facts on the ground and
inform their superiors of their findings,'' Andjelkovic said. ``And
the facts clearly show that the criminal gangs are terrorizing the
civilian population.''
	   The Serb-led government fears that the Oct. 12 agreement has
given the ethnic Albanian rebels time to regroup, retrain and
prepare for more battles when warmer weather will enable them to
smuggle more weapons and fighters across the snow-covered passes
from their sanctuaries in Albania.
	   According to Rexhepi, the guerrillas have already reorganized
and increased their presence in the Podujevo area. He estimates
that the KLA has deployed between 2,000 and 3,000 guerrillas around
this town.
	   He said total KLA strength has grown to about 6,000
province-wide since the Oct. 12 agreement.
	   ``They are more disciplined, better equipped and prepared for
any battle than they were several months ago,'' Rexhepi said.
	   Many of the villages in the Podujevo area are deserted, except
for uniformed KLA fighters. They are particularly strong in the
nearby village of Lapastica, where hundreds of ethnic Albanian
refugees have fled in wake of the latest fighting.
	   In Podujevo, 2 kilometers (1.5 miles) northeast of Lapastica,
Serbs are anxious and fearful of what will happen to them in the
coming months.
	   On Tuesday, a group of nervous Serb men smoked cigarettes as
they waited for news on a police effort to evacuate civilians from
rebel territory.
	   ``My mother and father are there,'' one Serb said, refusing to
give his name. ``They wouldn't listen to me when I told them to
evacuate in time.''
	   Another cursed the West for pressuring the government to halt
the crackdown in October. ``Our hands are tied,'' he said. ``The
world is against us.''
</TEXT>
