</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru,0327 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels attack police post, battle militias
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS new 7th and 8th grafs to change 'denied' to 'discounted',
expand army quote. No pick up &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ As peace talks approached, leftist
rebels attacked a police post and battled with right-wing
paramilitary fighters, authorities said Tuesday.
	   The fighting was taking place a week before negotiations between
the guerrillas and President Andres Pastrana, who is hoping to end
the 34-year conflict. The talks set for Jan. 7 are going forward
without a cease-fire.
	   Police said one officer was killed and three others were wounded
when rebels from the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or
FARC, overran a garrison in Nutibara, a village 190 miles (310
kilometers) northwest of Bogota in Antioquia state.
	   Nine officers were missing in the overnight assault, in which
rebels also blew up an electrical power station, burned down
civilian homes and downed a bridge, police said.
	   The men may have been kidnapped by the rebels, who previously
held about 350 police and soldiers seized in attacks during the
past two years
	   In separate fighting, clashes were also reported Tuesday between
the FARC and paramilitary groups in northern Cordoba state, a
stronghold of right-wing militias.
	   Army leaders discounted rumors that Carlos Castano_ the fugitive
chief of the United Autodefense Forces of Colombia _ was killed
during the combat in Murrucucu, a town 255 miles (410 kilometers)
northwest of Bogota.
	   Report's of Castano's death ``have no basis in reality at this
moment,'' armed services chief Gen. Fernando Tapias told a news
conference. Tapias said troops had not yet reached the scene of the
reported fighting.
	   The rumors swept the local media Tuesday after a well-known
militia confidant said in a radio interview that Castano had
``disappeared'' after guerrillas overran a fortified paramilitary
base.
</TEXT>
