<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-Anti-Doping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIS president defends anti-doping system in skiing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BORMIO, Italy (AP) _ Rejecting suggestions of careless drug
testing in skiing, FIS president GianFranco Kasper said Tuesday
that regular urine tests were carried out at World Cup races in
France and Italy over the last month.
	   Kasper conceded however that blood tests, urged by some athletes
in the frame of a stricter anti-doping campaign in Alpine skiing,
have not been enforced because they are not reliable enough at the
moment.
	   ``Our experts believe that at the moment blood tests are not
reliable enough in Alpine skiing,'' the president of the
International Ski Federation said.
	   Blood tests have been instead carried out in cross-country
skiing ``where they can help detect EPO in an endurance sport.''
	   Italian ski star Deborah Compagnoni, a three-time Olympic and
world champion, had lamented on Monday that anti-doping tests were
seldom carried out in Alpine skiing and that combined urine-blood
tests were necessary to dispel suspects of doping use in the sport.
	   Kasper said FIS was ready to enforce blood and even hair tests
if the International Olympic Committee (IOC) congress on doping,
scheduled in Lausanne in February, ``brings new and reliable
anti-doping controls.''
 &UR; (pv)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
