<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-US Military, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two U.S. servicemen arrested on suspicion of attempted murder
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS rank in 7th graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese police have arrested two U.S. Air Force
servicemen stationed near Tokyo on suspicion of attempting to kill
a 39-year-old Japanese by hitting him with a car, a police
spokesman said Tuesday.
	   Takeyasu Kasai, spokesman of Tokyo's Fussa Police, identified
the two arrested as Senior Airman Anthony Udy, 25, and Airman
Arthur Tuttle, 21 _ both assigned to Yokota Air Base in western
Tokyo.
	   Hometowns for the two were not immediately known, Kasai said.
	   Police allege both men hit Yasutoshi Ishizuka in the face while
walking on a street near the base early Monday morning. When
Ishizuka called police on a portable phone, a car driven by Udy hit
him from behind, Kasai said.
	   Ishizuka suffered a broken left leg, and his injuries will
require two months of treatment, Kasai said.
	   Police later found the two airmen were drunk at the time and on
their way to the base after drinking, the spokesman said. Police
are investigating what led to the two airmen's alleged initial
attack on Ishizuka.
	   Maj. Stephen Clutter, spokesman for Yokota Air Base, said the
base will express regret over the incident and cooperate fully with
the Japanese police investigation.
	   There are 47,000 U.S. military service people stationed in Japan
under a mutual security treaty.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
