<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0674 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Four Westerners held hostage by militant
Islamic tribesmen were killed on Tuesday as Yemeni security forces
stormed their hideout. Yemen's Interior Ministry said that the
kidnappers killed three of the captives and that a fourth, who was
wounded in the incident, died later in a hospital. In London,
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said the dead included three
British hostages and an Australian. The U.S. State Department later
said an American was wounded. (YEMEN-KIDNAPPING)
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ A defiant Iraq said Tuesday that its
aircraft are flying in the no-fly zones patrolled by U.S. and
British warplanes and its anti-aircraft batteries remain ready to
fire on allied planes. The statement comes only a day after U.S.
warplanes opened fire on an Iraqi anti-aircraft position in the
northern no-fly zone, killing four Iraqi soldiers. Washington said
the planes attacked after Iraq shot missiles at the aircraft.
Iraq's latest move appears to be aimed at building support among
Arabs who angrily protested mid-December's U.S.-British airstrikes
_ but whose governments did little to back Iraq's demands for
lifting eight-year-old U.N. sanctions on the country. Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan voiced Iraq's latest defiance when
asked in an interview with Associated Press Television News if Iraq
was flying aircraft in the no-fly zones. ``We are doing it right
now,'' he replied. (IRAQ)
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Saying they were ``very sorry,'' but
refusing to accept responsibility, two top Khmer Rouge leaders
asked Cambodians to ``let bygones be bygones'' Tuesday and forget
about the genocide of the 1970s. Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea were
flown by helicopter from a former rebel stronghold to the capital
to defect _ in effect, surrender _ to Prime Minister Hun Sen after
he pledged they would not face trial for crimes against humanity.
At a news conference, they were asked by journalists _ many of them
Cambodians who lost family members _ if they felt any remorse for
causing the deaths of as many as 2 million of their countrymen out
of a population of about 9 million. ``Yes, sorry, very sorry,''
Khieu Samphan said, looking red and sullen. (CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE)
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ A top rebel commander on Tuesday
said his forces would begin attacking Sierra Leone's capital within
two days if the government fails to agree to immediate talks to be
mediated by the Organization of African Unity. ``This is our
ultimatum,'' rebel leader Sam Bockarie said in a telephone
interview from his hideout in the countryside. ``If a dialogue is
not started we will have to invade Freetown. They have 48 hours.''
The renewed threat comes after Sierra Leone's defense force
retreated from the key central town of Makeni and were redeploying
to defend the capital. The rebel Revolutionary United Front along
with allies from Sierra Leone's disbanded military are demanding
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's resignation and have rejected an
offer of amnesty in return for their weapons. (SIERRA LEONE)
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ After the worst outbreak of fighting
in months, more international monitors were sent Tuesday to Kosovo
to shore up the fragile truce between government forces and ethnic
Albanian rebels. Meanwhile, NATO repeated warnings it stands ready
to intervene if the two sides fail to respect the Oct. 12 agreement
between Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke, which ended seven months of fighting and averted
NATO airstrikes. That agreement was severely strained by four days
of fighting between government forces and the ethnic Albanian
Kosovo Liberation Army, which erupted Christmas Eve and left at
least 15 people dead. Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia's main
republic Serbia, was generally quiet Tuesday. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
</TEXT>
