<HEADER>
w2105 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APTopFinancialNews     12-29 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0622 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Dow industrials rose within 55 points of a
new record Tuesday, advancing for an eighth straight session for
its longest winning streak in two years. The Standard and Poor's
500 index and the Nasdaq composite reached new highs again despite
some profit-taking among leading Internet stocks. The Dow Jones
industrial average erased an early 39-point loss and rose 94.23
points _ or by 1 percent _ to 9,320.98, closing fast on the Nov. 23
record of 9,374.27. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia produced an estimated 303.5 million metric
tons of oil in 1998, and exported 134 million metric tons, the Fuel
and Energy Ministry said Tuesday. Oil exports are Russia's main
revenue earner, and the cash-strapped government has been trying to
keep up exports, despite the slide of world oil prices. This year's
exports will mark a 6.3-percent increase from 1997, the Fuel and
Energy Ministry said, according to the Interfax news agency. But
revenues were down considerably, officials have said. Next year,
Russia is expected to produce between 284 million metric tons and
296 million metric tons of oil _ down nearly 5 percent from 1998,
the ministry said. (RUSSIA-OIL)
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Kuwait's northern oil fields could be developed
and operated by interested foreign companies for about dlrs 7
billion in five years, the oil minister said in remarks published
Tuesday. The minister, Sheik Saud al-Sabah, told local newspaper
editors on Monday that the operation agreements Kuwait was seeking
with American and British companies would double production from
these fields to more than 900,000 barrels a day. No contracts or
memorandums of understanding have yet been signed with any
companies, the minister said. But the firms approached by Kuwait
have reacted positively and they believe Kuwait's proposal is
``unique,'' he added. (KUWAIT-OIL)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia attracted dlrs 2 billion in foreign direct
investment in 1998, only about half what was invested the year
before, a news agency reported Tuesday, citing an Economics
Ministry official. The relatively paltry foreign capital inflows,
given the country's size, reflected investors' concerns over the
Russian economy, heightened by the recent financial crisis and the
ruble's collapse, Vladimir Yefimov said. ``Unfortunately, this is a
very small volume given the state of our industry,'' Yefimov told
the ITAR-Tass news agency. Direct foreign investment in Russia
reached dlrs 3.9 billion in 1997 before collapsing this year.
Yefimov predicted that direct investment _ that is, investment
directly in companies, as opposed to stocks or other financial
instruments _ would reach dlrs 2.5 billion in 1999. (RUSSIA-FOREIGN
INVESTMENT)
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Sweden's decision not to adopt the euro
on Jan. 1, when 11 other European Union countries do, denies
significant cost savings to carmaker AB Volvo, a company official
said Tuesday. ``Our main competitors are in the euro zone, and if
Sweden would have joined the single currency, our costs would have
been several hundred millions of kronor less,'' said Lars Persson,
in charge of Volvo's euro strategy. That's tens of millions of
dollars. Volvo plans to adopt the euro as a group currency from
Jan. 1, 2001. Projected benefits should start earlier. As currency
exchange operations in the 11 other countries _ including Germany,
France and Italy _ tend to disappear, price comparisons will be
more transparent. (SWEDEN-VOLVO)
</TEXT>
