<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0990 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Matthias Hoffmann, Arthur Kostler, a
religious ruling on the use of computers, Jim Caviezel, Gerhard
Schroeder and Steven Spielberg . &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANNHEIM, Germany (AP) _ Both sides filed appeals Tuesday in the
tax evasion conviction of Matthias Hoffmann, a former concert
promoter who helped organize the Three Tenors events.
	   Hoffmann, 47, was convicted last week of evading dlrs 9 million
in taxes and was sentenced to five years and eight months in
prison.
	   Prosecutors had sought a sentence of seven years, while the
defense had asked for less than five.
	   Appeals were filed with the Federal Court of Justice in
Karlsruhe, but both sides declined to comment.
	   The tenors _ Luciano Pavarotti, Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo _
and soprano Montserrat Caballe were named as suspects last month
for allegedly helping Hoffmann evade taxes. They are still under
investigation.
	   ___
	   EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) _ A bronze bust of the late writer
Arthur Koestler, alleged in a recent biography to have been a
serial rapist, was removed Tuesday from a foyer in Edinburgh
University.
	   The university said the move was due to fears of vandalism.
	   ``The university decided, as a temporary precaution, to remove
the bust from the Department of Psychology's main entrance hall
into another part of the department, in case anyone decided to take
action against the bust,'' a spokeswoman for the university said.
	   Koestler, who died in 1983 at age 77 in a suicide pact with his
wife, was described this year in David Cesarani's biography, ``The
Homeless Mind,'' as being a heavy drinker who was routinely violent
toward women.
	   British newspapers reported Tuesday that some female students
were uncomfortable with the statue. However, the university said it
had received no complaints directly from students.
	   Koestler was a former Communist whose best-known novel
``Darkness at Noon'' was an indictment of Stalinist terror. He was
held as a prisoner under Gen. Francisco Franco during the Spanish
Civil War while working as a journalist, and settled in England in
1940.
	   He left dlrs 800,000 in his will to set up a chair of
parapsychology at a British university to investigate the
paranormal after his death. The bequest was awarded to Edinburgh
University, which erected the bust in his honor.
	   ___
	   BNEI BRAK, Israel (AP) _ A leading Orthodox rabbi has ruled that
the word ``God'' may be erased from a computer screen or disk,
because the pixels do not constitute real letters.
	   According to Jewish law, printed matter with the word _
``elohim'' in Hebrew, and its manifestations in any other language
_ must be stored or ritually buried.
	   Rabbi Moshe Shaul Klein published his ruling this week in a
computer magazine aimed at Orthodox Jews, ``Mahsheva Tova.'' Klein
was responding to a question from a reader who was anxious about
whether the ban on erasing the variations on the word ``God''
applied to computers.
	   The rabbi, prominent in ultra-Orthodox circles in this Tel Aviv
suburb, ruled that the letters may be erased.
	   ``The letters on a computer screen are an assemblage of pixels,
dots of light, what have you,'' the rabbi's assistant, Yossef Hayad
explained Tuesday.
	   ``Even when you save it to disk, it's not like you're throwing
anything more than a sequence of ones and zeroes away,'' Hayad
said.
	   The existence of the magazine _ a pun that suggests both ``Good
Computing'' and ``Worthy Thinking'' _ reflects the growing
incursion of modern implements into the world of the
ultra-Orthodox.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Jim Caviezel knows what it's like to consider
giving up.
	   After nearly seven years of frustration and bit parts, the
30-year-old actor was contemplating moving with his schoolteacher
wife, Kerry, back to his native Washington state and studying
chiropractic medicine when he won a lead role in Terrence Malick's
``The Thin Red Line,'' a World War II film which opened last week.
	   ``I was almost out the door,'' Caviezel said in Tuesday's Daily
News.
	   Shortly before that, Caviezel had been up for a role in ``The
Hi-Lo Country,'' a Western directed by Stephen Frears. That part
eventually went to Billy Crudup.
	   ``I had been close before, but I thought maybe I had a shot with
this,'' he said. ``He took the wind out of me.''
	   But the wind was restored when he got Malick's call about ``The
Thin Red Line.''
	   ``It's like winning the lottery,'' he said. ``Everything from
this point on is just cake.''
	   ___
	   HAMBURG, Germany (AP) _ Talk about The Real World.
	   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's first New Year's address
to the nation will be carried first on the music channel MTV.
	   MTV _ the channel that has brought viewers ``The Real World,''
``Singled Out'' and ``FANatic'' _ announced Monday that it will air
the taped address during an afternoon New Year's Eve special.
Germany's public stations traditionally broadcast the chancellor's
New Year's speech after their evening news programs.
	   MTV said the decision to run Schroeder's address was a reaction
to the positive response it got to its German election night
coverage in September.
	   MTV also plans to repeat the address in the evening, during its
``Dancefloor Mix'' show.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   UNIVERSAL CITY, California (AP) _ E.T. tugged on viewers'
heartstrings in the movie ``E.T.: The Extra-Terrestrial.'' In 1999,
he'll be tugging on your seat belt.
	   The lovable alien with the glowing index finger will be a safety
ambassador in a ``Buckle-Up-America'' public service TV ad
campaign, organizers said Monday.
	   ``E.T. holds a special place in so many hearts,'' Steven
Spielberg, who directed the cute critter in his 1982 debut, said
Monday.
	   ``I'm extremely pleased that the values symbolized by E.T. will
be used to aid and address the issues of safe driving.''
</TEXT>
