<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Costa Rica-Turtle Eggs,0424 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Costa Rica lets villagers harvest eggs of endangered turtles
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY301-306 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   OSTIONAL, Costa Rica (AP) _ Several times a year, thousands of
olive ridley turtles laboriously drag themselves up onto a pristine
Pacific beach to deposit their eggs.
	   Each time, hundreds of Costa Ricans follow in the endangered
creatures' tracks to scoop up the eggs.
	   The scene isn't altogether unusual in Central America, where the
poor get by any way they can. What's unusual is that it's legal,
despite a ban on hunting the turtles, which were near extinction
not long ago.
	   Authorities have given 300 members of a local cooperative
permission to gather eggs during the first three days of each wave
of egg-laying turtles. The turtles come ashore for up to a week
several times during the August-December season.
	   The turtle eggs are sold as delicacies to augment the villagers'
meager incomes.
	   If the villagers didn't collect the eggs, they would be trampled
by other turtles coming ashore to lay their eggs, officials say.
	   The harvest in Ostional, a national refuge 185 miles (300
kilometers) west of San Jose, the capital, is ``biologically
viable'' and helps the local community's economy, biologist Randall
Arauz says.
	   Every year more than 200,000 of the endangered turtles arrive at
the park, depositing millions of eggs. Only about 8 percent of the
eggs mature fully because most are destroyed by crawling turtles,
Arauz says.
	   To the north of Ostional, thousands of giant sea turtles land at
Las Baulas National Park between October and March.
	   The arrival of the large creatures _ which can be more than 2
meters (6 1-2 feet) long and weigh 500 kilos (1,100 pounds) _
attracts hundreds of tourists, who are guided onto the beach at
night to witness the egg-laying.
	   Turtle fans also flock to Costa Rica's Atlantic Coast to visit
the famed Tortuguero National Park, where four different species of
turtles lay their eggs. Although it is a turtle sanctuary, the
government grants 1,600 permits each year for hunters to kill
turtles.
	   The environmental group Caribbean Conservation estimates illegal
hunters kill an additional 8,000 turtles, which can fetch more than
dlrs 45 each.
	   Arauz accuses Costa Rican authorities of failing to enforce the
anti-hunting law and says they don't allocate enough money for
guarding against poaching.
	   ``We have to learn that turtles can generate more money alive
than dead, because of the tourists they attract,'' he says. 	   
</TEXT>
