w2118 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Cambodia-Teaching     12-29 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Cambodia-Teaching Rights,0796 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Khmer Rouge official teaches human rights to ex-rebels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY314 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Mey Mann went off to Paris as a
young college student, and came back a leftist revolutionary.
	   But he later broke with his fellow founders of the Khmer Rouge
movement over the use of violence, and watched them go off into the
countryside to grow into a guerrilla army that became infamous for
its brutality.
	   Today, with the Khmer Rouge broken, Mey Mann is helping pick up
the pieces of his former colleagues' bloody legacy by teaching
Cambodians respect for basic human rights.
	   He says he does not know why the group's communist revolution
went terribly wrong _ why the charismatic young Saloth Sar he
studied with in Paris mutated into the ultra-radical Pol Pot who
led a regime that caused the deaths of as many as 2 million
Cambodians.
	   ``What I regret is that there was no good result from the
ideology we had at the beginning,'' says Mey Mann, now 77. ``Our
dream was for social justice, but what happened was not that.''
	   Pol Pot is now dead, the victim of an apparent heart attack in
April, and his once-fierce army has been reduced to a small band of
desperate guerrillas.
	   Mey Mann is working to rehabilitate the people the Khmer Rouge
left behind. Deeply involved in humanitarian work since 1979, he is
head of the U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights office in
Pailin, a one-time rebel stronghold near the border with Thailand.
	   Opened in September, the office is training school teachers and
former Khmer Rouge commanders so they can in turn instruct
civilians and soldiers about human rights principles.
	   It sounds odd. The Khmer Rouge were some of history's greatest
violators of human rights. They won a civil war in 1975 and
attempted to turn Cambodia into an agrarian utopia by enslaving the
entire population in labor camps.
	   Disease, hunger and systematic execution caused the deaths of
one Cambodian in five before a Vietnamese invasion toppled the
Khmer Rouge regime in 1979. But loyalists fought on for years.
	   The movement took a fatal blow only when thousands of guerrillas
in Pailin and other bases started defecting to the government in
1996. The last Khmer Rouge holdouts laid down their weapons in
early December, ending more than 20 years of civil war.
	   Mey Mann says the challenge of integrating the former guerrillas
into mainstream society is, ironically, made somewhat easier by the
discipline they followed as warriors.
	   Yet it's clear human rights are a long way from taking hold in
an area where summary executions were the accepted form of
punishment a short time ago.
	   ``Human rights for this integrated zone is something new for
them,'' Mey Mann says. ``They would like to understand what human
rights are exactly, but it will take some time.''
	   David Hawk, chief of education for the U.N. human rights effort
in Cambodia, praises Mey Mann's efforts in Pailin and brushes aside
questions about his past.
	   ``He had an interest in human rights and human rights education
in the late 1980s and later did translations for our office,'' Hawk
says. ``He was well known among educated Cambodians as a teacher
from the old society. His student days in Paris in the 1950s _ that
was a long, long time ago.''
	   Mey Mann traveled to Paris in 1949 to attend college and soon
met fellow Cambodian students who would become the nucleus of the
Khmer Rouge death machine _ Pol Pot, Ieng Sary and Khieu Samphan.
	   They craved independence for their country _ which was won from
France in 1953 _ and were swept up by the ideals of socialist
revolution. They returned home and preached a Marxist gospel to
growing numbers of Cambodians disaffected with the rule of Prince
Norodom Sihanouk.
	   Mey Mann says he last saw Pol Pot in person in 1963, just before
the Khmer Rouge leader and many other communists fled repression in
Phnom Penh and joined militants in the countryside.
	   ``He had charisma. Everybody loved him at that time,'' Mey Mann
recalls. ``I wish he was still alive so the international community
could bring him to trial and understand how he was.''
	   Mey Mann says he did not agree with the shift in emphasis to
military struggle, so he stayed in the capital and was forced to
reduce his political activities.
	   He says that when the Khmer Rouge captured Phnom Penh in 1975
and emptied the city of its inhabitants, a guerrilla commander
first asked him to stay behind. But after checking with his
superiors, the commander sent Mey Mann off into the countryside to
toil in a labor camp.
	   Mey Mann was separated from his family and never saw his four
children again. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
