<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0549 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia seeks to have Kosovo rebels declared terrorists
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By VESELIN TOSHKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ While diplomats try to shore up the
shaky Kosovo truce, Yugoslavia is urging the United Nations to
declare the province's ethnic Albanian rebels as terrorists and
crack down on their support network abroad.
	   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said an
additional 100 international observers have begun arriving in
Kosovo to try to prevent a recurrence of last week's four days of
fighting which severely strained an Oct. 12 peace accord.
	   The fighting, which erupted Christmas Eve, claimed at least 15
lives and sent an estimated 5,000 civilians fleeing villages around
the northern Kosovo town of Podujevo.
	   Although international verifiers managed to arrange a truce,
tensions in the area remain high. OSCE sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said four bodies were found Tuesday, two in
Kosovska Mitrovica and two others near the southern town of
Prizren.
	   The Serb Media Center reported a fifth body _ a 55-year-old
ethnic Albanian man _ was found near the southwestern town of Pec.
	   William Walker, an American diplomat who heads the OSCE's peace
verification force, said the additional 100 observers will bring to
about 700 the number of Americans, Canadians, Europeans and others
who are trying to ease tensions between Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
	   OSCE officials said they expect to have the full compliment of
2,000 verifiers on the ground in the province next month. Kosovo is
a province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's main republic.
	   ``We have to do whatever we can to stop violence,'' Walker said
Tuesday. ``That's what we're here for.''
	   Although Walker and his teams managed to bring an end to last
week's fighting, tensions remain high between Serbs and ethnic
Albanian rebels, who are demanding independence for the majority
Albanian province.
	   The spokesman for the ethnic Albanian rebels, Adem Demaci, said
the guerrillas will respect the truce ``but we will defend
ourselves with all means if necessary.''
	   Yugoslavia's Serb-led government claims the ethnic Albanian
Kosovo Liberation Army is a terrorist organization, which receives
financial support from Albanian expatriate communities in
Switzerland, Germany and elsewhere in Western Europe.
	   On Tuesday, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic asked
the United Nations to include the KLA in its list of terrorist
groups, a move which would pave the way to freezing foreign funds
and cracking down on supporters abroad.
	   In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Jovanovic
accused the KLA of exploiting the Oct. 12 truce negotiated by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke, which ended seven months of fighting.
	   Since the October agreement, which averted the threat of NATO
airstrikes, Jovanovic said the rebels have carried out 470
``terrorist attacks,'' including the killing of ethnic Albanians
loyal to the government.
	   Jovanovic claimed the KLA has links with ``organized
international terrorism.'' He called for an ``explicit
condemnation'' of the KLA and the closing down KLA liaison offices
in Western Europe.
</TEXT>
