<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,1118 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
and Mexico
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from: Argentina, Guatemala, Suriname, Nicaragua
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ Authorities on Tuesday arrested a
fugitive ex-naval officer accused of stealing babies during
Argentina's 1976-83 `dirty war' against political leftists and
dissidents.
	   Naval security officers took Jorge Eduardo Acosta into custody
at Marine headquarters, where he surfaced two weeks after a federal
judge issued an arrest warrant for him when he failed to make a
Dec. 15 court appearance.
	   Acosta was later handed over to police.
	   He is wanted in an investigation into charges of a systematic
plan existed during the military dictatorship for the illicit
adoption of more than 200 children born to political prisoners.
	   From 1976-78, Acosta headed up the Navy Mechanics School, a
military training facility later converted into a secret killing
center. Many of the children's parents disappeared from there.
	   Prosecutors say the children, now in their 20s, were given to
military officials to be raised after their parents were murdered.
	   ___
	   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) _ Guatemalan President Alvaru Arzu on
Tuesday marked the second anniversary of the signing of peace
accords by unveiling a prominently located monument.
	   The monument, on a patio near the National Palace, consists of
two brown hands opened toward the sky. Vice President Luis Alberto
Flores began what Arzu said will be a daily event: placing a white
rose on the monument.
	   Guatemala's peace agreement between the government and leftist
guerrillas was signed Dec. 29, 1996 and ended 36 years of civil
war. The conflict left 200,000 people dead or missing.
	   The peace accord succeeded in ending the fighting and the
demobilized rebels have put down their arms. Yet critics charge
that progress has been slow in strengthening the judicial system
and increasing civilian control over the military.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ For President Ernesto Zedillo, the price of
democracy has become rather steep: about 2.8 billion dollars.
	   That's how much Zedillo would like to make taxpayers pay to
compensate for an unexpected revenue shortfall. But an
opposition-led congress won't let him, saying the government should
tighten its belt rather than the people's.
	   Time is running out for an agreement. Should congress fail to
approve a 1999 budget by Dec. 31, Mexico could face an
unprecedented crisis. No one knows for sure what would happen in
such a scenario, which is not foreseen by the Mexican Constitution.
	   ``The government has shown no sign of being willing to
compromise,'' said Adolfo Aguilar Zinser, an independent senator.
	   Zedillo's predecessors never had to compromise. Congressional
approval of presidential initiatives _ no matter how unpopular _
was a foregone conclusion in Mexico during the 68 years that the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party enjoyed a majority in
Congress.
	   That changed with last year's midterm elections when the party,
known as the PRI, lost control of Congress.
	   ___
	   JAPALA, Mexico (AP) _ Mechanical failure was the likely cause
for the crash of a Mexican navy plane that killed four people, a
navy spokesman said Tuesday.
	   The plane that crashed and exploded Monday had been conducting
practice landings in the Veracruz commercial airport on the coast
of the Gulf of Mexico.
	   The pilot and three mechanics on board were killed in the crash.
	   ___
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ The death toll in an explosion at a
sugar processing plant has reached 10 and a doctor said Tuesday the
prospects for the sole survivor are dim.
	   Marco Antonio Mejia, 42, suffered burns on 95 percent of his
body in an explosion Saturday at the Ingenio San Antonio plant in
the northwestern province of Chinandega,
	   ``Only God's will and Marco Antonio Mejia's supernatural
resistance keep him alive,'' Dr. Larry Ubeda told reporters.
	   The explosion occurred when workers tried to fix a broken pump.
The 10 other victims died within 48 hours of the blast.
	   ___
	   PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) _ Surinamese President Jules
Wijdenbosch will visit Cuba on Jan. 11, the government announced
Tuesday.
	   Wijdenbosch, whose South American country is the second-poorest
in the Western Hemisphere after Haiti, is facing increasing
pressure to resign and has been seeking support from other leaders
in the region.
	   Cuba, meanwhile, has courted Suriname as part of its push to
become a member of the 15-member Caribbean Community trade group.
	   Wijdenbosch's visit is to ``contribute to the aim of deepening
the relationship'' between the two countries, the government said.
	   Cuban President Fidel Castro has been invited to Suriname next
year, it said.
	   ___
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) _ Antiguan fugitive Trevor Jacobs
suffocated while stowing away in the landing gear well of a BWIA
jetliner, coroners in Trinidad said Tuesday.
	   Pathologist Ramnath Chandu Lal of the Trinidad Forensic Science
Center said Trevor Jacobs, a 30-year-old former police officer,
died from lack of air at high altitude during the flight from
Antigua to Trinidad.
	   Jacobs' frozen body was found Dec. 22 by workers doing
maintenance on the Lockheed 1011 in a hangar at Trinidad's Piarco
International Airport. It apparently had frozen in temperatures
near -40 degrees Fahrenheit (-40 degrees Celsius) at the airplane's
cruising altitude.
	   The flight began in Toronto, and police believe Jacobs climbed
aboard the aircraft during a stopover in Antigua.
	   Jacobs was wanted by Antiguan authorities on charges of
kidnapping 60-year-old Donna Pietracupa on Oct. 7. Pietracupa was
later released unharmed.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ In a massive relocation operation,
authorities helped hundreds of families move out of a working-class
neighborhood in western Mexico City Tuesday.
	   Some 460 families that had to be relocated after their land was
bought by a company accepted compensation payments ranging from
dlrs 3,000 to dlrs 5,000, while another 40 families opposed being
relocated, said Jose Manuel Hernandez, spokesperson at the Alvaro
Obregon borough.
	   The company, Poniente Santa Fe, also provided moving trucks at
no charge to those families that were willing to relocate,
Hernandez said.
	   He said the families had lived for up to 8 years in the
Tlayacapa neighborhood on the city's outskirts.
	   ``They're throwing us out because we can't pay in dollars,''
said Ernesto Olvera, who opposed the relocation, as he attended a
small protest. Many real estate deals in Mexico are negotiated in
dollars to prevent against further devaluations of the peso.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Latin American Briefs; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
