<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
McMillan and Cairns put NZ close to victory
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Craig McMillan and Chris Cairns
hit unbeaten half centuries and shared a record stand as New
Zealand moved towards a second test victory over India at the Basin
Reserve Wednesday.
	   Resuming on 73 for four and needing a further 140 to overhaul
the 213-run target, the home side was 188 for five at lunch on the
last day.
	   Another 25 runs will give New Zealand 1-0 lead in the
three-match series. The first test was abandoned without a ball
bowled at Carisbrook, Dunedin.
	   While Cairns, 52, survived a few anxious moments against leg
spinner Anil Kumble, McMillan, calmly held the innings together
with a chanceless 63.
	   The pair came together four minutes into the day when medium
paceman Javagal Srinath trapped Paul Wiseman plumb in front to
reduce New Zealand to 74 for five.
	   McMillan hit five boundaries in his 110-ball innings while
Cairns was more forceful in hitting a six and seven boundaries off
86 balls.
	   Cairns' six off teenage off spinner Harbhajan Singh resulted in
a lost ball and play was held up for 10 minutes.
	   The stand, already worth 114, improved on the New Zealand record
for the sixth wicket between John Guy and Tony MacGibbon against
Pakistan in Hyderabad in the 1955-56 series.
 &UR; (ik-tjh)
</TEXT>
