w2134 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SierraLeone-Mutilated     12-29 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone-Mutilated Hope,0766 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World War I-era surgery gives hope to Sierra Leone's war amputees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos ABI101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By GLENN McKENZIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAKKA TOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Before rebel attackers shattered
Yanor Kanu's life by hacking off both of her hands with a dull
machete blade, her greatest pleasure was holding her grandchildren
in her arms.
	   Now she's learning to use crab-like pincers constructed by
surgeons so she can squeeze together the surgically separated bones
on each forearm to grip a spoon, a broom or a pen _ and even grasp
a small child's hand.
	   ``I can never be whole again, but at least I can do small jobs
and play with my little ones,'' Kanu said, gazing at her 5-year-old
granddaughter playing beside her.
	   In Sierra Leone, a country where thousands of defenseless
villagers have been mutilated in a brutal campaign by rebels
seeking revenge for their ouster from power earlier this year, Red
Cross doctors have resurrected an almost forgotten World War I-era
surgical operation to rehabilitate and give hope to the country's
growing ranks of amputees.
	   The operation, named the Krukenberg method after a German doctor
who pioneered the procedure, involves separating the two bones of
the forearm and covering each piece with skin grafted from other
parts of the body, often the leg.
	   Although the resulting pincers are more useful than old
fashioned hooks or even high-tech artificial hands, the relatively
simple operation is rarely performed anymore in the West because
the pincers are regarded as unsightly. And unless people have lost
both of their hands, they are often willing to make do with one
hand and a prosthetic limb.
	   However, for most people in this desperately poor West African
nation, where rebel fighters have amputated the arms and legs of
countless villagers, function comes before fashion.
	   Without the Krukenberg pincers, even something as simple as
going to the bathroom cannot be done alone by double amputees.
	   Kanu, who is in her 50s and has three children and five
grandchildren, says if not for the Swiss, British and German
doctors who performed her operation at Freetown's Netlands Hospital
earlier this year, she would not want to continue living.
	   She did not expect to live through her ordeal back in April when
rebels unexpectedly attacked her village of Batkanu in northern
Sierra Leone. Ten elderly people and five children were killed in
the attack, she said. Nine others, including herself, had their
hands amputated by the rebels. Only those swift enough to run away
escaped.
	   ``They placed my arms on a mortar and told me that I should tell
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah to give me new hands,'' Kanu grimly
recounted. ``Then they began chopping. The knives were not sharp,
and it took so long. I thought I would die from the pain. But
somehow I made it, and someone took me to a hospital.''
	   Staying with her granddaughter at a makeshift rehabilitation
center set up by the Red Cross at an abandoned tourist resort on
the tropical beachfront of Lakka Town, outside the capital, she is
learning how to flex previously unused muscles to wash dishes,
write and sweep the floor. Rehabilitation takes several months.
	   She plans to go back to her village of Batkanu when the fighting
dies down. Recent rebel advances, however, threaten the capital,
and pro-government forces have been put on the defensive.
	   Since July, dozens of Krukenberg operations have been performed
by foreign Red Cross doctors who, in the beginning, had little to
guide them but old textbooks.
	   Although Krukenbergs are also performed in India and Sri Lanka,
nowhere is the need as great as in Sierra Leone.
	   Margaret Staff, an Australian nurse working at Netlands
Hospital, said hundreds or thousands of operations could be needed
around the country. The Red Cross is planning to teach the method
to Sierra Leonean doctors.
	   ``Without this operation, there is no possibility of
rehabilitation for many of these patients,'' Staff said.
	   And while at first those who have been given Krukenberg pincers
draw curious stares from strangers, people quickly grow accustomed
to them, Staff said.
	   Children and teen-agers who have had the operation are the
quickest to adapt. Two months after having operations on both his
arms, Musa Mansary, 18, can write, draw and do other intricate
tasks. He plans to learn how to use a computer and would like to
work for the Red Cross one day.
	   ``The Red Cross helped me, and so now I'd like to help other
people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sierra Leone-Mutilated Hope; CT:i; 
