<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Journalist Released,0251 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government releases AFP correspondent after 20 months in detention
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs, ADDS CJP comment, new to some points &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ The government has released an Eritrean
journalist working for Agence France-Presse after 20 months in
detention without charge, an official said Tuesday.
	   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Ruth
Simon had been granted amnesty, but gave no further details.
	   Simon, 36, was at her home in Asmara, the capital of this Horn
of Africa nation. She and family members declined to comment.
	   Simon was arrested April 25, 1997, after reporting that
President Isaias Afwerki had told a meeting of the ruling party
that Eritrean rebels were fighting alongside Sudanese rebels in
neighboring Sudan.
	   Afwerki denied making the statement, and officials said the
meeting had been closed to the press.
	   The National Democratic Alliance, an umbrella organization of
groups opposed to Sudan's Islamic government, is based in Eritrea.
	   Simon was never charged with any crime.
	   In November, the correspondent for the French news service was
awarded in absentia the International Press Freedom Award by the
New York-based Committee to Protect Journalists.
	   CPJ's Africa coordinator, Kakuna Kerina, said in a statement
that her organization was seeking assurance from Eritrea that Ruth
had been released unconditionally, and said Ruth should be
compensated for her time behind bars.
</TEXT>
