<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-Austrians,0445 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Maier fills Austria's gap in downhill
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BORMIO, Italy (AP) _ Following three failures, Austria needed a
downhill victory to put its seal on the men's World Cup.
	   Hermann ``The Herminator'' Maier and his Austrian teammates came
through on Tuesday with an unprecedented 1-6 finish in the fourth
speed race of the season.
	   The Austrian triumph at Bormio, down the icy and twisty Stelvio
course which will host the World Cup finals in 2000, followed an
all-time 1-9 record finish by the Austrian skiers _ with Maier
again leading the pack _ in last week's Super-G at Innsbruck.
	   Austria's domination in seven of the 13 World Cup races held so
far _ three Super-Gs, two giant slaloms, one downhill and one
slalom _ left the opponents battered and hopeless.
	   ``They look unbeatable,'' said Italy's Peter Runggaldier, one of
the only three non-Austrians to finish in the top 11 at Bormio.
	   ``They are a strong team, with Maier as charismatic leader,'' he
added.
	   Maier earned the No.1 spot on the ``Power Team'' last season by
clinching 10 World Cup wins, the overall title and two Olympic
golds at Nagano.
	   He has added four World Cup wins this season in three different
disciplines.
	   On Tuesday the 26-year-old ski superstar from Flachau showed no
fear as he charged down the 3,070-meter-long (3,359-yard-long)
course beating runnerup Fritz Stobl by 0.70 seconds and third-place
Stephan Eberharter by 1.28.
	   It was Maier's first downhill victory since his dramatic and
spectacular spill at the Nagano Olympics in February. Quickly
recovered from the downhill crash Maier then went on to win the
Super-G and giant slalom titles.
	   ``I really wanted a downhill victory after Nagano .. I was brave
to win on a tough, difficult course,'' Maier said.
	   The Austrian ace said he was now looking forward to the
prestigious downhill race of Wengen, in January, for a double at
the Swiss track after his consecutive wins in Bormio.
	   Before Wengen Maier could improve his record of wins and his
World Cup overall lead in three giant slaloms _ the first at
Kranjska Gora on Jan. 6 - and a Super-G at Schladming.
	   Tuesday's victory gave Maier a commanding lead of 640 points
overall, 103 ahead of Norway's Lasse Kjus.
	   Kjus, who upset the Austrians in the first two downhills of the
season and finished second to Italy's Kristian Ghedina in the
third, did not start in Bormio because of a bronchitis and did not
pocket any point.
	   There were seven Austrians among the top ten in the Cup overall
standings and six among the top nine in the downhill lists.
</TEXT>
