<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher against yen, Tokyo stocks open lower
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen early
Wednesday in light, end-of-year trading. Share prices fell at the
open of the year's last session.
	   The dollar bought 115.70 yen in early trading, up 0.34 yen from
late Tuesday and also above its late New York level of 115.53 yen
overnight.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 2.84 points,
or 0.02 percent, to 13,844.06 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Tuesday, the average closed up 137.84 points, or 1.01
percent.
	   The Tokyo Stock Exchange closes out the year Wednesday with a
half-day session. It will reopen on Jan. 4, 1999.
	   In currency dealings, the dollar remained in a narrow range amid
the year-end lull. Many players were also holding back to await the
Jan. 1 launch of Europe's single currency, the euro.
	   On the stock market, share prices were under pressure as a drop
in bond prices rekindled fears about the recent turmoil in credit
markets.
	   But trades remained extremely sparse as most investors were
already away for the New Year's holidays.
	   ``Bond futures are not showing favorable moves, and that is
creating poor sentiment in the stock market,'' said Kenji Karikomi,
general manager of the equity department at Daiwa Securities.
	   Still, traders expected the market to remain relatively
supported Wednesday due to the overnight rise in New York stocks,
where the Dow Jones industrial average closed at 9,320.98 points,
up 94.23.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 2.54 points, or 0.23 percent, to 1,086.29.
The TOPIX closed up 8.94 points, or 0.83 percent, the day before.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond rose to 1.960 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.885 percent,
driving its price down to 98.72 yen from 99.31 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj)
</TEXT>
