<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Warne brought back to Australian team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Warne quotes in 7th graf &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY HARPER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Star spinner Shane Warne has been
restored to Australia's cricket team for the first time since
shoulder surgery in April following England's fourth test victory
in Melbourne.
	   Warne, who took a wicket with his first ball in Ashes play and
has dominated England ever since, will join fellow leg-spinner
Stuart MacGill and utility Colin Miller in the attack for the fifth
test, starting at the SCG on Saturday.
	   Australia, which has already retained the Ashes, leads the
series 2-1 with one to play following England's stirring 12-run win
in the fourth test which ended Tuesday.
	   Warne, who has more wickets than any other spin bowler in
history, replaces Matthew Nicholson for the SCG match. Nicholson
made his debut in the fourth test.
	   It is the only change to the 12-man squad.
	   Warne has been below his best since returning from his
nine-month break but said he was confident of making an impact.
	   ``There's no drama with my shoulder any more,'' Warne said.
	   He added that if captain Mark Taylor wanted him ``to bowl as
many overs as possible, I can.''
	   Warne has played three Sheffield Shield matches this season and
in his previous game took 1-118 from 30 overs against Queensland.
	   Meanwhile, Australia's media latched onto Taylor's appraisal
that his team ``got lazy'' in its run chase Tuesday and probed a
sore point that the team has a bad record in run chases.
	   `Not Again _ Lazy Australia fall victim to Test jinx' summed it
up in the Sydney Telegraph. The Sydney Morning Herald added `Poms
stun lazy, frail Australians' in its main report but also noted
England's remarkable comeback with `How's that for a miracle?
England win a cricket Test.'
	   Herald cricket writer Malcolm Knox wrote, ``They were inept,
outclassed, pathetic, gutless and, to top it off, unlucky _ but if
the English team believed what was said about them, their captain
Alec Stewart said, `we'd be walking around with Kleenexes all the
time.'''
	   Australia, the world's leading test team, has nonetheless shown
a striking inability to reach low targets. It was the fourth time
in six years that Australia has failed to make less than 200 in the
second innings to win a match.
	   Australia's media was united in believing England's win had
brought new life to Ashes contests.
	   ``Australia lost a Test match but Ashes cricket gained a future
after England pulled off a stunning win to reacquaint Australia
with its chronic cricketing disease, Small Target Syndrome,'' wrote
the Telegraph's Robert Craddock.
	   Australian squad for fifth test: Mark Taylor (captain), Michael
Slater, Justin Langer, Mark Waugh, Steve Waugh, Darren Lehmann, Ian
Healy, Damien Fleming, Stuart MacGill, Colin Miller, Shane Warne,
Glenn McGrath.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
