<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Legwear, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. subsidiary of Mexican legwear concern sold to Italian company
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SANTIAGO PEREZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Hosiery manufacturer Kayser-Roth Corp., a
unit of Mexican legwear concern Synkro SA, said Tuesday that it
reached a final agreement to sell the U.S. company to Italy-based
Golden Lady, S.P.A.
	   Synkro's chairman Luis Gutierrez had announced in late October
that Synkro's board agreed to sell Legwear Holdings, the holding
company for Kayser-Roth, to North Carolina-based Americal Corp. for
dlrs 62 million.
	   But Jerry Perlmutter, vice-president and general counsel of
Kayser-Roth, told Dow Jones Newswires that the sale to Golden Lady
is expected to be completed Jan. 31, 1999. Financial terms of the
transaction weren't disclosed.
	   Perlmutter said the sale was conducted by Synkro executives in
Mexico City. Synkro officials couldn't be reached for comment.
	   Mexico's state-run Bank Savings Protection Fund, also known as
Fobaproa, assumed rights from local banks which had converted
Synkro's debt into stakes in the hosiery concern.
	   Gutierrez said in late October that he didn't know how many
banks had renegotiated their interests in Synkro with Fobaproa. He
declined to say which banks have stakes in Synkro, but said 90
percent of the company's shares are held by Mexican banks.
	   Fobaproa assumed about dlrs 60 billion in non-performing loans
from local banks after the crisis triggered by the December 1994
peso devaluation forced hundred of thousands of debtors to default
on their loans.
	   When Synkro announced Kayser-Roth's sale to North Carolina-based
Americal, Gutierrez said the company decided not to divest its
Mexican hosiery units Cannon and Canofil.
	   Kayser-Roth's Perlmutter added that Americal emerged earlier
this year as leader of the bidding process and won exclusive rights
to conduct a due diligence process, but both parts failed to reach
an agreement.
	   A source close to the Americal transaction, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said Americal never received an official
response stating why Kayser-Roth was sold to Golden Lady.
	   Americal offered dlrs 62 million for Kayser-Roth, but approached
New York investment bank Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which
coordinated the transaction, and said the company was overpriced,
the source said.
	   Soon afterwards Kayser-Roth was sold to the Italian concern for
an undisclosed amount, the source added.
	   Kayser-Roth said in a news release Tuesday that Golden Lady, a
privately owned company, is the largest manufacturer, marketer and
distributor of sheer hosiery in Europe with revenues of about dlrs
400 million a year. The Mantova-based concern has 3,000 employees
in six manufacturing facilities, four distribution centers and 600
retail boutiques throughout Europe.
	   Kayser-Roth has about 2,500 workers and average annual sales of
dlrs 290 million.
	   Nerino Grassi, president of Golden Lady, said in the news
release that taking advantage of the synergies between Golden Lady
and Kayser-Roth ``will result in a major force in the world legwear
market.''
</TEXT>
