<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-Israel-Statehood Scramble,0667 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinian statehood takes center stage in Israeli elections
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURA KING &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's national election is months away, but
already the biggest campaign issue is an event that hasn't
happened, in a place yet to be determined, under circumstances no
candidate is eager to talk about in stump speeches.
	   That issue is Palestinian statehood.
	   With direct voting for Israel's next prime minister set for May
17, the election countdown nearly coincides with the independence
timetable that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has used for months
now to rattle Israel's nerves and bolster his own people's sagging
spirits.
	   Arafat has said repeatedly that Palestinians have the right to
declare statehood on May 4 _ the date under which the interim Oslo
accords expire, by Palestinian interpretation _ whether or not
terms of the new state have been negotiated with Israel.
	   The hard-line government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
has threatened a drastic response to any unilateral Palestinian
declaration of independence, such as annexing large chunks of the
new state's West Bank heartland.
	   Coupled with an impasse in the peace process, the election
campaign represents a high-stakes showdown over statehood _ not
only between Israel and the Palestinians, but among the various
candidates for prime minister.
	   At least five politicians have already declared their
candidacies, including several one-time allies who are now turning
on one another. More are waiting in the wings.
	   Netanyahu has already tried to pre-empt the statehood issue,
boasting that Palestinians wouldn't dare declare independence two
weeks before the election for fear of propelling him _ their
nemesis _ back into office.
	   But the Palestinians could just as easily warn that if he did
win the election, they would respond with a swift statehood
declaration.
	   Arafat and his inner circle have already shown they are capable
of adjusting the tenor of statehood comments to fit their agenda of
the moment.
	   In September, Arafat's aides promised he would use a speech at
the U.N. General Assembly to make an unambiguous call for
Palestinian statehood. But at U.S. urging, he softened his comments
considerably, helping pave the way for the Wye River summit the
next month with Netanyahu.
	   Similar mixed signals have emerged in recent days. On Monday,
Palestinian negotiator Hassan Asfour suggested Arafat might hold
off on a statehood declaration because it could drive jittery
Israeli voters into the Netanyahu camp.
	   On Tuesday, though, Palestinian parliament speaker Ahmed Qureia,
known as Abu Ala, said May 4 statehood plans were as alive as ever.
	   ``Everything is as scheduled,'' he told The Associated Press.
``It's a historical and serious and very important date, and our
decision hasn't changed.''
	   Such contradictory comments reflect genuine debate among
Palestinians as to whether a speedy declaration would serve their
interests or wreck chances for negotiating a better deal later.
	   On the Israeli side, Netanyahu's opponents have said as little
as possible about statehood prospects. That's especially true of
challenger Ehud Barak, whose dovish Labor Party already stands
accused by Netanyahu of colluding with Arafat.
	   But Israeli public opinion is changing. U.S. President Bill
Clinton's visit earlier this month was seen not only by
Palestinians but by many Israelis as setting a seal of approval on
Palestinian statehood aspirations. Even key Israeli conservatives
are now saying it's bound to happen.
	   Each side has a strong interest in reaching accommodation. A
declaration of statehood with so many explosive issues unresolved _
its borders, Jewish settlements, the status of Jerusalem, which
both sides claim as their capital _ could prove highly dangerous
for both.
	   ___
	   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Laura King is based in Jerusalem and covers
Palestinian affairs. 	   
</TEXT>
