<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Nomura </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nomura Securities to cut 650 overseas jobs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Nomura Securities Co., Japan's biggest brokerage,
will cut 650 overseas jobs next year as part of a major
restructuring campaign, a company official said Wednesday.
	   Facing massive losses in its overseas operations, the company
will shed nearly 20 percent of its work force in Europe and the
Americas and close some overseas offices, Nomura representative
Kimizo Hayakawa said.
	   At the same time, the company will hire 50 new employees in Asia
outside Japan to strengthen securities operations in Taiwan and the
Philippines, he said.
	   As of the end of September, Nomura employed 4,600 people outside
Japan, including 1,400 in North and South America and 2,300 in
Europe.
	   Through the planned job cuts, to be carried out by March 1999,
the company hopes to reduce fixed overseas costs by 30 billion yen
(dlrs 259 million), targeting overseas businesses that sustained
big losses in the first half of fiscal 1998.
	   Nomura announced in October that it would cut 2,000 jobs from
its 13,000-strong domestic work force by 2001 and close about 20
percent of its Japanese retail outlets to cope with the nation's
economic recession.
	   At that time, the company reported 207.2 billion yen (dlrs 1.76
billion) in losses, mostly from foreign operations, for the first
half of fiscal 1998.
 &UR; (gp)	   
</TEXT>
