<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Mercosur Cup ,0405 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palmeiras Wins Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By Jamie McGeever &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) _ Palmeiras beat Cruzeiro 1-0 Tuesday
night in the final match of the inaugural Mercosur Cup, lifting the
trophy and the dlrs 4.7 million cash prize offered by the South
American Soccer Confederation.
	   Cruzeiro won the opening match in Belo Horizonte 2-1, but
Palmeiras turned the tables in the second game with a 3-1 victory
in Sao Paulo last Sunday, before clinching victory in the
three-match series.
	   The win brings Palmeiras its second major title of the year,
after a Brazilian Cup win - also against Cruzeiro - and brings down
the curtain on a disappointing 1998 for Cruzeiro, which lost all
three national finals it disputed.
	   The winning goal came 15 minutes into the second half, and
perhaps fittingly, from Paraguayan international right-back Arce,
the only non-Brazilian Mercosur-born player on the field.
	   Brazilian internationalist Junior Baiano blasted a 30-yard free
kick through Cruzeiro's defensive wall, which goalkeeper Dida did
well to block. The rebound fell kindly to the oncoming Arce, who
swept the ball home from eight yards to the delight of the partisan
home crowd.
	   The first half opened brightly, with fast, incisive, and
committed football from both sides, particularly Palmeiras. Paulo
Nunes, Zinho, and Alex looked in the mood.
	   Just as quickly, however, the game became tense and littered
with fouls. Referee Luciano Almeida began to lose respect from the
22 players on the pitch, with a series of inconsistent and erratic
decisions which favored neither team. Most glaring of all was his
failure to produce the red card for Palmeiras midfielder Thiago for
a crude tackle from behind on Valdo, only minutes after he was
booked for a rash challenge on Gilberto.
	   The highlight of the half was a fine save by Palmeiras
goalkeeper Velloso from a curling Valdo free kick.
	   Cruzeiro's urgency at the start of the second 45 minutes stung a
strangely pedestrian Palmeiras into action, with a Junior Baiano
free kick almost smashing the crossbar in two.
	   After Palmeiras broke the deadlock, play opened up, as Cruzeiro
pushed forward in search of the equalizer, and the effects of an
ardous season began to tell. Simmering tempers came to the boil,
and Cruzeiro's Marcelo Ramos was sent off for his second yellow
card offence ten minutes from the end.
</TEXT>
