<HEADER>
w2249 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-PierDisaster     12-29 0230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Pier Disaster </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai pier owner, employee avoid prison over deadly accident
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The owner and an employee of a company
that ran a Bangkok pier which capsized in 1995 killing 29 people
have received suspended jail terms, local papers reported
Wednesday.
	   A criminal court said that Suphaphan Phichaironarongsongkhram,
joint owner of the Suphathra Co., which owned the pier, and an
employee, Karuna Thepklang, had dismantled a gate which was used to
control the number of people streaming onto the pier.
	   They were given one year jail terms, which were suspended. The
company was fined 20,000 baht (dlrs 555), the Nation newspaper
reported.
	   In handing out the sentences, the court said that the two women,
by paying compensation to the families of the 29 killed, had
performed an act of atonement.
	   Three Harbor Department officials responsible for overseeing
piers on the Chao Phraya River in Bangkok, were acquitted of
negligence charges, The Nation said.
	   The floating pier, used by commuters to catch express boats on
the Chao Phraya, the main waterway in Bangkok, capsized on June 14,
1995 after too many people crammed toward its front.
	   The pier's capacity was 60 people. In addition to the 29 who
drowned, more than 100 were injured, including one who was
paralyzed. Many of the victims were school children. 	   
</TEXT>
