<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Soldiers Killed </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Villagers kill seven soldiers in northwest Indonesia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A mob of 200 villagers, some armed
with machetes, tortured and killed seven Indonesian soldiers after
stopping their car in a northwestern province, local media reported
Wednesday.
	   The Tuesday incident in Aceh province was likely to raise
tensions in a region where the Indonesian military recently ended a
decade-long campaign against separatist rebels. Officials suspect
guerrillas were behind the attack.
	   Accused of widespread atrocities in Aceh, the military
apologized and withdrew some troops in a conciliatory gesture after
the resignation in May of former President Suharto. But resentment
toward the armed forces remains deep.
	   Some soldiers managed to escape their attackers in the village
of Lhok Nibung and reported to their superiors, the official Antara
news agency quoted army spokesman Maj. Gen. Syamsul Ma'arif as
saying.
	   Some 200 troops were dispatched to search for the killers, but
there were no reported arrests. The bodies of those slain, who had
been going on leave to the nearby city of Medan, were not found.
	   Aceh, about 1,750 kilometers (1,100 miles) northwest of Jakarta,
is a staunchly Muslim province where rebels have been fighting for
an Islamic state for decades.
	   The military has acknowledged that 760 people died in fighting
since the late 1980s, although human rights groups put the death
toll higher. Mass graves have been uncovered and some widows have
alleged they were raped by soldiers.
	   Col. Johny Wahab, a military commander in Aceh, said the attack
on Tuesday indicated that appeals to the local community to ensure
security in the region had been in vain.
	   ``Good intentions have been responded to inhumanly with the
abduction and torture of servicemen who were about to go on
leave,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
