r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Corruption     12-29 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government reveals corruption losses tied to Suharto associates
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: One name correct for Hartarto &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Corrupt business practices, largely by
the family and associates of former President Suharto, cost the
state as much as dlrs 580 million over the last five years, the
Indonesian government has concluded.
	   Authorities have been investigating evidence of corruption
during the long rule of Suharto, who was ousted in May after riots
by Indonesia's poor and student protests against his 32-year rule.
	   The new report on corruption, released Tuesday, could bolster an
investigation of the origin of Suharto's wealth even though critics
have dismissed the probe as cosmetic. Suharto has denied any
wrongdoing.
	   The government has also terminated dozens of investment projects
tainted by collusion and nepotism, said Hartarto, the chief Cabinet
minister for development and administrative reform.
	   Hartarto said the state expected to recover dlrs 43 million of
the money lost because of corruption in contracts and government
agencies between 1993 and September 1998.
	   Suharto's credibility was eroded in part by allegations of
official graft at a time when Indonesia's economy was buckling
under the worst financial crisis in decades. Millions of people
have lost their jobs and inflation has soared.
	   President B.J. Habibie ordered an investigation of his
predecessor and onetime mentor after coming under pressure from
student protesters who want 77-year-old Suharto to be put on trial.
	   Government opponents question whether Habibie, who owes his
position to Suharto and whose family also owns dozens of
businesses, is conducting a serious probe.
	   On Tuesday, prosecutors questioned one of Suharto's three sons,
businessman Bambang Trihatmodjo, about his role as head of one of
seven charitable foundations once owned by the former president.
	   The foundations were allegedly used in part to collect money
that Suharto's family used for its own benefit. After questioning,
Bambang said the foundation provided funds ``for social needs.'' 	   
</TEXT>
