<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-India-Pitches </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pitches and test schedules blamed for poor record
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Batsmen-friendly pitches at home
and infrequent test schedules may be responsible for India's
threadbare track record outside the subcontinent, observers said
Wednesday.
	   In the second cricket test against New Zealand this week, India
found itself in familiar territory, losing a one-time lead in the
match to be beaten by an inexperienced Kiwi side.
	   While it has won 18 of its last 31 tests at home, India hasn't
won a test overseas since beating Sri Lanka in July, 1993, in
Colombo 18 matches ago.
	   ``The real problem is the batsmen-friendly wickets,'' said Ayaz
Memon, a senior cricket writer and editor of Bombay based Mid-day
newspaper.
	   ``We get a completely false idea of our strength and when you
encounter pitches that do a little bit we are badly exposed,'' he
said.
	   Memon said the at-home wins came easily in conditions good for
spin bowling. This was the case when India thrashed Australia 2-1
early this year.
	   He said Indian cricketers weren't mentally prepared for overseas
tests and suffer from short attention spans. This was reflected in
the seven dropped catches that let New Zealand slip away.
	   India's last win outside the subcontinent was a 2-0 success over
England in 1986. The team then lost a one-off test to Zimbabwe in
Harare in October.
	   The Indians played just four tests before the current series
compared to the 40 one-day internationals when it won five
championship finals.
	   ``We play so many one-day games these days, it is very difficult
to suddenly change in test matches,'' skipper Mohammed Azharuddin
said.
	   ``We should play both in equal proportions.
	   ``It has been said in the past but nothing has was done.
	   ``People are more concerned about making money than doing what
is right by the game and for the improvement of it,'' he said.
	   India has lost recent series in the West Indies, South Africa
and Zimbabwe.
	   Azharuddin said it was sad, but that he hoped the teams
prospects would improve.
	   ``We don't go overseas with the intention of losing,'' he said.
	   ``From country to country we encounter different conditions and
by the time you get a feel for it, the series is lost,'' he said.
	   Azharuddin said a test championship was a good idea but should
be thoroughly examined before the final decision is made.
	    &UR; (ik-rs)
</TEXT>
