u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Economy     12-29 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government: Chinese economy grew by 7.8 percent in 1998
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Boosted by massive state spending on public
works, China's economy grew by 7.8 percent this year but missed its
official target, according to figures released Wednesday.
	   Growth was down sharply from 1997, when the economy expanded by
8.8 percent. Chinese leaders had hoped for at least 8 percent this
year to create jobs for millions of workers laid off in a sweeping
overhaul of state companies.
	   China has escaped the full impact of the 18-month-old Asian
financial crisis, but faces serious problems of its own in trying
to turn around money-losing state industries and clean up its
state-owned banking system.
	   The Chinese economy has slowed considerably since the early
1990s, when it was growing by double digits. But it still is doing
better than its neighbors, some of which are recording negative
growth. Indonesia says its economy could shrink by up to 15 percent
this year.
	   In a positive sign, the Chinese growth rate began to rise in
recent months, pumped up by the start of a dlrs 1.4 trillion,
three-year stimulus plan of spending on new highways and other
projects, according to the State Statistical Bureau.
	   Exports were almost unchanged from 1997 at dlrs 182 billion,
while imports fell 3.8 percent to dlrs 137 billion. That left China
with a trade surplus of dlrs 45 billion, up dlrs 4.7 billion from
the previous year.
	   Ye Zhen, a spokesman for the Statistical Bureau, declined at a
press conference to give a growth forecast for 1999. He said it
would be released by the National People's Congress early next
year.
	   The economy expanded by only 7 percent in the first half of
1998. That prompted Chinese leaders to implement the stimulus plan
and increase lending by state banks, loosening austerity measures
that date to the early 1990s.
	   Those austerity measures, imposed to fight inflation that at the
time was raging at more than 20 percent a year, have been so
effective at cooling the Chinese economy that consumer prices are
actually falling.
	   Spurred by the increased spending, the economy grew by 9 percent
in the fourth quarter of the year, according to an estimate by the
Statistical Bureau.
	   Real utilized foreign investment for the year fell 16 percent to
dlrs 54 billion, according to the government figures.
	   Ye blamed the decline on the Asian financial crisis, which has
hurt Japan, South Korea and other key investors.
	   Foreign companies also have become more reluctant to invest in
China because of dissatisfaction with low profits. 	   
</TEXT>
